! Passengers\n|-\n| 1990||1,619,880||||2000||3,068,890||||2010||3,181,616\n|-\n| 1991||1,589,123||||2001||2,880,186||||2011||3,072,572\n|-\n| 1992||1,855,954||||2002||2,745,788||||2012||3,005,664\n|-\n| 1993||2,329,953||||2003||2,789,499||||2013||2,926,858\n|-\n| 1994||2,687,482||||2004||3,059,667||||2014||2,986,652\n|-\n| 1995||2,988,575||||2005||3,197,440||||2015||3,133,342\n|-\n| 1996||3,258,762||||2006||3,224,423||||2016||3,234,095\n|-\n| 1997||3,043,238||||2007||3,471,901||||2017||3,550,912\n|-\n| 1998||2,949,833||||2008||3,422,110||||2018||3,998,272\n|-\n| 1999||3,041,626||||2009||3,055,081||||2019||'''4,112,784'''\n|}\n\n==Ground transportation==\n[[Spokane Transit Authority|Spokane Transit]] operates two stops at Spokane International Airport, with bus route 60 connecting the airport to Downtown Spokane. Transfer opportunities are available in downtown to the rest of the STA system. The STA also has stops near the terminal for route 63, which serves Airway Heights and the West Plains Transit Center. The airport is served by the [[Washington State Department of Transportation|WSDOT's]] [[Travel Washington]] Gold Line, which provides twice-daily bus service to cities north of Spokane, including Deer Park, Chewelah, Colville, and Kettle Falls.  Northwestern Trailways operates buses to and from Colfax, WA, Pullman, WA, Moscow, ID, and Lewiston, ID.  Wheatland Express offers service to Colfax, WA, Pullman, WA, and  Moscow, ID.  Special Mobility Service carries passengers to Newport, WA.  Queen City Shuttle, which is also known as Kootenay Shuttle, serves Nelson, and other destinations in British Columbia, Canada.\n\nA [[consolidated rental car facility]] is located adjacent to the Ground Transportation Center on the north end of the main terminal.  The consolidated facility opened in November 2008, replacing several satellite operations, and is intended to meet passenger growth at the airport for 20 years after its opening.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2008/nov/12/car-rental-a-short-walk-away/|title=Car rental a short walk away|work=The Spokesman-Review|first=Mike|last=Prager|accessdate=2016-01-14|date=2008-11-12}}</ref>\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n* On January 21, 1981, a [[Beechcraft Model 99]]A, [[Cascade Airways]] Flight 201, crashed into a hill 4.5 miles from the runway. The accident was caused by an incorrect distance measuring equipment frequency and premature descent to minimum descent altitude. Of the nine people on board, seven were killed (including both pilots), and the other two passengers were seriously injured. The airline ceased operations about five years later.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.airdisaster.com/reports/ntsb/AAR81-11.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-07-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201134808/http://www.airdisaster.com/reports/ntsb/AAR81-11.pdf |archivedate=December 1, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bruceair.com/aviation_writing/aviation_samples/Flight201.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-07-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708100829/http://www.bruceair.com/aviation_writing/aviation_samples/Flight201.pdf |archivedate=July 8, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*On March 18, 1994, [[Douglas DC-3|Douglas]] DC-3C N3433Y of Salair crashed shortly after take-off on a cargo flight to [[Portland International Airport]]. The starboard engine failed shortly after take-off. The engine that failed had previously been in long-term storage and had been overhauled the previous year and fitted to the aircraft on February 21, replacing an engine that developed a misfire and loss of power. It had accumulated 15 hrs flight time at the time of the accident. The aircraft was destroyed in the subsequent fire and both crew members were killed.<ref name=ASN180394>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19940318-0 |title=N3433Y Accident description|publisher=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=June 25, 2010}}</ref><ref name=NTSBSEA94FA085>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntsb.gov/ntsb/brief2.asp?ev_id=20001206X00995&ntsbno=SEA94FA085&akey=1 |title=SEA94FA085 |publisher=National Transportation Safety Board |accessdate=June 28, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|World War II}}\n* [[Washington World War II Army Airfields]]\n* [[Western Air Defense Force]] (Air Defense Command)\n* [[9th Space Division|9th Air Division]]\n\n==References==\n{{Air Force Historical Research Agency}}\n{{reflist}}\n*[http://www.dodfire.com/history/Academy.htm Air Force & DOD Fire Academy History]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Spokane International Airport}}\n* [http://www.spokaneairports.net/ Spokane International Airport], official site\n* [http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/aviation/AllStateAirports/Spokane_SpokaneIntl.htm Spokane International Airport] at [[WSDOT]] Aviation\n* {{FAA-diagram|00403}}\n* {{FAA-procedures|GEG}}\n{{US-airport|GEG}}\n\n{{Airports in Washington}}\n{{Aerospace Defense Command}}\n{{USAAF 2d Air Force World War II}}\n{{Transportation in the Spokane, WA\u2013Coeur d'Alene, ID region}}\n\n[[Category:Airports established in 1940]]\n[[Category:Airfields of the United States Army Air Corps]]\n[[Category:Airfields of the United States Army Air Forces in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Airports in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Transportation buildings and structures in Spokane County, Washington]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Spokane, Washington]]\n[[Category:1940 establishments in Washington (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|GEG|the Geg Albanian dialect|Gheg Albanian}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name         = Spokane International Airport\n| nativename   = Geiger Army Airfield\n| image        = SpokaneInternationalAirport-logo.svg\n| image-width  = 225\n| image2       = Aerial GEG August 2010.JPG\n| image2-width = 280\n| caption      = \n| caption2     = Spokane International Airport in 2010, viewed from the south\n| IATA         = GEG\n| ICAO         = KGEG\n| FAA          = GEG\n| type         = Public\n| owner        = [[Spokane County, Washington|Spokane County]] & [[Spokane, Washington|City of Spokane]]\n| operator     = Spokane Airport Board\n| city-served  = [[Inland Northwest (United States)|Inland Northwest]] (primarily [[Spokane\u2013Coeur d'Alene combined statistical area|Spokane\u2013Coeur d'Alene area]])\n| location     = [[Spokane, Washington|Spokane]], [[Washington (state)|Washington, USA]]\n| hub          =\n*[[Empire Airlines]]\n| elevation-f  = 2385\n| elevation-m  = 727\n| coordinates  = {{Coord|47|37|12|N|117|32|02|W|type:airport}}\n| website      = [http://www.spokaneairports.net/ SpokaneAirports.net]\n| pushpin_map            = USA Washington#USA\n| pushpin_relief         = yes\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location of airport in Washington / United States\n| pushpin_label          = '''GEG'''\n| pushpin_label_position = bottom\n| r1-number    = 3/21\n| r1-length-f  = 11,002\n| r1-length-m  = 3,353\n| r1-surface   = Asphalt/Concrete\n| r2-number    = 8/26\n| r2-length-f  = 8,199\n| r2-length-m  = 2,499\n| r2-surface   = Asphalt\n| stat1-header = Aircraft operations (2019)\n| stat1-data   = 69,097\n| stat2-header = Based aircraft (2018)\n| stat2-data   = 60\n| stat3-header = Total Passengers Served (12 months ending December 2019)\n| stat3-data   = 4,112,784\n| stat4-header = Cargo handled (12 months ending December 2019)\n| stat4-data   = 137,961,598 lbs.\n| footnotes    = Source: [[Federal Aviation Administration]];<ref name=\"FAA\">{{FAA-airport|ID=GEG|use=PU|own=PU|site=27013.1*A}}, effective May 25, 2017.</ref> Spokane International Airport<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.spokaneairports.net/core/files/business/uploads/files/Passenger%20Stats/12_15to.pdf|title=Spokane Intl Airport \u2013 Home|publisher=}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Spokane International Airport''' {{airport codes|GEG|KGEG|GEG}} is a commercial airport approximately {{convert|5|mi|0}} west of [[Downtown Spokane|downtown]] [[Spokane, Washington|Spokane]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]]. It is the primary airport serving the [[Inland Northwest (United States)|Inland Northwest]], which consists of 30 counties and includes areas such as Spokane and the [[Tri-Cities, Washington|Tri-Cities]], both in [[Eastern Washington|Eastern]] Washington, and [[Coeur d'Alene, Idaho|Coeur d'Alene]] in [[Idaho Panhandle|North]] [[Idaho]]. The airport's code, GEG, is derived from its airfield's namesake, Major [[Harold Geiger]].\n\nAs of 2015, Spokane International Airport (GEG) ranks as the 70th-busiest airport in the United States in terms of passenger enplanements.<ref>{{cite web|title=Calendar Year 2015 Passenger Boardings at Commercial Service Airports|url=http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/passenger_allcargo_stats/passenger/media/cy15-commercial-service-enplanements.pdf|publisher=Federal Aviation Administration (FAA)|accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref> At 4,112,784 total passengers served in 2019, it is also the second busiest airport in Washington. GEG is served by six airlines with [[Non-stop flight|non-stop]] service to 15 airports in 13 markets.\n\nIt is included in the [[Federal Aviation Administration]] (FAA) [[National Plan of Integrated Airport Systems]] for 2017\u20132021, in which it is [[FAA airport categories|categorized]] as a small-hub primary commercial service facility.<ref name=\"NPIAS Airports\">{{cite web|title=List of NPIAS Airports|url=https://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/npias/reports/media/NPIAS-Report-2017-2021-Appendix-A.pdf|website=FAA.gov|publisher=Federal Aviation Administration|accessdate=29 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\n[[File:Army Air Forces - Postcard - Geiger Field Washington.jpg|thumb|left|World War II Geiger Field Postcard]]\n[[File:Geiger Field Washington.jpg|thumb|left|Geiger Field in 1943]]\nKnown as '''Sunset Field''' before 1941, it was purchased from the county by the [[United States Department of War|War Department]] and renamed '''Geiger Field''' after Major [[Harold Geiger]], an [[United States Army Air Corps|Army aviation]] pioneer who died in a crash in 1927.\n\nDuring [[World War II]], Geiger Field was a major training base by [[Second Air Force]] as a group training airfield for [[B-17 Flying Fortress]] heavy bombardment units, with new aircraft being obtained from [[Boeing]] near [[Seattle]]. It was also used by Air Technical Service Command as an aircraft maintenance and supply depot; Deer Park Airport and [[Felts Field]] were auxiliaries.\n\nIn 1943, General Hap Arnold established the first formal fire protection training course at Geiger Field, Washington. It was used until 1946.\n\nGeiger Field was served by a rail connection to the [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railway]].<ref>Staff, \"Align Rail Route To Air Depot\", ''The Spokesman-Review'', Spokane, Washington, Wednesday 13 May 1942, Volume 59. Number 364, page 6.</ref>\n\nGeiger was closed in late 1945 and turned over to [[War Assets Administration]] (WAA), then transferred to Spokane County and developed into a commercial airport. The airport hosted USAF [[Air Defense Command]] [[interceptor aircraft|interceptor]] units during the [[Cold War]] for air defense of [[Hanford Site|Hanford Nuclear Reservation]] and [[Grand Coulee Dam]]. Built in 1942 as the Spokane Air Depot, [[Fairchild Air Force Base]] is four miles (7&nbsp;km) to the west.\n\nIt became Spokane's municipal airport in 1946, replacing [[Felts Field]], and received its present name in 1960, after the City of Spokane was allotted Spokane Geiger Field by the Surplus Property Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spokaneairports.net/faq.htm|title=Spokane Intl Airport \u2013 Home}}</ref> It was still used by the Air Force into the early 1960s, with the [[84th Combat Sustainment Group#Air Defense Command|84th Fighter Group]] operating [[Convair F-106 Delta Dart|F-106 Delta Dart]] [[Interceptor aircraft|interceptors]].<ref name=gfintcp>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=cDlWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=z-gDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7212%2C1786223 |work=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington) |title=Geiger's fast interceptors protecting area and nation |date=January 6, 1963 |page=6}}</ref> The airport code is still GEG, for Geiger Field.\n\n===Modern era===\n[[File:SpokaneIntAirport32.JPG|thumb|left|Concourse A and B complex originally opened in 1965]]\nThe current Concourse A and B complex opened in 1965 and was designed by Warren C. Heylman and William Trogdon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historicspokane.org/HeritageTours/modern/tour/tour7.html|title=Historic Preservation: Mid-Century Modern Architecture|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOccasional non-stop flights to southern California since the 1970s have been among the first to be suspended during economic downturns.\n\n===Growth and expansion===\n\nA second level was added to Concourse A and Concourse B in 1974.<ref>{{cite news |title=Terminal Roof Bid Accepted|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1314&dat=19770824&id=kTxOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1u0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6873,3728006|newspaper=[[The Spokesman-Review]]|location=Spokane|date=August 25, 1977|accessdate=January 22, 2015|page=7}}</ref>\n\nThe airport has a Master Plan,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spokaneairports.net/MasterPlan.htm|title=Spokane Intl Airport \u2013 Home}}</ref> which includes a third runway and gates added to Concourse C.\n\nA new [[control tower]] has been built south of the airport, replacing the one near Concourse C. The new control tower is the tallest one in the State.  The [[Airport terminal|Terminal]], [[Rotunda (architecture)|Rotunda]], and Concourse C Enhancement Project (TRACE) was recently completed, designed by Bernardo/Wills Architects, P.C.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spokaneairports.net/4-26-06.htm|title=Spokane Intl Airport \u2013 Home}}</ref> The project, which concluded in November 2006, added retail space and expanded security checkpoints in the airport's three concourses, and gave the Rotunda an aesthetic renovation. In 2010, 2000 feet was added to Runway 3\u201321, and parallel taxiways 'A' and 'G' enabling heavier aircraft departures in summer months.\n\nBy 2023, the airport plans to add new gates, centralized security and expanded baggage claim space as it looks to add more direct flights, including to the east coast, to capitalize on and accommodate growing passenger and cargo traffic; the Spokane market has been hosting big events and attracting business to the area.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/2017/mar/19/spokane-air-travelers-have-more-options |title=New flights boosting travel options at Spokane airport |first=Mike |last=Prager |work=The Spokesman-Review |location=Spokane |date=March 19, 2017 |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/2019/aug/24/spokane-international-airport-board-considering-sc/ |title=Spokane International Airport board considering scaled-down terminal expansion plan |first=Amy |last=Edelen |work=The Spokesman-Review |location=Spokane |date=August 24, 2019 |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\n[[File:GEG airport diagram.svg|thumb|right|Runways and terminals at Spokane International Airport.<!--Note that runway 8/26 has been incorrectly labelled 7/25-->]]\n\n===Airfield===\nThe airport covers {{convert|6140|acre}} and operates two paved runways:<ref name=\"FAA\" />\n*Runway 3/21: {{convert|11002|\u00d7|150|ft|abbr=on}}, Asphalt/Concrete\n*Runway 8/26: {{convert|8199|\u00d7|150|ft|abbr=on}}, Asphalt\n\n===Tower===\n\nIt is believed that the tower is the only [[Federal government of the United States|federal]] air traffic control tower named for any single person, after that honor was bestowed in 2010 on Ray Daves, the [[World War II]] [[radioman]] who survived [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|Pearl Harbor]] and [[Battle of Midway|Midway]] and went on to serve as an air traffic controller in Spokane after the war until the 1970s.<ref>[https://www.spokesman.com/stories/2011/jun/16/fond-memories-of-ray-daves-endure/ Front Porch: Fond memories of Ray Daves endure] by Cindy Hval in [[The Spokesman-Review]], June 16, 2011</ref><ref>[https://us.macmillan.com/books/9781250040985 Radioman: An Eyewitness Account of Pearl Harbor and World War II in the Pacific], a memoir by Ray Daves, as told to Carol Edgemon Hipperson ([https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/see-picture-aircraft-carrier-was-sunk-member-crew-told-us-how-73021 excerpt])</ref>\n\n===Terminals===\n[[File:GEG terminal diagram.svg|thumb|left|Terminals at Spokane International Airport]]\nThe passenger terminal facility at Spokane International Airport has three main structures; Concourse A and B in the center, Concourse C to the southwest, and the Ground Transportation Center to the north. The three structures are immediately adjacent and connected, however the two concourse structures are not linked with an airside connector on the sterile side; as such, connecting passengers need to transit between Concourse A-B and Concourse C through the landside, non-sterile circulation.\n\n====Concourse A-B====\n[[File:GEG B Concourse.JPG|thumb|right|Entrance to the Concourse A-B ticketing area.]]\n[[File:Spokane Airport Rotunda1.jpg|thumb|right|400px|View of the Rotunda in Concourse A-B]]\nThe 1965 Concourse A-B complex includes the two concourses linked by a central rotunda area with dining and shopping vendors. The {{convert|37000|ft2|abbr=on|adj=on}} rotunda is supported entirely along its perimeter and features no obstructions.<ref name=CFP-650409>{{cite news |url=http://cfp.stparchive.com/Archive/CFP/CFP04091965P05.php |title=New Airport Dedication Will Feature Alan Boyd |author= |date=9 April 1965 |newspaper=Cheney Free Press |accessdate=19 August 2017}}</ref> Concourse A houses 5 gates (11-15), while Concourse B houses 8 gates (1\u20138).\n\nThe Concourse A-B complex originally opened on April 1, 1965 and was designed by Warren C. Heylman and William Trogdon.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2016/jul/10/warren-heylman-spokane-architecture/#/0 |title=Warren Heylman's architectural vision 'all over' Spokane |author=Deshais, Nicholas |date=10 July 2016 |newspaper=The Spokesman-Review |accessdate=19 August 2017}}</ref> The new terminal cost a reported {{US$|4600000|1965|round=-4}} and was dedicated on May 8, 1965,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=BDhWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=segDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4972%2C8950 |title=New Terminal for Airport Opens Today |author= |date=1 April 1965 |newspaper=The Spokesman-Review |accessdate=19 August 2017}}</ref> in a ceremony attended by Senator [[Warren Magnuson]] and [[Civil Aeronautics Board]] chair [[Alan Stephenson Boyd|Alan Boyd]].<ref name=CFP-650409 /> Designed to the Neo-Expressionism style, the building's architecture prominently features exposed concrete as well as distinct sculpted and monolithic architectural shapes and forms.\n\nHowever, as the airport has continued to incrementally expand, some of the original architectural intent of the Concourse A-B complex has been lost. While several expansions to the concourse extended the building's original architectural style, other additions have altered it. In 1974, a second floor was added to both Concourses A and B to allow for the implementation of [[Jet bridge|passenger boarding bridge]] access to aircraft. The new floors, while sharing some material commonality with the original Heylman and Trogdon concourse, lacked the same curvy and sculpted neo-expressionistic forms. The later additions of the ground transportation facility and Concourse C to the ends of the concourse building further altered the architecture by replacing its distinct bookend elevations and entrances with corridors to the adjacent buildings. Interior renovations in the mid-2000s also replaced many of Concourse A-B complex's original sculpted forms and monolithic materials with more rectilinear forms and contemporary finish materials. Despite this, many of the original architectural elements remain integral to the space (such as the exposed concrete roof trusses and concrete columns), creating a juxtaposition between the newer elements and the original architecture.\n\nUnder the proposed Terminal Renovation and Expansion (TREX) program to accommodate projected growth, the separate baggage claim areas in Concourse A-B and Concourse C would be consolidated into a single baggage claim with five carousels, and A-B would receive a renovation. Ultimately, operations at A-B would wind down under long-term plans to construct a new terminal in 2030, at the earliest.<ref name=S-R-170719>{{cite news |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2017/jul/19/spokane-airport-eyeing-major-improvements/#/0\n |title=Spokane Airport eyeing major improvements |author=Prager, Mike |date=19 July 2017 |newspaper=The Spokesman-Review |accessdate=19 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Southwest Airlines]] is the current primary occupant operating in and out of Concourse A. [[Delta Air Lines|Delta]] and [[United Airlines]] both operate in and out of Concourse B. [[American Airlines]] operated in and out of Concourse B before relocating to Concourse C in March 2016.\n\n====Concourse C====\n[[File:Spokane Intl Airport - Concourse C at Night.jpg|thumb|right|Concourse C]]  \nConcourse C houses 9 gates, both upper (30-32) and lower (21a, 21b, 22-26). The lower level gates house regional turboprop aircraft, while the upper-level gates house narrow-body aircraft. The current iteration of Concourse C opened in 2000 after a $20 million redevelopment and expansion project, designed by Bernardo-Wills Architects.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bernardowills.com/portfolio/concoursec/ |title=Concourse C Addition & Remodel, Spokane International Airport |author=\n |date= |publisher=Bernardo-Wills Architects |accessdate=19 August 2017}}</ref>  The project, which broke ground in 1998 added {{convert|80000|ft2}} to the concourse including a new baggage claim and two-story passenger facility. The {{convert|11000|ft2|adj=on}} concourse was remodeled into service and operations functions.<ref>{{cite news |title=Airport projects set to take off|url=http://www.spokanejournal.com/local-news/airport-projects-set-to-take-off/ |author=Cain, Chad |date=9 April 1998 |newspaper=Spokane Journal of Business |accessdate=January 15, 2016}}</ref> The new Concourse C has a more contemporary architectural style, contrasting the appearance of the Concourse A and B complex, by employing a large use of metal cladding and large curtain window walls on its exterior building envelope. However, it draws inspiration from its neo-expressionist neighbor by architecturally expressing a modular, repetitive, and exposed structural grid through its fa\u00e7ade and interior lobby areas.\n\n[[Alaska Airlines]] and its sister carrier [[Horizon Air]] were the primary occupants operating in and out of Concourse C after [[Frontier Airlines]] ceased operations to Spokane in January 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Frontier Airlines ending service at Spokane International Airport|url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2014/dec/22/frontier-airlines-ending-service-at-spokane/|work=Spokesman Review|accessdate=March 30, 2016}}</ref> However, that changed once [[American Airlines]] relocated to Concourse C in March 2016. Alaska and American operate in and out of the upper-level gates, while Horizon operates in and out of the lower level gates.\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\nSpokane International Airport is served by 6 carriers. These carriers serve 13 markets through non-stop service to 15 airports.\n\n===Passenger===\n[[File:Delta CRJ700 GEG.JPG|right|thumb|Delta Connection Bombardier CRJ-700 taxis to Concourse B Gate B6.]]\n[[File:United Express ERJ170 GEG.JPG|right|thumb|United Express Embraer 170 begins taxiing for departure.]]\n[[File:Delta 757 GEG.JPG|right|thumb|Delta Air Lines Boeing 757 seen at Concourse B Gate B8.]]\n{{Airport destination list\n<!-- -->\n| [[Alaska Airlines]] | [[Boise Airport|Boise]], [[Paine Field|Everett]], [[Los Angeles International Airport|Los Angeles]], [[Portland International Airport|Portland (OR)]], [[San Diego International Airport|San Diego]], [[San Francisco International Airport|San Francisco]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Deshais |first=Nick |date=August 28, 2019 |title=Alaska Airlines to begin direct flights next year from Spokane to Los Angeles, San Francisco |url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/2019/aug/28/alaska-airlines-to-begin-direct-flights-next-year-/ |work=The Spokesman-Review |accessdate=August 28, 2019}}</ref> [[Seattle\u2013Tacoma International Airport|Seattle/Tacoma]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[American Airlines]] | [[Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport|Dallas/Fort Worth]], [[Phoenix Sky Harbor International Airport|Phoenix\u2013Sky Harbor]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Delta Air Lines]] | [[Hartsfield\u2013Jackson Atlanta International Airport|Atlanta]] (begins July 6, 2020),<ref>{{cite news |last=Deshais |first=Nicholas |date=December 16, 2019 |title=Delta Air Lines to launch direct flights from Spokane to Atlanta in July |url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/2019/dec/16/delta-air-lines-to-launch-direct-flights-from-spok/ |work=The Spokesman-Review |accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref> [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul International Airport|Minneapolis/St. Paul]], [[Salt Lake City International Airport|Salt Lake City]], [[Seattle\u2013Tacoma International Airport|Seattle/Tacoma]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Delta Connection]] | [[Los Angeles International Airport|Los Angeles]], [[Salt Lake City International Airport|Salt Lake City]], [[Seattle\u2013Tacoma International Airport|Seattle/Tacoma]]\n| [[Frontier Airlines]] |[[McCarran International Airport|Las Vegas]] <br />'''Seasonal:''' [[Denver International Airport|Denver]]\n<!-- -->\n| {{nowrap|[[Southwest Airlines]]}} | [[Boise Airport|Boise]], [[Denver International Airport|Denver]], [