gan\n* [[Hazen Street]] \u2013 Mackie\n* [[Kraut (band)|Kraut]] \u2013 Holland\n* MOI (Mode of Ignorance) \u2013 Flanagan, Holland, JJ\n* [[Murphy's Law (band)|Murphy's Law]] \u2013 Flanagan, Hines\n* S\u0103ms\u00e4ra \u2013 Flanagan, Mayhew, Di Censo, George\n* [[Shelter (band)|Shelter]] - Di Censo\n* [[Suicidal Tendencies]] - George\n* [[The Icemen]] \u2013 Mackie\n* [[The Stimulators (NYC band)|The Stimulators]] \u2013 Flanagan\n* [[Urban Blight (band)|Urban Blight]] \u2013 Mackie\n* White Devil \u2013 Flanagan, Mayhew, Di Censo\n\n==See also==\n* [[New York hardcore]]\n* [[Animal rights and punk subculture]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.realcromags.com/ Official Cro-Mags Website]\n* [http://www.cro-mags.com/ Parris Mayhew's Cro-Mags Website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090430155937/http://www.halfcute.com/2009/03/evolution-of-writer-john-joseph.html Interview with Quarter-Life Crisis]\n* [http://musicbrainz.org/artist/9ffa627f-32c2-4cb1-bfad-00cf348abc70.html Artist: Cro-Mags \u2013 MusicBrainz]\n\n{{Cro-Mags}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1981 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American thrash metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Crossover thrash groups]]\n[[Category:Hardcore punk groups from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal musical groups from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:International Society for Krishna Consciousness bands]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1981]]\n[[Category:Musical quartets]]\n[[Category:Squatters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Cro-Magnon (disambiguation)}}\n{{More citations needed|date=September 2008}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name            = Cro-Mags\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Harley Cro-Mags.jpg|thumb|]] -->\n| caption         = \n| image           =  \n| image_size      = \n| background      = group_or_band\n| alias           = \n| origin          = [[New York City]], New York, US\n| genre           = {{flatlist|\n* {{nowrap|[[Hardcore punk]]}}\n* [[crossover thrash]]}}\n| years_active    = 1981\u20132002, 2008-present\n| label           = {{flatlist|\n* [[Victory Records]]\n* [[Arising Empire]]\n* [[Century Media]]\n* [[Mightier Than Sword Records|Mightier than Sword]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[The Stimulators (NYC band)|The Stimulators]]\n* [[Murphy's Law (band)|Murphy's Law]]\n* White Devil\n* S\u0103ms\u00e4ra\n* [[Urban Blight (band)|Urban Blight]]\n* [[The Icemen]]\n* [[Bad Brains]]\n* [[Suicidal Tendencies]]\n* Bloodclot!\n* MOI\n* Both Worlds\n* [[Kraut (band)|Kraut]]\n* [[Shelter (band)|Shelter]]\n}}\n| website         = {{URL|realcromags.com}}\n| current_members =\n* [[Harley Flanagan]]\n* [[Gabby Abularach]]\n* Garry Sullivan\n* [[Rocky George]]\n| past_members    = \n* [[John Joseph (singer)|John Joseph]]\n* Mackie Jayson\n* A.J. Novello\n* [[Craig Setari]]\n* Parris Mayhew\n* Eric Casanova\n* [[Doug Holland]]\n* Pete Hines\n* Dave di Censo\n* Rob Buckley\n}}\n\nThe '''Cro-Mags''' are an American [[hardcore punk]] band from [[New York City]], United States. The band, which has a strong [[cult following]],{{fact|date=February 2020}} has released five studio albums, their first two considered the most influential.{{fact|date=February 2020}} With a [[International Society for Krishna Consciousness|Hare Krishna]] background, they were among the first bands to fuse hardcore punk with [[thrash metal]]{{fact|date=February 2020}} and were associated with the birth of a tougher attitude within the hardcore scene in the late 1980s,{{fact|date=February 2020}} related to the world of martial arts.{{fact|date=February 2020}} [[Harley Flanagan]] (formerly drummer for [[The Stimulators (NYC band)|the Stimulators]]) and [[John Joseph (singer)|John Joseph]] are practitioners of [[Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu|Brazilian jiu-jitsu]] and [[boxing]] respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bjjstyle.com/hardcore-legend-harley-flanagan-his-journey-to-black-belt/|title=HARDCORE LEGEND HARLEY FLANAGAN: HIS JOURNEY TO BLACK BELT \u2013 Jiu Jitsu Style|last=Style|first=Jiu Jitsu|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.triathlete.com/2013/03/features/john-joseph-from-frontman-to-ironman_71597|title=John Joseph: From Frontman To Ironman|last=Harder|first=Jeff|date=2013-03-05|website=Triathlete.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref>\n\nThe Cro-Mags have gone through many line-up changes since the band's beginnings. Flanagan has been the sole trademark owner of the group's name since the early 1990s,\u00a0the primary songwriter and only member featured on every album, while Joseph and Mackie continued to tour with other musicians using the Cro-Mags name against the wishes of Flanagan. In April 2019, Flanagan reached a settlement with Joseph and Mackie in which Flanagan would retain exclusive rights to the Cro-Mags name while Joseph and Mackie would move forward under the name, Cro-Mags \"JM\".\n\n==History==\nThe band's early years were spent living in burnt out buildings, squats and on the streets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cro-mags.com/|title=The Official Cro-Mags Website|website=Cro-mags.com|accessdate=2019-11-13}}</ref> By 1982/83 Flanagan recorded the very first Cro-Mags [[demo (music)|demo]] consisting of 4 songs that would become the blue print for their debut album ''[[The Age of Quarrel]]'' ([[1986 in music|1986]]). Flanagan wrote all of the music, played each instrument, and performed vocals. Before long he connected with Parris Mayhew and the two started writing music and auditioning band members. Age of Quarrel singer John Joseph parted ways with the band for the first time after Age of Quarrel, leaving [[bass guitar|bass]] player Harley Flanagan to sing on the following Cro-Mags release, ''[[Best Wishes (Cro-Mags album)|Best Wishes]]'' ([[1989 in music|1989]]), which had a more heavy metal-influenced sound. The next record ''[[Alpha Omega (Cro-Mags album)|Alpha Omega]]'' saw the return of Joseph singing along with Flanagan. According to guitarist and songwriter Parris Mayhew, he wrote most of the album with guitarist Rob Buckley. However, neither Mayhew or Buckley played on the actual recording and the writing has been disputed by Flanagan and others. The Cro-Mags disbanded and later recorded the album with the return of [[Doug Holland]] and a new rhythm guitarist: [[Gabby Abularach]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cro-mags.com/emails.htm|title=The Official Cro-Mags Website|website=Cro-mags.com|accessdate=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\nThe album ''[[Near Death Experience (Cro-Mags album)|Near Death Experience]]'' was released in 1993, after which the group disbanded for several years. They began touring again in the late 1990s with Flanagan on vocals and bass and Mayhew returning to the fold and eventually released ''[[Revenge (Cro-Mags album)|Revenge]]'' in 2000. For many fans, this album signified a return to Cro-Mags' early hardcore roots. Many songs were comparable to those on ''The Age of Quarrel'', although some featured a more melodic/punk rock style. The release of ''Revenge'' and its subsequent tour resulted in yet another break up, which caused lasting resentment between Mayhew and Flanagan. In 2001 Flanagan asked Joseph to join him once again, but that was a short lived reunion and ended in 2002.\n\nIn 2008, John Joseph and Mackie began playing shows under the Cro-Mags name with other established hardcore musicians such as Craig Setari from Sick of It All on bass, and A.J. Novello from Leeway on guitar. In an October 2010 interview, Joseph revealed that they were planning to release a new album in 2011,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.punknews.org/article/40101/cro-mags-plan-2011-album|title=Cro-Mags plan 2011 album|website=Punknews.org}}</ref> though ultimately this did not happen. Flanagan released his solo debut album, ''Cro-Mags'', in 2016, it featured Cro-Mags alum  Gabby Abularach on guitar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.punknews.org/review/14145/harley-flanagan-cro-mags|title=Harley Flanagan - Cro-magsg|date=23 Jan 2016|website=Punknews.org|language=en|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Flanagan filed a federal trademark infringement action suing prior band members John Joseph and Mackie Jayson. In April 2019 Flanagan announced a settlement wherein he would own exclusive use of the name \"Cro-Mags\"; simultaneously, Joseph announced his recognition of the settlement, and that he and his band would perform as Cro-Mags \"JM\", beginning in August.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.punknews.org/article/69655/harley-flanagan-and-john-joseph-settle-cro-mags-lawsuit|title=Harley Flanagan and John Joseph settle Cro-Mags lawsuit|website=Punknews.org|language=en|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref>\n\nOn June 28, 2019, Cro-Mags released their first new music in nineteen years, sharing three new songs \"Don't Give In\", \"Drag You Under\" and \"No One's Victim\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/cro-mags-new-music-853285/|title=Hear Hardcore Heroes Cro-Mags Return With First New Songs in 20 Years|website=Rollingstone.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> and they were preparing a new album with producer, Arthur Rizk for a planned early 2020 release date. They were the opening act for four shows with the reunited [[Misfits (band)|Misfits]]: June 29 in Los Angeles, September 7 in Denver, September 11 in Oakland and September 14 in Seattle. This was followed by a ten-date European tour to commemorate the thirtieth anniversary of the ''Best Wishes'' album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/realcromags/photos/a.2050359058382637/2448310508587488/?type=3|title=CRO-MAGS|website=Facebook.com|accessdate=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the European tour, Cro-Mags released the digital single, \"From the Grave\" that featured former [[Mot\u00f6rhead]] guitarist [[Phil Campbell (musician)|Phil Campbell]] on lead and slide guitar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/listen-to-new-cro-mags-single-from-the-grave-feat-motorhead-guitarist-phil-campbell/|title=Listen To New CRO-MAGS Single 'From The Grave' Feat. MOT\u00d6RHEAD Guitarist PHIL CAMPBELL|website=Blabbermouth.net|language=en|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref> A three-song 7\" EP of the same name was released on December 6 2019 in various colors and have the tracks \"PTSD\" and \"Between Wars\" included. The band was set to perform with [[Body Count (band)|Body Count]] in New York City on March 15 at Webster Hall. The show was postponed due to the [[COVID-19]] virus. Flanagan announced that Friday <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/realcromags/videos/233014748099216/|title=Cro-Mags Corona Virus Quarantine Show - Live Stream Sunday night|accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> the band would instead perform at SIR studios on the Sunday and stream it worldwide for free, one of the first bands to do so during the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/entertainment/2020/03/23/musicians-reach-out-amid-coronavirus.cnn|title=musicians-reach-out-amid-coronavirus.cnn|website=cnn.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> On March 31, 2020, the band offered a free download of the track, \"The Final Test\" and announced their first studio album in twenty years, ''In the Beginning'', will be released on June 19, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/cro-mags-to-release-in-the-beginning-album-in-june-new-song-available-for-free-download/|title=CRO-MAGS To Release 'In The Beginning' Album In June; New Song Available For Free Download|website=Blabbermouth.net|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n==Members==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=May 2017}}\n\n===Current===\n* [[Harley Flanagan]] \u2013 bass, (1981\u20131996, 1999\u20132002, 2019\u2013present) vocals (1987\u20131996, 1992\u20132002, 2019\u2013present)\n* [[Gabby Abularach]] \u2013 rhythm guitar (1991\u20131995, 2019\u2013present)\n* [[Rocky George]] - lead guitar (1999\u20132001, 2002\u20132003, 2019\u2013present)\n* Garry \"G-Man\" Sullivan \u2013 drums (1999, 2001-2002, 2002-2003, 2019\u2013present)\n\n===Former===\n* [[John Joseph (singer)|John Joseph]] \u2013 vocals (1981, 1984\u20131987, 1991\u20131999, 2002\u20132003, 2008-2019)\n* Mackie Jayson \u2013 drums (1984\u20131986, 1996\u20131999, 2008\u20132019)\n* A.J. Novello \u2013 guitars (2008-2019)\n* [[Craig Setari]] \u2013 bass (2008-2019)\n* Parris Mayhew \u2013 rhythm guitar (1982\u20131991, 1999\u20132001)\n* Eric Casanova \u2013 vocals (1982\u20131984)\n* [[Doug Holland]] \u2013 lead guitar (1985\u20131989, 1991\u20131993, 1996\u20131999, 2001)\n* Pete Hines \u2013 drums (1986\u20131989)\n* Dave di Censo \u2013 drums (1989\u20131995)\n* Rob Buckley \u2013 lead guitar (1989\u20131991, 1993\u20131995, 2001)\n\nAt various times during the 1990s and 2000s, Flanagan and Joseph simultaneously led separate versions of the Cro-Mags with completely different lineups. The groups billed themselves as Cro-Mag Jam, Street Justice, Age of Quarrel, Rival Mob, FVK (Fearless Vampire Killers) or Cholo-Mags.{{citation needed|date=July 2012}}\n\n===Timeline===\n<div align=\"center\">\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize = width:800 height:auto barincrement:20\nPlotArea = left:150 bottom:60 top:10 right:30\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat  = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/01/1981 till:{{#time:d/m/Y}}\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend = orientation:horizontal position:bottom\nScaleMajor = increment:4 start:1981\nScaleMinor = increment:1 start:1981\n\nColors =\n id:vocals     value:red       legend:Vocals\n id:guitar     value:green     legend:Guitars\n id:bass       value:blue      legend:Bass\n id:drums      value:orange    legend:Drums\n id:studio     value:black     legend:Studio_album\n id:bars       value:gray(0.9)\n\nBackgroundColors =  bars:bars\n\nLineData =\n layer:back\n color:studio\n  at:01/07/1986\n  at:26/04/1989\n  at:01/06/1992\n  at:01/06/1993\n 