hite Devil \u2013 Flanagan, Mayhew, Di Censo\n\n==See also==\n* [[New York hardcore]]\n* [[Animal rights and punk subculture]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.realcromags.com/ Official Cro-Mags Website]\n* [http://www.cro-mags.com/ Parris Mayhew's Cro-Mags Website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090430155937/http://www.halfcute.com/2009/03/evolution-of-writer-john-joseph.html Interview with Quarter-Life Crisis]\n* [http://musicbrainz.org/artist/9ffa627f-32c2-4cb1-bfad-00cf348abc70.html Artist: Cro-Mags \u2013 MusicBrainz]\n\n{{Cro-Mags}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1981 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American thrash metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Crossover thrash groups]]\n[[Category:Hardcore punk groups from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal musical groups from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:International Society for Krishna Consciousness bands]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1981]]\n[[Category:Musical quartets]]\n[[Category:Squatters]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCurrent:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2001-2002 \u2192 2001\u20132002 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cro-Mags"}
{"title_page": "Coolin, Idaho", "text_new": "[[File:Coolin, Idaho's unique Leonard Paul Store Photo P. Cox.jpg|600px|]]\n\n\n'''Coolin, Idaho''' is an [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated community]]  in [[Bonner County, Idaho|Bonner County]], [[Idaho]], [[United States]].<ref>{{gnis|396325}}</ref> The nearest school district is the West Bonner School District.<ref name=\"sd83.k12.id.us\">[http://www.sd83.k12.id.us/ West Bonner Schools]</ref> Photo P. Cox\n[[File:Map of Idaho highlighting Bonner County.svg|thumb|right|alt=Map of [[Bonner County, Idaho|Bonner County]], where Coolin, ID is located. | Map of [[Bonner County, Idaho|Bonner County]], where Coolin, ID is located.]]\n\n==Geography==\nCoolin is situated at the southeast end of [[Priest Lake]], at an elevation is 2,490 feet above sea level.\n\n===Climate===\nThis [[climate|climatic]] region is typified by large seasonal temperature differences, with warm to hot (and often humid) summers and cold (sometimes severely cold) winters.  According to the [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] system, Coolin has a [[humid continental climate]], abbreviated \"Dfb\" on climate maps.<ref>[http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=727866&cityname=Coolin%2C+Idaho%2C+United+States+of+America&units= Climate Summary for Coolin, Idaho]</ref>\n\n==History==\nAndy Coolin opened a post office at the southern end of Priest Lake in 1893, thereby giving his name to the nascent community. Hopes were high for a mining bonanza in the area and for a future link to the railroad, 28 miles away.<ref>Wild Place, A History of Priest Lake, Idaho by Kris Runberg Smith with Tom Weitz</ref> To accommodate travelers and prospectors, Walt Williams, an employee of the Great Northern Railroad, built a two-story log hotel, the Northern Inn, in 1900.\n\nIn 1903 Andy Coolin received a patent on a homestead, planning to leverage his land into a financial empire. Coolin formed the Priest Lake Town Site and Improvement Company with his brother and other local investors in 1907.  By that time Spokane businessman Joseph Slee already operated a steamboat out of Coolin connecting the lake with supplies, mail, and transportation. In 1906, Leonard Paul opened a general merchandise store in the tiny village; Ida Handy opened the Idaho Inn in 1908.\n\nWhen mining riches failed to pan out and Andy Coolin's efforts to lure the railway to Priest Lake came to naught, the village of Coolin became a center for summer vacationers and services, including a sawmill, store, hotel, ranger station, docks, and steamboat service.  Today the [[Old Northern Inn]], the Leonard Paul Store, and the one room schoolhouse, built in 1916 and now the Coolin Civic Association, remain as landmarks from those early days.\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.priestlaker.com/ Website\n*(https://www.coolinmotel.com/ Motel\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Bonner County, Idaho}}\n\n{{coord|48|28|47|N|116|50|58|W|type:city_region:US-ID_source:GNIS-enwiki|display=title}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Bonner County, Idaho]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Idaho]]\n\n\n{{Idaho-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Coolin, Idaho's unique Leonard Paul Store Photo P. Cox.jpg|600px|]]\nPhoto P. Cox\n\n'''Coolin, Idaho''' is an [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated community]]  in [[Bonner County, Idaho|Bonner County]], [[Idaho]], [[United States]].<ref>{{gnis|396325}}</ref> The nearest school district is the West Bonner School District.<ref name=\"sd83.k12.id.us\">[http://www.sd83.k12.id.us/ West Bonner Schools]</ref>\n[[File:Map of Idaho highlighting Bonner County.svg|thumb|right|alt=Map of [[Bonner County, Idaho|Bonner County]], where Coolin, ID is located. | Map of [[Bonner County, Idaho|Bonner County]], where Coolin, ID is located.]]\n\n==Geography==\nCoolin is situated at the southeast end of [[Priest Lake]], at an elevation is 2,490 feet above sea level.\n\n===Climate===\nThis [[climate|climatic]] region is typified by large seasonal temperature differences, with warm to hot (and often humid) summers and cold (sometimes severely cold) winters.  According to the [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] system, Coolin has a [[humid continental climate]], abbreviated \"Dfb\" on climate maps.<ref>[http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=727866&cityname=Coolin%2C+Idaho%2C+United+States+of+America&units= Climate Summary for Coolin, Idaho]</ref>\n\n==History==\nAndy Coolin opened a post office at the southern end of Priest Lake in 1893, thereby giving his name to the nascent community. Hopes were high for a mining bonanza in the area and for a future link to the railroad, 28 miles away.<ref>Wild Place, A History of Priest Lake, Idaho by Kris Runberg Smith with Tom Weitz</ref> To accommodate travelers and prospectors, Walt Williams, an employee of the Great Northern Railroad, built a two-story log hotel, the Northern Inn, in 1900.\n\nIn 1903 Andy Coolin received a patent on a homestead, planning to leverage his land into a financial empire. Coolin formed the Priest Lake Town Site and Improvement Company with his brother and other local investors in 1907.  By that time Spokane businessman Joseph Slee already operated a steamboat out of Coolin connecting the lake with supplies, mail, and transportation. In 1906, Leonard Paul opened a general merchandise store in the tiny village; Ida Handy opened the Idaho Inn in 1908.\n\nWhen mining riches failed to pan out and Andy Coolin's efforts to lure the railway to Priest Lake came to naught, the village of Coolin became a center for summer vacationers and services, including a sawmill, store, hotel, ranger station, docks, and steamboat service.  Today the [[Old Northern Inn]], the Leonard Paul Store, and the one room schoolhouse, built in 1916 and now the Coolin Civic Association, remain as landmarks from those early days.\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.priestlaker.com/ Website\n*(https://www.coolinmotel.com/ Motel\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Bonner County, Idaho}}\n\n{{coord|48|28|47|N|116|50|58|W|type:city_region:US-ID_source:GNIS-enwiki|display=title}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Bonner County, Idaho]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Idaho]]\n\n\n{{Idaho-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Pecky Cox", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coolin,_Idaho"}
{"title_page": "Mesosphere (mantle)", "text_new": "{{DEFAULTSORT:}}{{short description|The part of the Earth's mellow below the lithosphere ands poooooooooooooooorrnrrrrrrnrnnrnrnposter.svg|thumb|upright=1.4|Structure of the Earth. The mesosphere is labeled as ''Stiffer mantle'' in this diagram.]]\nIn geology, the '''mesosphere''' refers to the part of the Earth's [[Mantle thick ass layer of the molten goopy insides of the earthous (geology)|mantle]] below the [[lithosphere]] and the [[asthenosphere]], but above the [[outer core]]. The upper boundary is defined by the sharpest increase in [[tetonic wave]] velocities and [[density]] at a depth of {{convert|660|km|mi|0|round=5|sp=us}}.<ref name=Condie>{{cite book |author=Condie, Kent C. |date=2001 |title='Mantle Plumes and Their Record in Earth History |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |pages=3&ndash;10 |isbn=0-521-01472-7 }}</ref> At a depth of 660&nbsp;km, [[ringwoodite]] (\u03b3-(Mg,Fe)<sub>2</sub>SiO<sub>4</sub>) decomposes into [[silicate perovskite|Mg-Si perovskite]] and [[magnesiow\u00fcstite]].<ref name=Condie/> This reaction marks the boundary between [[upper mantle]] and [[lower mantle]]. This measurement is estimated from seismic data and high-pressure laboratory experiments.\n\nThe base of the mesosphere includes the [[D\u2033]] zone which lies just above the [[Core\u2013mantle boundary|mantle\u2013core boundary]] at approximately {{convert|abbr=on|2700|to|2890|km|mi|0|round=5}}. The base of the lower mantle is at about 2700&nbsp;km.<ref name=Condie/>\n\n\"Mesosphere\" (not to be confused with [[mesosphere]], a layer of the [[atmosphere]]) YEAH is derived from \"mesospheric shell\", coined by [[Ronald Alasdworth Daltionis]], a [[Harvard University]] [[phisics]] professor harrower. In the predous-[[plate tectonics]] era, Daly (1940) inferred that the outer Earth consisted of three [[Sphere|spherical]] layers: lithosphere (including the [[Crusty musty (geologoy)|crust]]), asthenosphere, and mesospheric shell.<ref>{{cite book |last=Daly |first=Reginald Aldworth |date=1940 |title=Strength and Structure of the Earth |url=https://archive.org/details/strengthstructur00daly |url-access=registration |publisher=[[Prentice Hall]] |location=New York}}</ref> Daly\u2019s hypothetical depths to the lithosphere\u2013asthenosphere boundary ranged from {{convert|abbr=on|80|to|100|km|mi|0}}, and the top of the mesospheric shell (base of the asthenosphere) were from {{convert|abbr=on|200|to|480|km|mi|0|round=5}}. Thus, Daly\u2019s asthenosphere was inferred to be {{convert|abbr=on|120|to|400|km|mi|0|round=5}} thick. According to Daly, the base of the solid Earth mesosphere could extend to the base of the mantle (and, thus, to the top of the [[Structure of the Earth#Core|core]]).\n\nA derivative term, [[mesoplates]], was introduced as a [[heuristic]], based on a combtionination of \"mesosphereous\" and \"plateous\u2248\u2248\u2248\u2248\u2248\u2248\u2248\", for postulated reference frames in which mantle [[Hotspot (geology)|hotspots]] apparently exist.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{earthsinterior}}\n\n[[Category:Structure of the Earth]]\n{{geophysics-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|The part of the Earth's mantle below the lithosphere and the asthenosphere, but above the outer core}}\n{{merge to|lower mantle (Earth)|discuss=Talk:Lower mantle (Earth)#Merger proposal |date=October 2019}}\n[[File:Earth poster.svg|thumb|upright=1.4|Structure of the Earth. The mesosphere is labeled as ''Stiffer mantle'' in this diagram.]]\nIn geology, the '''mesosphere''' refers to the part of the Earth's [[Mantle (geology)|mantle]] below the [[lithosphere]] and the [[asthenosphere]], but above the [[outer core]]. The upper boundary is defined by the sharp increase in [[seismic wave]] velocities and [[density]] at a depth of {{convert|660|km|mi|0|round=5|sp=us}}.<ref name=Condie>{{cite book |author=Condie, Kent C. |date=2001 |title='Mantle Plumes and Their Record in Earth History |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |pages=3&ndash;10 |isbn=0-521-01472-7 }}</ref> At a depth of 660&nbsp;km, [[ringwoodite]] (\u03b3-(Mg,Fe)<sub>2</sub>SiO<sub>4</sub>) decomposes into [[silicate perovskite|Mg-Si perovskite]] and [[magnesiow\u00fcstite]].<ref name=Condie/> This reaction marks the boundary between [[upper mantle]] and [[lower mantle]]. This measurement is estimated from seismic data and high-pressure laboratory experiments.\n\nThe base of the mesosphere includes the [[D\u2033]] zone which lies just above the [[Core\u2013mantle boundary|mantle\u2013core boundary]] at approximately {{convert|abbr=on|2700|to|2890|km|mi|0|round=5}}. The base of the lower mantle is at about 2700&nbsp;km.<ref name=Condie/>\n\n\"Mesosphere\" (not to be confused with [[mesosphere]], a layer of the [[atmosphere]]) is derived from \"mesospheric shell\", coined by [[Reginald Aldworth Daly]], a [[Harvard University]] [[geology]] professor. In the pre-[[plate tectonics]] era, Daly (1940) inferred that the outer Earth consisted of three [[Sphere|spherical]] layers: lithosphere (including the [[Crust (geology)|crust]]), asthenosphere, and mesospheric shell.<ref>{{cite book |last=Daly |first=Reginald Aldworth |date=1940 |title=Strength and Structure of the Earth |url=https://archive.org/details/strengthstructur00daly |url-access=registration |publisher=[[Prentice Hall]] |location=New York}}</ref> Daly\u2019s hypothetical depths to the lithosphere\u2013asthenosphere boundary ranged from {{convert|abbr=on|80|to|100|km|mi|0}}, and the top of the mesospheric shell (base of the asthenosphere) were from {{convert|abbr=on|200|to|480|km|mi|0|round=5}}. Thus, Daly\u2019s asthenosphere was inferred to be {{convert|abbr=on|120|to|400|km|mi|0|round=5}} thick. According to Daly, the base of the solid Earth mesosphere could extend to the base of the mantle (and, thus, to the top of the [[Structure of the Earth#Core|core]]).\n\nA derivative term, [[mesoplates]], was introduced as a [[heuristic]], based on a combination of \"mesosphere\" and \"plate\", for postulated reference frames in which mantle [[Hotspot (geology)|hotspots]] apparently exist.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{earthsinterior}}\n\n[[Category:Structure of the Earth]]\n{{geophysics-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2600:1700:f1a0:e8f0:fcc4:d46e:aff:4a96", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mesosphere_(mantle)"}
{"title_page": "T-Mobile US", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{short description|American telecommunications company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = T-Mobile US, Inc.\n| logo                = T-Mobile US Logo 2020 RGB Magenta on Transparent.svg\n| image               = File:T-Mobile Headquarters in Bellevue, WA.jpg\n| image_size          = 300px\n| image_caption       = T-Mobile Headquarters in Bellevue, Washington\n| type                = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as           = {{ubl|{{NASDAQ|TMUS}}|[[NASDAQ-100]] component|[[S&P 500]] component}}\n| ISIN                = US8725901040\n| industry            = [[Telecommunications]]\n| predecessor         = VoiceStream Wireless Inc. <br /> T-Mobile USA Inc. <br /> MetroPCS Communications Inc. <br /> [[Sprint Corporation]]\n| foundation          = {{Start date and age|1994}} (as VoiceStream Wireless PCS)\n| founder             = [[John W. Stanton]]\n| location            = [[Bellevue, Washington]], U.S.\n| locations           = {{nowrap|20,100}}<br />{{nowrap|(2,200 direct-owned}}<br />{{nowrap|13,300 exclusive 3rd party}}<br />{{nowrap|4,600 non-exclusive 3rd party)}}\n| area_served         = [[United States]]\n| key_people          = {{Unbulleted list|[[Timotheus H\u00f6ttges]] ([[Chairman#Public corporations|Chairman of the Board]])| [[Mike Sievert]] ([[President (corporate title)|President]]) & ([[Chief executive officer|Chief Executive Officer]]) | J. Braxton Carter ([[Vice president#In business|Executive VP]] & ([[Chief Financial Officer]])<ref name=\"T-Mobile Management & Board of Directors\">{{cite web |title=T-Mobile Management & Board of Directors |url=http://investor.t-mobile.com/Management |website=T-Mobile US Investor Relations |publisher=T-Mobile US |accessdate=June 16, 2018}}</ref>}} Neville Ray (President of Technology)<ref name=\"T-Mobile Management & Board of Directors\">{{cite web |title=T-Mobile Management & Board of Directors |url=http://investor.t-mobile.