s.\n|-\n|66\n| Active/Building&nbsp;Out<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/tmobile/comments/69bim1/execute_order_66_may_4th_santa_fe_nm/|title=Execute order 66! May 4th Santa Fe, NM. \u2022 r/tmobile|website=reddit|language=en|access-date=May 5, 2017}}</ref>\n| Extended AWS block for additional capacity in some areas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://maps.spectrumgateway.com/t-mobile-aws-3-spectrum.html|title=Map of T-Mobile's AWS-3 spectrum|website=maps.spectrumgateway.com|access-date=May 5, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1900&nbsp;MHz&nbsp;PCS\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2\n|GSM/GPRS/EDGE\n|2G\n|Active\n|Currently retaining 2G service for M2M customers and international roaming.\n|-\n|UMTS/HSPA+\n|3G<ref name=\"Qualcomm\" /><ref name=\"4gamericas\" /><ref name=\"3GPP\" /><ref name=\"GSMA\" />\n|Active/Refarming to LTE\n|Used for 3G service in most markets as AWS spectrum is refarmed for LTE. 3G PCS service may operate alongside AWS 3G in some urban markets. 3G PCS service is being refarmed in some areas for additional LTE capacity.<ref name=\"1900Mhz-upgrade\">{{Cite news|url=https://support.t-mobile.com/docs/DOC-31961|title=Network upgrades from U1900 to LTE|work=T-Mobile Support|access-date=April 27, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n|-\n|LTE\n|4G\n|Active/Building Out\n|Refarmed from 3G.<ref name=\"1900Mhz-upgrade\"/> PCS LTE is typically deployed in rural areas to reuse GSM antennas. PCS LTE is also being rolled out in urban areas to increase LTE capacity. It is also the main LTE band in some markets where AWS is not available.<ref name=\"2013 Q4 results\">{{cite web|url=http://seekingalpha.com/article/2048673-t-mobile-us-management-discusses-q4-2013-results-earnings-call-transcript?page=3|title=T-Mobile US Management Discusses Q4 2013 Results \u2013 Earnings Call Transcript|date=February 25, 2014|publisher=Seeking Alpha|accessdate=February 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiercewireless.com/story/t-mobile-focus-1900-mhz-lte-deployment-expand-network-footprint/2014-09-24|title=T-Mobile to focus on 1900 MHz LTE deployment to expand network footprint|date=September 24, 2014|accessdate=October 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsroom.t-mobile.com/issues-insights-blog/t-mobile-lte-now-reaches-250-million-americans-months-ahead-of-schedule.htm|title=T-Mobile LTE Now Reaches 250 Million Americans \u2013 Months Ahead of Schedule|last1=Ray|first1=Neville|website=T-Mobile Newsroom|accessdate=November 28, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|5200&nbsp;MHz U-NII\n|46\n|LTE\n|4G\n|Active/Building Out\n|[[License Assisted Access|License assisted access]] (LAA). Additional capacity in select cities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcmag.com/news/t-mobiles-laa-creates-screaming-fast-speeds-in-nyc|title=T-Mobile's LAA Creates Screaming Fast Speeds in NYC|website=PCMAG|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n|-\n|28&nbsp;GHz mmWave\n|n261\n|NR\n|5G\n|Active/Building Out\n|Secondary 5G NR band mmWave for high-speed LAA using small cells. Only will be available in select areas.<ref name=\"5g30cities\" /><ref name=\"5gcitiesfierce\" /> Went live in June 2019.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.t-mobile.com/news/samsung-galaxy-s10-5g|title=T-Mobile to Carry the Samsung Galaxy S10 5G|last=Bellevue|last2=June 25|first2=Washington-|website=www.t-mobile.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-07|last3=2019 \u2014}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tmonews.com/2019/06/t-mobile-galaxy-s10-5g-launch-network-six-cities/|title=T-Mobile launching Samsung Galaxy S10 5G on June 28th, 5G network going live in six cities|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref>\n|-\n|39&nbsp;GHz mmWave\n|n260\n|NR\n|5G\n|Active/Building Out\n|Available in pockets of select cities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.t-mobile.com/support/coverage/t-mobile-network|title=T-Mobile network|website=T-Mobile Support|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==={{anchor|T-Mobile HotSpots}}T-Mobile HotSpots===\nT-Mobile has used the term \"''Hotspot''\" to represent various products and technologies.\n\n====Wi-Fi network (public)====\n\nThe company operates a nationwide Wi-Fi Internet access network under the T-Mobile HotSpots brand. The T-Mobile HotSpots network consists of thousands of Wi-Fi access points installed in businesses, hotels, and airports throughout the U.S.\n\nThe T-Mobile HotSpot service offers access to a nationwide network of approximately 8,350 access points, installed in venues such as [[Starbucks]] coffeehouses, [[FedEx Office]] Office and Print Centers, [[Hyatt]] hotels and resorts, [[Red Roof Inns]], [[Sofitel]] hotels, [[Novotel]] hotels, the airline clubs of [[American Airlines]], [[Delta Air Lines]] and [[United Airlines]], as well as airports.<ref>[https://selfcare.hotspot.t-mobile.com/locations/viewLocationMap.do \"T-Mobile HotSpot Location\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130312063201/https://selfcare.hotspot.t-mobile.com/locations/viewLocationMap.do |date=March 12, 2013 }}.  t-mobile.com.</ref>\n\nThe T-Mobile HotSpots network can be traced to the company's 2002 purchase of bankrupt wireless [[ISP]] [[MobileStar]], which began building its network in 1998. After completing the purchase, the company expanded the network into 400 [[Borders Group|Borders]] bookstores, as well as 100 of the most-frequented airport clubs and lounges operated by American Airlines, Delta Air Lines, and United Airlines.<ref>[http://www.news.com/2100-1033-275664.html \"MobileStar Network Back On\"]. [[News.com]].</ref><ref>[http://www.t-mobile.com/Company/CompanyInfo.aspx?tp=Abt_Tab_CompanyOverview&tsp=Abt_Sub_History \"Company History\"].  t-mobile.com.</ref>\n\nOn September 14, 2014, T-Mobile partnered up with GoGo to provide free texting on airplanes for its customers. GoGo services are provided on Delta Airlines, American Airlines, United Airlines and Alaska Airlines.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://topmobiletrends.com/gogowifi-free-texting-t-mobile-users|title=GoGoWiFi: Free Texting For T-Mobile Users|author=Top Mobile Trends | publisher=Top Mobile Trends|date=September 6, 2014| access-date=July 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn June 6, 2016, T-Mobile expanded its partnership with GoGo to offer T-Mobile users one hour of free WiFi on customers phones while T-Mobile One Plus and One Plus International users also get free WiFi throughout the entire flight. T-Mobile also included other messaging apps (iMessage, Google Hangouts, WhatsApp and Viber) in addition to SMS texting being provided since September 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newsroom.t-mobile.com/news-and-blogs/un-carrier-11.htm|title=UnCarrier 11|author=T-Mobile|date=June 6, 2016| access-date=August 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Wi-Fi network (private)====\nT-Mobile has also used the term to describe Wi-Fi Access Points that it sold to end users to expand their cell phone network to phones equipped to also receive Wi-Fi using a [[VOIP]]-like technology.  (The models included at least two by [[Linksys]]: the WRTU54G-TM and the WRT54G-TM and one by [[D-Link]]: the TM-G5240.)\n\n== Finances ==\nFor the fiscal year 2017, T-Mobile US reported earnings of US$4.481 billion, with an annual revenue of US$40.604 billion, an increase of 8.3% over the previous fiscal cycle. T-Mobile's shares traded at over $62 per share, and its market capitalization was valued at over US$58.1 billion in November 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.annualreports.com/Company/t-mobile|title=T-Mobile - AnnualReports.com|website=www.annualreports.com|access-date=December 3, 2018}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable float-left\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n!Year\n!Revenue<br />in mil. USD$\n!Net income<br />in mil. USD$\n!Total Assets<br />in mil. USD$\n!Price per Share<br />in USD$\n!Employees\n|-\n|2011\n|20,618\n|\u22124,718\n|9,483\n|17.40\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|19,719\n|\u22127,336\n|33,622\n|12.10\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|24,420\n|35\n|49,953\n|21.14\n|40,000\n|-\n|2014\n|29,564\n|247\n|56,653\n|30.59\n|45,000\n|-\n|2015\n|32,467\n| 678\n|62,413\n|36.45\n|50,000\n|-\n|2016\n|37,490\n|1,405\n|65,891\n|44.29\n|50,000\n|-\n|2017\n|40,604\n|4,481\n|70,563\n|62.59\n|51,000\n|}\n\n==Products and services==\n\n===Magenta & Magenta Plus===\n\nOn June 2, 2019 T-Mobile announced the launch of Magenta and Magenta Plus plans to phase out and replace the T-Mobile ONE family of plans. The Magenta family of plans build on the existing features of the T-Mobile ONE and ONE Plus plans, but now include additional features like 3GB of Mobile HotSpot Data for standard Magenta plans, and retaining the same enhanced HD Streaming, 20GB of Mobile HotSpot Data, and other features of the T-Mobile ONE Plus plans.<ref>https://www.t-mobile.com/cell-phone-plans/magenta</ref>\n\n===Military, First Responder, and Unlimited 55+===\n\nAlongside the T-Mobile Magenta family of plans are the specialized plans offered to Military personnel, First Responders, and seniors age 55 and up.\n\nMilitary and First Responder plans allow for qualified service members to receive 50% off of standard pricing Magenta and Magenta Plus plans. Customers must verify their affiliation within 45 days of activation or switching to the plan in order to retain the discounted offer.<ref>https://www.t-mobile.com/cell-phone-plans/military-discount-plans</ref><ref>https://www.t-mobile.com/cell-phone-plans/first-responder-discounts</ref>\n\nThe Unlimited 55+ allows customers at or over the age of 55 to receive a set discounted price on standard rate plans, however these accounts are limited to only 2 lines per account. Certain customers were permitted to add a third line to their account during a specific promotional period.<ref>https://www.t-mobile.com/cell-phone-plans/unlimited-55-senior-discount-plans</ref>\n\n===T-Mobile ONE w/ ONE Plus Family===\n\nIn August 2018, T-Mobile introduced T-Mobile ONE w/ ONE Plus Family plan, which allows HD streaming and adds 20 GB of mobile hotspot at 4G LTE speeds, and Name ID.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.t-mobile.com/cell-phone-plans | title=Cell Phone Plans &#124; Family Plans &#124; Compare Cell Phone Plans &#124; T-Mobile}}</ref>\n\n===T-Mobile ONE===\n\nIn August 2016, T-Mobile introduced T-Mobile ONE. It will be the only rate plan offered in the future, with plans to gradually phase out Simple Choice.<ref name=\"explore.t-mobile.com\">{{cite web|title=Frequently Asked Questions about T\u2011Mobile ONE|url=http://explore.t-mobile.com/t-mobile-one-faq}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=T-Mobile ONE Fact Sheet|url=http://newsroom.t-mobile.com/news-and-blogs/t-mobile-links/t-mobile-fact-sheet.htm}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=T-Mobile USA, Inc.|title=T-Mobile ONE|url=https://www.t-mobile.com/cell-phone-plans|accessdate=April 23, 2017}}</ref> The plan has been criticized by the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] and others for potentially violating [[net neutrality]] rules and making previously-included features paid extras.<ref>{{cite web|title=EFF says T-Mobile One seems to violate net neutrality|url=http://www.tmonews.com/2016/08/eff-t-mobile-one-violate-net-neutrality/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=T-Mobile's new 'unlimited' One plan is complete nonsense|url=https://thenextweb.com/opinion/2016/08/18/t-mobile-one-plan-complete-nonsense/|date=August 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=T-Mobile's New 'Unlimited' Plan Doesn't Sound Very Unlimited|url=https://gizmodo.com/t-mobiles-new-unlimited-plan-doesnt-sound-very-unlimite-1785452553}}</ref>\n\nAs of June 2, 2019, the T-Mobile ONE and ONE w/ ONE Plus Family plans have been retired and replaced by the new Magenta plans.<ref>https://www.tmonews.com/2019/05/t-mobile-one-magenta-plan-changes/</ref>\n\n===T-Mobile Essentials===\n\nThe T-Mobile Essentials plan provides customers Unlimited Talk, Text, and Data service at a lower price than a standard Magenta or Magenta Plus plan. However, the Essentials plan does not include taxes and fees as the Magenta and Magenta Plus plans do. It also allows T-Mobile to \"prioritize\" Essentials customers data usage on the network at any time during network congestion or peak times.<ref>https://www.t-mobile.com/cell-phone-plans/essentials</ref>\n\n===Netflix On US===\n\nT-Mobile offers any customer on a Magenta or Magenta Plus plan with 2 or more lines to participate in the Netflix on Us offer, essentially covering the cost of one standard Netflix subscription in the plan. Customers have the option to upgrade their subscription to Netflix's premium service for an additional cost, which will be added to the customer's T-Mobile bill.<ref>https://www.t-mobile.com/offers/netflix-on-us</ref>\n\n===Simple Choice===\nIn March 2013, T-Mobile introduced a new streamlined plan structure known as '''Simple Choice''' for new customers. This is part of an initiative called ''[[Un-carrier]]'' which drops contracts, subsidized phones, overage fees for data, and early termination fees.<ref name=nyt-uncarrier>{{cite news|title=T-Mobile Shakes Up Its Service|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/27/technology/t-mobile-unveils-aggressive-phone-pricing-with-no-contracts.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=April 20, 2013|first=Brian X.|last=Chen|date=March 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Capping unlimited data users===\nOn August 31, 2015, T-Mobile announced it will ask users who abuse its unlimited on-smartphone data plan by violating T-Mobile's Terms & Conditions regarding [[tethering]] (which like unlimited on-smartphone data, remains unlimited, but offers a 14 [[Gigabyte|GB]] high-speed allotment before throttling takes effect), by permanently removing user access to unlimited plans and migrating users to a tiered data plan. By doing so, all plans after a select amount of inclusive high-speed data, result in automatic throttled speeds, preventing unlimited high-speed tethering use and abuse of the network. T-Mobile stated that there are a small handful of users who abuse the tethering plan by altering device software and/or the use of an [[Android (operating system)|Android]] app that masks T-Mobile's ability monitoring whether data is on-smartphone, or through smartphone mobile hotspot (tethering) by mimicking all data as on-smartphone use, with some customers abusing the service by using as much as 2 [[Terabyte|TB]] per month, causing speed issues for all other customers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/8/31/9230595/t-mobile-unlimited-data-tethering-warning|title=T-Mobile will now punish customers who abuse unlimited data|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===InReach program===\nThe InReach program<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lifeline.t-mobile.com/|title=InReach Program at T-Mobile US|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140123043942/https://lifeline.t-mobile.com/|archivedate=January 23, 2014}}</ref> provides a free cell phone and a limited number of voice minutes each month for [[low-income]]-eligible families (one per family) who do not use Lifeline services offered by any other phone or wireless company.  It is funded through the [[Universal Service Fund]],<ref>[http://www.lifelinesupport.org/ Universal Service Administrative Company], About Lifeline</ref> but is only operational in a limited number of states and [[Puerto Rico]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110903041653/http://www.t-mobilepr.com/servicios_lifeline.php InReach Program in T-Mobile Puerto Rico]</ref>\n\n===Metro by T-Mobile===\n{{main|Metro by T-Mobile}}\nThe former MetroPCS was taken over by T-Mobile in 2013, the new company formed T-Mobile US and currently continues to offer [[prepaid mobile phone|prepaid]] wireless services under the Metro by T-Mobile brand.\n\n===GoSmart Mobile===\nGoSmart Mobile was a T-Mobile branded service that launched in [[betaware|beta]] on December 7, 2012, and became officially available nationwide on February 19, 2013. GoSmart offered no-contract SIM wireless services. GoSmart Mobile was sold to consumers through dealers who worked as independent contractors under their own company name. Such sellers are known as \"Authorized Dealers\" with either physical or online stores. In September 2016, T-Mobile sold the brand and 326,000 GoSmart Mobile customers to [[TracFone Wireless]].<ref>[http://www.tmonews.com/2016/10/t-mobile-sells-walmart-family-mobile-tracfone/ \"T-Mobile sells Walmart Family Mobile to TracFone\"], ''TmoNews'', October 5, 2016</ref> The customers were reclassified as wholesale subscribers.<ref>[http://investor.t-mobile.com/Cache/1001215618.PDF?O=PDF&T=&Y=&D=&FID=1001215618&iid=4091145 \"Investor Factbook\"], ''T-Mobile USA, Inc'', 2016-10</ref>\n\n===Banking cards===\n\nOn January 22, 2014, T-Mobile announced that it would expand its products into banking. T-Mobile would provide Visa card with banking features and a smartphone money management application with reduced-fee or zero-cost services for T-Mobile wireless customers. In addition, customers would have access to over 42,000 ATMs with no fees.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/01/22/us-tmobile-banking-idUSBREA0L1BR20140122|accessdate=January 23, 2014|newspaper=Reuters|date=January 22, 2014|first=Sinead|last=Carew|title=T-Mobile US says to expand into banking cards}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2016 T-mobile decided to discontinue the banking cards. They can no longer be purchased at T-Mobile.\n\nIn early 2019 T-mobile released T-mobile Money, an online banking option.\n\n=== TVision Home ===\nOn December 13, 2017, T-Mobile US announced its intent to acquire the [[IPTV]] provider Layer3 TV, which operates in Chicago and Washington, as the basis of its own subscription television service initially planned to launch in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/12/13/t-mobile-plans-pay-tv-service-in-2018-field-by-layer3-acquisition/|title=T-Mobile plans pay-TV service in 2018 fueled by Layer3 TV acquisition|last=Etherington|first=Darrell|work=TechCrunch|access-date=December 13, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-12-13/t-mobile-agrees-to-buy-layer3-in-preparation-for-new-tv-service|title=T-Mobile to Buy Layer3 TV in Preparation for Video Service|date=December 13, 2017|work=Bloomberg News|access-date=December 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=T-Mobile completes purchase of Denver's Layer3 TV, plans to offer TV service to all \u2014 including AT&T and Verizon customers|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2018/01/23/t-mobile-layer-3-att-verizon-tv-service/|publisher=[[The Denver Post]]|accessdate=January 24, 2018|date=January 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=T-Mobile completes Layer3 acquisition, on track to launch new TV service this year|url=https://www.geekwire.com/2018/t-mobile-completes-layer3-acquisition-track-launch-new-tv-service-year/|publisher= Geek Wire|accessdate=January 24, 2018|date=January 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=T-Mobile TV service nears as Uncarrier closes Layer3 acquisition|url=https://www.slashgear.com/t-mobile-tv-service-nears-as-uncarrier-closes-layer3-acquisition-23516841/|publisher= Slash Gear|accessdate=January 24, 2018|date=January 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn April 10, 2019, T-Mobile officially announced the re-branding and re-launch of Layer3 TV as '''TVision Home'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/4/10/18304455/tmobile-layer3-tvision-home-tv-cable-service-announced|title=T-Mobile relaunches Layer3 TV service as TVision Home|last=Welch|first=Chris|date=April 10, 2019|website=The Verge|access-date=April 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe service has been criticized for mirroring the hardware, packaging, and pricing models of other linear television providers, with no meaningful differentiation in services or disruptive pricing models like T-Mobile's wireless services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2019/04/10/t-mobiles-tvision-home-here-but-looks-lot-like-regular-cable/3415988002/|title=T-Mobile's new TVision Home service goes after cable TV, but doesn't look much different|website=USA Today|language=en|access-date=April 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20190410/07465741969/t-mobiles-revolutionary-new-tv-service-looks-like-same-old-crap.shtml|title=T-Mobile's 'Revolutionary' New TV Service Looks Like The Same Old Crap|last=Mon|first=April 15, 2019 1:36pm-Karl Bode|website=Techdirt.|access-date=April 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Customer service==\n[[File:T-Mobile Store in Hartford, CT.jpg|thumb|T-Mobile Store in Hartford, Connecticut]]\n\n===Team of experts===\n\nIn 2018, T-Mobile officially announced its new customer care concept called Team of Experts. The premise being customers never being transferred to another department. All representatives are trained billing, payment arrangements, and cancellations when in the past each had their own separate department. In addition to being cross-trained, the Team of Experts, which consists of usually between 30 and 35 account reps, 4 to 6 technical support representatives, 4 supervisors overseeing the representatives, and one manager, are assigned specific markets, usually within the region, the call center is in.<ref>{{cite web |title=T-Mobile Customer Care |url=https://www.t-mobile.com/customers/customer-care |website=t-mobile.com}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\nFrom as early as 2004, the company has captured multiple [[J. D. Power and Associates|J. D. Power]] annual awards in the areas of retail sales satisfaction, wireless customer care, and overall customer satisfaction.<ref name=overview2011 /> In 2011, J. D. Power and Associates stated that T-Mobile retail stores achieved the highest ratings among major wireless carriers for customer satisfaction for the fourth consecutive year, performing particularly well in price and promotions.<ref name=jdp_retailsatisfaction_2011>{{cite press release |title=J.D. Power and Associates Reports: Spending Sufficient Time Explaining Mobile Device Operation Is Critical to Higher Satisfaction with the Wireless Retail Sales Process |publisher=J.D. Power and Associates, The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc |date=February 17, 2011 |url=http://businesscenter.jdpower.com/news/pressrelease.aspx?ID=2011016 |accessdate=April 28, 2011 |archivedate=April 28, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yHs6QD31?url=http://businesscenter.jdpower.com/news/pressrelease.aspx?ID=2011016 |quote=T-Mobile ranks highest in customer satisfaction among major wireless carrier-owned retail stores for a fourth consecutive time with a score of 739, performing particularly well in price and promotions, such as the competitiveness of service plans and devices offered. |url-status=dead }}</ref> Also in 2011, J. D. Power and Associates ranked T-Mobile USA highest among major providers in wireless customer care for the second consecutive year.<ref name=jdp_customercare_2011>{{cite press release |title=J.D. Power and Associates Reports: Interaction with Agents May Significantly Elevate Satisfaction with the Wireless Customer Care Experience |publisher=J.D. Power and Associates, The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc |date=February 3, 2011 |url=http://businesscenter.jdpower.com/news/pressrelease.aspx?ID=2011010 |accessdate=April 28, 2011 |archivedate=April 28, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yHt1Hl5a?url=http://businesscenter.jdpower.com/news/pressrelease.aspx?ID=2011010 |quote=T-Mobile ranks highest in wireless customer care performance for a second consecutive time with an overall score of 758. T-Mobile USA performs particularly well in phone contacts that originate in the ARS channel and are then transferred to a live service representative, and through phone calls made directly to a CSR. |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn December 3, 2015, [[Consumer Reports]] named T-Mobile the number one American wireless service provider. The results combine data from customer service, voice quality, text messaging services, and data speeds.<ref name=\"money.cnn.com\"/>\n\nOn February 6, 2016, T-Mobile was awarded the JD Power Award for customer satisfaction in the full-service wireless category for the second year in a row. T-Mobile received the highest score ever in the wireless industry.<ref>{{cite web|title=2016 Wireless Awards Press Release|url=http://www.jdpower.com/press-releases/2016-us-wireless-customer-care-fs-nc-performance-studies-vol-1|website=JDPower.com|date=January 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, T-Mobile was recognized as one of Fortune's Top 100 Companies To Work For, ranking #49.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.t-mobile.com/news/fortune-best-companies-list|title=Keeping It 100: What Made T-Mobile One of Fortune's Best Companies to Work For|website=www.t-mobile.com|language=en|access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Outages===\n\n====Sidekick data outage====\n{{Main|Microsoft data loss 2009}}\nOn October 1, 2009, some users of Microsoft's Sidekick handset temporarily lost personal data, including contacts, notes, and calendars. On October 8, most data services were restored to users.  The company and [[Microsoft]] announced on October 10 that Sidekick device data \"almost certainly has been lost as a result of a server failure at Microsoft/Danger.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2009/10/10/t-mobile-we-probably-lost-all-your-sidekick-data/ |title=T-Mobile: we probably lost all your Sidekick data |publisher=Engadget |date= |accessdate=September 20, 2012}}</ref> On October 15, Microsoft said it had been able to recover most or all data and would begin to restore it.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20091015-710685.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091227071928/http://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20091015-710685.html |archivedate=December 27, 2009 |title=Update: Microsoft Says It Has Recovered Lost Sidekick Data |work =[[The Wall Street Journal]]  |date=October 15, 2009 |accessdate=October 15, 2009}}</ref><ref name=bbc_sidekick>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/8309218.stm |title=Microsoft Recovers Sidekick Data |publisher=BBC News |date=October 15, 2009 |accessdate=October 15, 2009 |quote=Microsoft says it has now recovered the personal data lost when its Sidekick servers suffered an outage on 13 October.}}</ref> A few weeks later, all Sidekick customers were able to recover their data via Danger's sync website using a restore file or had the option to wait until data was restored to the device itself.\n\n====Network outages====\nOn November 9, 2009, some of the company's subscribers temporarily lost the ability to send and receive [[Telephone call|call]]s and text messages for several hours.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fried |first=Ina |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-1035_3-10390097-94.html |title=T-Mobile experiencing widespread outage &#124; Mobile \u2013 CNET News |publisher=News.cnet.com |date=November 3, 2009 |accessdate=September 20, 2012}}</ref> The company confirmed the outage via Twitter. The company stated that approximately five percent of its subscribers had been affected. It claimed that the problem was caused by a system software error.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/technologybrierdudleysblog/2010204191_t-mobile_says_software_glitch.html |newspaper=The Seattle Times |title=T-Mobile Says Software Glitch Jammed Network Tuesday | author = Dudley, Brier |date=November 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn February 13 and March 25, 2015, T-Mobile suffered LTE outages along the east coast causing users to lose data connections.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\nOn May 8, 2018, subscribers throughout [[Houston]], [[Texas]] experienced an approximately four-hour interruption in service caused by damage to a [[Optical fiber|fiber-optic cable]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amp.click2houston.com/news/what-caused-t-mobile-service-outage-in-houston|title=What caused T-Mobile's service outage in Houston?|website=amp.click2houston.com|access-date=May 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Marketing==\n[[File:Harmon Corner 2.jpg|thumb|A T-Mobile advertisement at [[Harmon Corner]] on the [[Las Vegas Strip]]]]\n[[Jamie Lee Curtis]] was the spokesperson for T-Mobile USA's predecessor, VoiceStream Wireless, since 1998. VoiceStream's advertising slogan was: \"Get more from life\". During the transition to the T-Mobile brand, Jamie Lee Curtis continued as a spokesperson for a short time and the slogan was changed to \"T-Mobile. Get More.\"\nStarting in 2002, the company's spokesperson was [[Catherine Zeta-Jones]] who was the main figure in its branding strategy. As of September 2006, Zeta-Jones had officially been dropped as the \"face\" of the company for its advertising campaigns due to a corporate rebranding strategy.<ref>[http://online.wsj.com/public/article/SB115923297434173806-MhwUTXKGBvVjSs_kJoPkTnTXM3Q_20061026.html?mod=tff_main_tff_top \"T-Mobile Readies New Web Phones&nbsp;\u2013 And Hangs Up on a Star Pitchwoman\"].  ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''</ref> The company also relied on rapper [[Snoop Dogg]] as the spokesperson for its [[Danger Hiptop|T-Mobile Sidekick]] in a series of commercials late in 2004, the company also released a series of Sidekick phones known as the D-Wade Edition for basketball player [[Dwyane Wade]].\n\nThe company is also an official sponsor of [[Major League Baseball]], the [[National Basketball Association]], the NBA [[Rookie Challenge]], [[Women's National Basketball Association]] and the [[Overwatch League]]\n\nIn 2009, it changed its approach to advertising and moved from the \"Get More\" slogan to a \"Stick Together\" slogan to focus more on the personal aspect of staying together with those who matter the most to its customers.{{Citation needed|date=September 2007}} The slogan was also meant to promote its MyFaves calling-circle plan. With this, the company also ended its relationship with Zeta-Jones, and now use mainly non-celebrity spokespeople (though Dwyane Wade, [[Charles Barkley]], and [[Dwight Howard]] are featured in some commercials, in association with the company's sponsorship of the NBA as official wireless provider).\n\nIn late May 2009, Zeta-Jones was brought back as a company spokesperson to show customers how to pay less for their wireless plan in a new \"Mobile Makeovers\" advertising campaign that refers a customer to third-party comparison site BillShrink.com.<ref>T-Mobile Press Release [http://www.t-mobile.com/company/PressReleases_Article.aspx?assetName=Prs_Prs_20090520&title=T-Mobile%20Aims%20to%20Help%20Wireless%20Customers%20Save%20Money%20by%20Offering%20%27Mobile%20Makeovers%27 \"T-Mobile Aims To Help Wireless Customers Save Money by Offering Mobile Makeovers\"].</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billshrink.com/ |title=BillShrink.com |publisher=BillShrink.com |date= |accessdate=September 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2009, commercials for the [[HTC Magic|T-Mobile MyTouch 3G]] featured the song \"[[If You Want to Sing Out, Sing Out]]\" by [[Cat Stevens]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://onmilwaukee.com/music/articles/tmobilemytouchsong.html|title=What the Heck Is the Song in That Commercial?| author = Olson, Drew|publisher = [[Onmilwaukee.com]] |date=October 19, 2009|accessdate=July 30, 2009}}</ref> and celebrities such as [[Chevy Chase]], [[Molly Shannon]], [[Dana Carvey]] and [[Darrell Hammond]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unitedmonkee.com/2009/10/snl-phone-commerical.html |title=Retrieved 2009-10-21 |publisher=Unitedmonkee.com |date=October 9, 2009 |accessdate=September 20, 2012}}</ref> Another commercial with the same song performed by a different artist showed [[Wyclef Jean]], [[Avril Lavigne]] and [[Brad Paisley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thelifefiles.com/2009/11/22/wyclef-jean-avril-lavigne-and-brad-paisley-star-in-t-mobiles-mytouch-commercial/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717011231/http://www.thelifefiles.com/2009/11/22/wyclef-jean-avril-lavigne-and-brad-paisley-star-in-t-mobiles-mytouch-commercial/|archivedate=July 17, 2011 |title=Wyclef Jean, Avril Lavigne And Brad Paisley Star In T-Mobile's \"myTouch\" Commercial! |publisher=Thelifefiles.com |date= |accessdate=September 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Carly Foulkes]] is the spokeswoman for the [[HTC Glacier|myTouch 4G]] in commercials that parody the [[Get a Mac]] campaign. The model is known for [[Rugby Ralph Lauren]] ads.<ref name=lat_carly>{{cite news |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/alltherage/2010/11/who-made-t-mobile-mytouch-4g-girls-pink-and-white-dress.html |title=Burning Questions: Just Who is T-Mobile's Stylish New 4G Girl, and Who Made That Pink-and-White Dress? |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] | author = Tschor, Adam |date=November 16, 2010|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/209667/tmobile_gets_tough_with_competitors_over_4g.html |title=T-Mobile Gets Tough With Competitors Over 4G|author1=Mello Jr. |author2=John P. |work= [[PC World (magazine)|PC World]] |date=November 3, 2010 |accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailytech.com/TMobile+Takes+ATT+and+iPhone+HeadOn+in+New+Ad/article20056.htm |title=T-Mobile Takes AT&T and iPhone Head-On in New Ad | author = Kurlyandchik, Mark |publisher= [[Daily Tech]] |date=November 3, 2010 |accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\nAlthough Foulkes is often identified with the color pink, T-Mobile actually has a color trademark for the color [[magenta]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/319824/t+mobile-owns-magenta|title=T-Mobile Owns Magenta|accessdate=November 20, 2011|date=November 7, 2007|work=[[Gizmodo]]|author=Wilson, Mark}}</ref> and markets itself using its corporate colors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tmonews.com/2011/11/its-tmobiles-magenta-saturday-sale-are-you-shopping/|title=It's T-Mobile's \"Magenta Saturday\" Sale, Are You Shopping?|accessdate=November 20, 2011|date=November 19, 2011|work=TMoNews}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/t-mobile-to-hold-magenta-saturday-sale-with-smartphones-and-tablets-for-as-little-as-0-4999-net-down-2011-11-15 |title=T-Mobile to Hold \"Magenta Saturday\" Sale With Smartphones and Tablets for as Little as $0--$49.99 Net Down: On Nov. 19, T-Mobile will help holiday shoppers escape the dark lines of Black Friday and help them step up to data and the smartphone revolution with minimal upfront cost. |accessdate=November 20, 2011 |date=November 15, 2011 |work=[[Market Watch]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102033550/http://www.marketwatch.com/story/t-mobile-to-hold-magenta-saturday-sale-with-smartphones-and-tablets-for-as-little-as-0-4999-net-down-2011-11-15 |archivedate=November 2, 2013 }}</ref>\n[[Virgin Mobile]] has, in turn, parodied the Carly Foulkes ads.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/virgin-mobile-mocks-t-mobiles-carly-spokeswoman-161155591.html|title=Virgin Mobile Mocks T-Mobile's 'Carly' Spokeswoman|last=Yin|first=Sara|work=[[PC Magazine]]|publisher=Yahoo News|date=August 8, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2010, the company launched \"Kids are free till 2012\" for family lines.\n\nOn December 1, 2011, a group of 100 Chicago-area women, along with [[Carly Foulkes]], were featured in a flash-mob style performance at [[Woodfield Mall]] in [[Schaumburg, Illinois]], where the group, dressed in magenta dresses, sang and danced through the mall's atrium to their cover of [[(There's No Place Like) Home for the Holidays]]. The performance was filmed and edited into a holiday commercial, which was a success.\n\n===Un-carrier movement===\nStarting in 2013, T-Mobile launched the [[Un-carrier]] marketing campaign. This movement introduced a slew of new tactics to offer consumers cheaper rate plans, cheaper global coverage, and several other benefits. T-Mobile CEO John Legere laid out an 'Un-Carrier manifesto' highlighting the approach and goals he wanted the company to pursue. One popular Un-carrier move features T-Mobile Tuesdays, where customers are offered a variety of free products and also able to win prizes.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mills|first1=Chris|title=T-Mobile is giving away tons of free stuff, here's how to get it|url=http://bgr.com/2016/06/06/t-mobile-tuesdays-rewards-how-to-download/|website=BGR|publisher=BGR Media, LLC|accessdate=June 27, 2016|date=June 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=T-Mobile Tuesdays - Customer Appreciation - Get Free Products & More | url=https://explore.t-mobile.com/t-mobile-tuesdays?icid=WMM_TM_UNCRRR11_3A0N090NAEH5110}}</ref> The most recent Un-carrier campaign is titled 'T-Mobile One'. This is a new family plan offering, replacing all previous plans and is an all-inclusive unlimited plan, giving unlimited talk, text, and data. The only caveat being a video streaming on any device is limited to 480p resolution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://explore.t-mobile.com/t-mobile-one|title=T-Mobile One {{!}} One Price Unlimited Phone & Data Plans for Everyone|website=explore.t-mobile.com|access-date=October 8, 2016}}</ref> CEO John Legere in an interview said \"The biggest pain point that a million customers told me about is that they hate data buckets. And we had such success with Binge On that we wanted to turn our company into somebody that's selling a monthly subscription to the internet, all in, unlimited.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/t-mobile-ceo-calls-competition-123000823.html|title=The T-Mobile CEO who calls his competition \u2018dumb and dumber\u2019 explains how he doubled customers in 4 years, and how a group of employees made him cry|access-date=October 8, 2016}}</ref> As of October 7, 2016, about a quarter of the overall account numbers have moved over to T-Mobile One, and about three-quarters of new postpaid accounts are activating on T-Mobile One.\n\n==Labor relations==\nT-Mobile US employees and two labor unions have led multiple unionization attempts beginning as early as 2001.\n\n===Formation of TU===\nHundreds of T-Mobile employees, with the backing of the [[Communications Workers of America]] (CWA) and the German union [[ver.di]], have joined together as [[TU (union)|TU]] to gain representation at T-Mobile.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tmobileworkersunited.org/about-us/ |title=About Us |publisher=Tmobile Workers United |date=August 13, 2013 |accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref> In July 2011, technicians in Connecticut, voted for representation by the Communications Workers of America-TU.<ref name=2009_tmo_response>{{cite web |url=http://www.cwa-union.org/news/entry/t-mobile_workers_win_union_voice_in_connecticut#.UkClKdK-opN |title=T-Mobile Workers Win Union Voice in Connecticut |date=July 19, 2011}}</ref> On September 25, 2013, MetroPCS workers in Harlem, NY, voted for a union voice and representation by CWA-TU.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.cwa-union.org/news/entry/new_york_city_metropcs_workers_vote_to_join_cwa |title=New York City MetroPCS Workers Vote to Join CWA &#124; Communications Workers of America |publisher=Cwa-union.org |date=September 26, 2013 |accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2009 coordinated organizing effort===\n[[File:Cohen and disguised worker at press conference 2010.09.22.jpg|thumb|right|CWA President Larry Cohen and a disguised, unidentified T-Mobile USA employee pictured at a 2009 press conference announcing a coordinated unionizing effort]]\nIn 2008, the CWA and ver.di launched a coordinated effort to unionize company employees. A spokesman for the CWA called on the company to stop resisting mobilization efforts and allow company employees to unionize as German employees of T-Mobile USA's parent company, DT, have done. In response, the company released an employee satisfaction study showing that more than seventy percent of the company's 40,000 workers were \"very satisfied\" with their jobs. Through a spokesman, the company stated, \"Despite the Communication Workers of America's periodic organizing efforts for more than nine years, no group of T-Mobile employees has ever chosen to be represented by a union. While our company is always striving to find ways to improve, year after year, employees continue to view T-Mobile as a good place to work where they have no need for, or interest in, a union.\"<ref name=2009_tmo_response/>\n\n====Political pressure====\nIn 2009, a number of politicians, in one case acting after lobbying efforts by CWA union activists, wrote letters to [[Ren\u00e9 Obermann]], DT's chief executive officer, in an effort to influence T-Mobile USA's labor practices in the U.S.<ref name=cwaactivists>{{cite web |url=http://www.cwa-union.org/news/entry/House_Members_Urge_Deutsche_Telekom_to_Respect_U.S._Workers_Rights |title=House Members Urge Deutsche Telekom To Respect U.S. Workers' Rights |date=May 6, 2010 |publisher=[[Communications Workers of America]], AFL-CIO, CLC  |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yH0Ro4lM?url=http://www.cwa-union.org/news/entry/House_Members_Urge_Deutsche_Telekom_to_Respect_U.S._Workers_Rights |archivedate=April 28, 2011 |accessdate=April 28, 2011 |quote=Hard work by CWA activists was key to getting 26 Democratic members of the House Education and Labor Committee to sign on to a letter calling on Deutsche Telekom...}}</ref>\n\nIn a March 13, 2009, letter, U.S. Senator [[John Kerry]] (D-MA) asked \"why the company's approach to labor rights are different in Germany than in the United States\". In an April 30, 2010, letter sent after lobbying by Communications Workers of America activists, 26 Democratic members of Congress called on DT to protect and respect workers' rights in the U.S.<ref name=cwaactivists /> A separate July 1, 2010, letter from seven Republicans addressed the same issue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thelocal.de/national/20100504-26971.html |title=US government calls out Deutsche Telekom over union busting \u2013 The Local |publisher=Thelocal.de |date= May 4, 2010|accessdate=September 20, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=realtmobile |url=http://www.dailykos.com/storyonly/2010/7/14/884032/-Life-is-More-Fun-When-You-are-Organized! |title=Life is More Fun When You are Organized! |publisher=Daily Kos |date=July 14, 2010 |accessdate=September 20, 2012}}</ref> On August 10, 2010, U.S. Senator [[Bob Casey, Jr.|Bob Casey]] (D-PA) released a statement in support of the worker's efforts to organize a union at the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.loweringthebarforus.org/news/entry/U.S._Senator_Bob_Caseys_Statement_Supporting_T-Mobile_workers |title=We Work Better Together |publisher=Loweringthebarforus.org |date=July 14, 2010 |accessdate=May 15, 2012}}</ref> In a letter, dated September 21, 2010, fifteen Californian [[Members of Congress]] urged Obermann to take action and implement fair and equitable [[labor relations]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}\n\nIn a November 5, 2009, letter, [[Thomas DiNapoli]], [[New York State Comptroller]] and Trustee of the [[New York State Common Retirement Fund]], stated concerns about \"the potential impact on the value of T-Mobile that may result from a disenfranchised workforce and the associated negative publicity that may impact T-Mobile's profitability.\"{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}\n\n===Reports===\n[[File:Lowering The Bar Cover 2010.09.22.jpg|thumb|right|A Cover image of a report written by John Logan and published in 2009 by [[American Rights at Work]]]]\nOn December 9, 2009, the non-profit organization [[American Rights at Work]] published a report written by Prof. John Logan, Director of Labor Studies at [[San Francisco State University]], titled [https://web.archive.org/web/20100717142730/http://www.americanrightsatwork.org/dmdocuments/ARAWReports/loweringthebar_lowres.pdf \"Lowering the Bar or Setting the Standard? Deutsche Telekom's U.S. Labor Practices\"]. The report details behavior by the company that the author perceives as anti-union including dissemination of anti-union materials, intimidation and threats directed at pro-union workers, \"[[captive audience meetings]]\" and the retention of anti-union specialists.<ref>Logan, John. [https://web.archive.org/web/20100610010611/http://www.americanrightsatwork.org/publications/general/lowering-the-bar-or-setting-the-standard-20091209-853-116.html \"Lowering the Bar or Setting the Standard. Deutsche Telekom's U.S. Labor Practices\"]. Washington, D.C.: [[American Rights at Work]] Education Fund, 2009</ref> In the report, which is based on documents from the [[National Labor Relations Board]], internal company memos and handbooks, and interviews with workers, Logan asserts that the company engaged in a systematic campaign to prevent employees from forming a union and that DT was guilty of operating by a double standard. He claims that Deutsche Telekom respects workers' rights in Germany, where it cooperates closely with unions, but mistreats workers in the United States and interferes with their right to organize.{{clarify|date=July 2011|reason=where does quotation start?}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanrightsatwork.org/press-center/2009-press-releases/new-report-exposes-labor-relations-double-standard-at-t-mobile-usa-20091209-854-374-374.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110506214611/http://www.americanrightsatwork.org/press-center/2009-press-releases/new-report-exposes-labor-relations-double-standard-at-t-mobile-usa-20091209-854-374-374.html|archivedate=May 6, 2011 |title=New Report Exposes Labor Relations Double Standard at T-Mobile USA |publisher=American Rights at Work |date=December 9, 2009 |accessdate=September 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn September 2, 2010, [[Human Rights Watch]] released a report written by Lance Compa titled \"[https://www.hrw.org/node/92719 A Strange Case: Violations of Workers' Freedom of Association in the United States by European Multinational Corporations]\". The report concludes that \"company policy has translated into practices that leave the workforce fearful about even seeking union representation.\"<ref>Compa, Lance. [https://www.hrw.org/en/reports/2010/09/02/strange-case-0 \"A Strange Case: Violations of Workers' Freedom of Association in the United States by European Multinational Corporations\"].  New York: [[Human Rights Watch]], 2010. [https://www.hrw.org/en/node/92718/section/6 page 35]</ref> DT proclaims its adherence to international labor law and standards that are embodied in German domestic laws. But HRW found that \"T-Mobile USA's harsh opposition to workers' freedom of association in the United States betrays Deutsche Telekom's purported commitment to social responsibility, impedes constructive dialogue with employee representatives, and in several cases, has violated [[ILO]] and [[OECD]] labor and human rights standards\".<ref>Compa, Lance.  [https://www.hrw.org/en/reports/2010/09/02/strange-case-0 \"A Strange Case: Violations of Workers' Freedom of Association in the United States by European Multinational Corporations\"]. New York: [[Human Rights Watch]], 2010.</ref>\n\n===Workplace activities===\nAt the company's [[Allentown, Pennsylvania]], call center, security guards were ordered by company managers to write up incident reports whenever union supporters appeared on nearby public grounds and to record the license plate numbers of employees who stopped to take leaflets. In 2006, the [[National Labor Relations Board]] found that these activities violated Section 8(a)(1) of the [[National Labor Relations Act]].<ref>Letter to CWA counsel of Dorothy L. Moore-Duncan, Regional Director, NLRB Region 4, T-Mobile, Case No. 4-CA 34590, June 30, 2006, copy on file with Human Rights Watch</ref>\n\nIn 2008, company management in the Pacific Northwest and Southwest Retail Divisions sent a memorandum to store managers instructing them to immediately report any union activity to their supervisors.<ref>E-mail memorandum from Divisional Human Resources Manager, Pacific Northwest, and Southwest Retail Divisions, to T-Mobile managers, May 30, 2008, copy on file with Human Rights Watch</ref> Human Rights Watch states, \"The NLRB has long held that such activity interferes with, restrains, and coerces employees in the exercise of Section 7 rights in violation of workers' right to freedom of association.\"<ref>See, for example, Arcata Graphics, 304 NLRB 541 (1991); Nashville Plastic Products, 313 NLRB 462 (1993); Ryder Truck Rental, Inc,341 NLRB No. 109 (2004).</ref>\n\n===Awards===\nT-Mobile has received multiple workplace awards. T-Mobile received a score of 100 on the Disability Equality Index (DEI), which measures disability inclusion. They were also named the Best Place to Work for LGBT Equality by the Human Rights Campaign for four consecutive years. T-Mobile was also awarded a Designation for the top 100 Military Friendly Employer by Military Friendly in 2017 for the tenth time. It was recognized as one of the World's Most Ethical Companies by the [[Ethisphere Institute]] for the ninth year in a row. In addition to national awards, T-Mobile has also won local awards in many locations, including the best place to work in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]] and [[Wichita, Kansas]] where the company has call centers located.<ref>{{cite web|title=Company Information-Awards and Recognition|url=https://www.t-mobile.com/company/company-info/awards.html|website=T-Mobile.com}}</ref> On February 16, 2018 [[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] announced their 100 best companies to work for, naming T-Mobile 86th.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fortune 100 Best Companies to Work For 2018|url=https://www.greatplacetowork.com/best-workplaces/100-best/2018|website=GreatPlacetoWork.com}}</ref> On July 24, 2018, [[Forbes.com|Forbes]] ranked T-Mobile 182nd on their top 300 Best Places to Work for Women list.<ref>{{cite web |title=America's Best Employers For Women 2018 |url=https://www.forbes.com/best-employers-for-women/list/ |website=Forbes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Information security==\nNicolas Jacobsen was charged with intruding into the company's internal network in January 2005.<ref>{{cite web|first=Kevin|last=Poulsen |url=http://www.securityfocus.com/news/10271 |title=Hacker penetrates T-Mobile systems |publisher=Securityfocus.com |date=January 11, 2005 |accessdate=September 20, 2012}}</ref> Reports indicated that for about a year Jacobsen had access to customer passwords, e-mail, address books, [[Social Security number]]s, birth dates, and [[Danger Hiptop|Sidekick]] photos. Affected customers included members of the [[United States Secret Service]]. Secret Service informant identified Jacobsen as part of [https://web.archive.org/web/20080916201228/http://www.ustreas.gov/usss/press/pub2304.pdf \"Operation Firewall\"] which provided evidence that Jacobsen had attempted to sell customer information to others for identity theft. T-Mobile USA and the Secret Service did not elaborate on the methods Jacobsen used to gain access but sources close to the case indicated that Jacobsen exploited an unpatched flaw in the [[Oracle Weblogic Server|Oracle WebLogic Server]] application software used by the company.<ref>{{cite news|first=Kevin|last=Poulsen |url=https://www.wired.com/politics/security/news/2005/02/66735 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080607062210/http://www.wired.com/politics/security/news/2005/02/66735 |archivedate=June 7, 2008 |title=Known Hole Aided T-Mobile Breach |publisher=Wired.com |accessdate=September 20, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Additional [[SQL injection]] vulnerabilities with the company's web site were reported by Jack Koziol of the InfoSec Institute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/id,119851-page,1/article.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403054602/http://www.pcworld.com/article/id,119851-page,1/article.html |archivedate=April 3, 2008 |title=PC World \u2013 Paris Hilton: Victim of T-Mobile's Web Flaws? |date=April 3, 2008 |accessdate=September 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nT-Mobile offers access to voicemail without the input of a password by default. Parties acting in bad faith may be able to access such voice mailboxes via [[Caller ID spoofing]]. To avoid this possibility, T-Mobile recommends that all customers password-protect their mailboxes, but still offers the no password configuration by default due to customer demand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://support.t-mobile.com/knowbase/root/public/tm21077.htm?WT.srch=2&Result_Inq=answer&InqSource=TMO|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060509183751/http://support.t-mobile.com/knowbase/root/public/tm21077.htm?WT.srch=2&Result_Inq=answer&InqSource=TMO|archivedate=May 9, 2006 |title=Support: T-Mobile Voicemail Security Features |publisher=Support.t-mobile.com |date= |accessdate=September 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn June 6, 2009, a message posted from an email account \"pwnmobile_at_Safe-mail.net\" to the Full Disclosure mailing list claimed that the company's network had been breached and showed sample data. The sender offered \"databases, confidential documents, scripts and programs from their servers, financial documents up to 2009\" to the highest bidder.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lists.grok.org.uk/full-disclosure-charter.html |title=[Full-Disclosure&#93; Mailing List Charter |publisher=Lists.grok.org.uk |date= |accessdate=May 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>Full Disclosure mailing list [http://seclists.org/fulldisclosure/2009/Jun/0062.html \"T-Mobile USA Sources and Data\"].</ref> On June 9, the company issued a statement confirming the breach but stating that customer data was safe. It claimed to have identified the source document for the sample data and believe it was not obtained by hacking.<ref>Prince, Brian (June 9, 2009).  [http://www.eweek.com/c/a/Security/TMobile-Confirms-Breach-But-Says-Customers-Safe-507228/ \"T-Mobile Confirms Breach, But Says Customers Safe\"].  ''[[eWeek]]''.  Retrieved 2011-07-30.</ref> A later statement claimed that there was not any evidence of a breach.<ref>[https://www.pcworld.com/article/166395/tmobile_data_was_not_taken_by_hacking_company_says.html \"T-Mobile Data Was Not Taken by Hacking, Company Says\"]. ''[[PC World (magazine)|PC World]]''.</ref>\n\n==Privacy and surveillance==\nT-Mobile USA received a portion of the 1.3 million largely warrantless law enforcement requests for subscriber information (including text messages and phone location data) made in 2011, but refused to state how many requests it received.<ref name=\"Wired-massive-surveillance\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/threatlevel/2012/07/massive-phone-surveillance/|title=Mobile-Phone Surveillance by Police Targets Millions Annually|last=Kravets|first=David|publisher=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|accessdate=September 28, 2012|date=July 9, 2011}}</ref> It did say that in the last decade, the number of requests have increased by 12 to 16 percent annually.<ref name=\"Register-snooping\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2012/07/09/markey_wireless_snooping/|title=US law enforcement phone snooping on the rise|first=Neil|last=McAllister|publisher=The Register}}</ref>\n\n===Data retention policies===\n\nAccording to T-Mobile's privacy policy highlights, \"Retention and Disposal\", information is retained for as long as there is business or tax need or as applicable laws, regulations, or government orders require. T-Mobile notes that it disposes of Personal Information,  uses reasonable procedures designed to erase or render it unreadable (for example, shredding documents and wiping electronic media).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.t-mobile.com/company/website/privacypolicy.aspx|title=Privacy Policy & Personal Information - T-Mobile|website=www.t-mobile.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, the Department of Justice (DOJ) released a document entitled, \"Retention Periods of Major Cellular Providers,\" to advise law enforcement agents seeking to obtain cell phone records. This document was uncovered by the ACLU's coordinated records request on cell phone location tracking by police. Notably, the document showed that T-Mobile subscriber information was retained for 5 years and call detail records were kept for 2 years (prepaid) and 5 years (postpaid).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aclu.org/cell-phone-location-tracking-request-response-cell-phone-company-data-retention-chart|title=Cell Phone Location Tracking Request Response \u2013 Cell Phone Company Data Retention Chart|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Massachusetts Sen. [[Edward Markey]] revealed responses from the top four U.S. wireless providers as well as U.S. Cellular, C Spire, and Cricket/Leap Wireless, to his inquiry regarding user information disclosed to law enforcement officials. The following was T-Mobile's response regarding data retention: T-Mobile US retains customers' historic cell site information and cell tower dump information (180 days); call details records (7\u201310 years); text message content, data requests, and geo-location data not stored; voicemail content (up to 21 days); subscriber information (6 years after the account is closed).<ref>[http://uk.pcmag.com/smartphones/11539/news/wireless-carriers-reveal-user-data-requests Mobile Phone Reviews: Wireless Carriers Reveal User Data Requests<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nComparing the 2010 DOJ memo released by the ACLU and Markey's 2013 wireless data retention disclosures, T-Mobile increased the retention period for subscriber information from 5 to 6 years. T-Mobile also increased its call detail record retention from 2 years (prepaid) and 5 years (postpaid) to 7\u201310 years.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Companies|Telecommunication|United States}}\n* [[List of companies based in Bellevue, Washington]]\n* [[List of United States wireless communications service providers]]\n* [[List of mobile network operators of the Americas]]\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.telekom.com/  Deutsche Telekom AG's homepage ]\n* [https://www.metropcs.com/ MetroPCS's official website]\n\n{{Finance links\n| name = T-Mobile US\n| symbol = TMUS\n| sec_cik = TMUS\n| reuters = TMUS.O\n| bloomberg = TMUS:US\n| yahoo = TMUS\n| google = TMUS\n}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{Deutsche Telekom}}\n{{United States mobile communications brands}}\n{{Caribbean mobile phone companies}}\n{{Puerto Rico mobile phone companies}}\n{{NASDAQ-100}}\n{{Seattle Corporations}}\n{{Telecommunications}}\n|state=expanded\n}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Mobile phone companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Wi-Fi providers]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Bellevue, Washington]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies established in 1994]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1994]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1994]]\n[[Category:Deutsche Telekom]]\n[[Category:American subsidiaries of foreign companies]]\n[[Category:2013 initial public offerings]]\n", "name_user": "Dogojosho", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling Correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T-Mobile_US"}
{"title_page": "Solar Entertainment Corporation", "text_new": "{{short description|Filipino Media Company}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Expert needed|date=February 2016}}\n{{Overly detailed|date=February 2016}}\n{{Self-published|date=February 2016}}\n{{More citations needed|date=February 2016}}}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Solar Entertainment Corporation\n| logo = | \n| caption = | \n| foundation = {{start date and age|1976|1|3}} (as a TV movie company)<br>{{start date and age|1988|7|15}} (as a film distribution company)<br>{{start date and age|2000|6|17}} (as a cable television network)<br>{{start date and age|2008|1|1}} (as a broadcast company)\n| type = [[Private company|Private]] ([[Subsidiary]])\n| traded_as = |\n| predecessor = |\n| location_city = '''Master Playout Facility:''' <br> Third Floor, Worldwide Corporate Center, EDSA corner [[Shaw Boulevard]], [[Mandaluyong|Mandaluyong City]] <br> '''Corporate Offices:''' <br>Solar Century Tower,\n100 Tordesillas St., Corner H.V. Dela Costa St. Salcedo Village, [[Makati City]]\n| location_country = \n| area_served = Nationwide\n| industry = [[Media (communication)|Media company]]\n| services = Free-to-air TV channels and shows, radio broadcasting, cable television, local and international film distribution, film-making, entertainment, television programs and production, news, sports, websites\n| founder = William Y. Tieng<br>Willy Y. Tieng <!-- In other parts of the country remained under the Tieng management and founder led by former Solar Entertainment Corporation Chairman William Tieng and former Solar Entertainment Corporation Vice Chairman Willy Tieng. However, SEC remained as its licensee until July 2015. -->\n| products = [[ETC (Philippine TV network)|ETC]], [[Jack TV]], [[Solar Sports]], Solar Pictures, Solar Scoop, Sinag Maynila Film Festival\n| key_people = Wilson Y. Tieng <small> ([[President (corporate title)|President]] and [[Chief executive officer|CEO]])</small><br>Gidget Lao <small>(Chief Executive for Business Operations)\n| revenue = [[Philippine Peso|PHP]]1.372 billion <small>([[Fiscal year|FY]] 2015)</small><ref name=\"financial\">{{cite web|title=Media Ownnership Monitor Philippines - Solar Entertainment Corporation|url=http://philippines.mom-rsf.org/en/philippines/owners/companies/detail/company/company/show/solar-entertainment-corporation/|access-date=November 24, 2016|publisher=VERA Files}}</ref>\n| operating_income = PHP124.43 million <small>(FY 2015)</small><ref name=\"financial\"/>\n| num_employees = |\n| owner = Solar Films Inc. {{small|(38%)}} <br> Wilson Y. Tieng {{small|(21%)}} <br> William Y. Tieng {{small|(15%)}}\n| subsid = [[ETC (Philippine TV network)|ETC Productions]] <br> [[Southern Broadcasting Network]] <br> [[Easy TV (Philippines)|Solar Digital Media Holdings]] <br> Domestic Satellite Philippines, Inc.\n| homepage = {{URL|www.solarentertainmentcorp.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Solar Entertainment Corporation''' (simply known as '''Solar''' or '''SEC''') is a [[Media in the Philippines|Filipino media company]] founded and owned by the siblings of the Tieng family (Wilson, William and Willy Tieng) which also engages in property development, and distribution of imported products and generic pharmaceutical products. <ref> [http://solarresourcesinc.com/about-us/ Solar Resources - About Us] Solarresourcesinc.com, Accessed on 15 December 2015 </ref>\n\nSolar Entertainment operates two [[Free-to-air|digital free-to-air channels]] and two [[cable television|cable channels]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solarentertainmentcorp.com/about/page/networks|title=List of Solar Networks|website=Solarentertainmentcorp.com}}</ref> Solar also owns a film distribution company (Solar Pictures) and defunct [[freemium]] [[digital television]] service ([[Easy TV (Philippines)|Easy TV Home]]).\n\n==History==\n===Film production and distribution===\nSolar Entertainment was founded and established by the brothers William Tieng, Wilson Tieng and Willy Tieng in 1976.\nSolar Films was then formed in 1988 (one of the first films that distributed by Solar Films is [[Rambo III]] of [[Sylvester Stallone]]), bringing international films (and later, local films since 2009) to the Philippines. Since 2012, Solar has collaborated with independent film director [[Brillante Mendoza]] for a multiple film contract.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.solarentertainmentcorp.com/about/page/solar_today |title=Archived copy |access-date=May 15, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517114818/http://www.solarentertainmentcorp.com/about/page/solar_today |archive-date=May 17, 2014 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On March 18, 2015, Solar launched the Sinag Maynila film festival is, which featured five films from a talented group of directors, each with a different vision and approach. The films were shown in select SM Cinemas from March 18 to 24, 2015. The winners were announced at the \u201cGabi ng Parangal\u201d on March 22.\n\n===Cable television===\nOn January 1, 1994, Solar launched on cable television as the Solar Entertainment Channel.\n\nIn 2000, DOMSAT became Solar's subsidiary. As a result, DOMSAT\u2019s teleport is being used by Solar to produce, originate, and distribute its various television program services. Its full service digital broadcast teleport features server technology facility located in Barangay Sta. Cruz, Sumulong Highway, [[Antipolo City]], Rizal. It is built around two encoder platforms, Scientific Atlanta Power Vu Classic(DVB) and Motorola Digicipher II(MPEG-@). Program origination is done on a SeaChange Media Cluster Server System. The facility includes a 500-square-meter studio and various linear and non-linear production bays.<ref name=\"acquisition\">{{cite news|title= MVP-Ang rivalry set to spill over into television with San Miguel acquisition of Solar stake |url= http://www.spin.ph/sports/basketball/news/mvp-ang-rivalry-set-to-spill-over-into-television-with-san-miguel-acquisition-of-solar-stake|date= November 9, 2013|access-date= August 18, 2014}}</ref> Solar Entertainment first launched its namesake entertainment cable channel in the early 2000s, one devoted to American programs. This channel was later known as Solar USA (the acronym stands for \"Ultimate in Suspense and Action\"), and then later simply as USA before it was replaced by two separate channels.\n\nIn January 2004, Solar launched on cable sports alternative channel as Sports Plus.\n\nOn August 23, 2004, Solar Entertainment launched [[ETC (Philippine TV channel)|ETC]] or Entertainment Central, which is positioned as the country\u2019s premier cable female entertainment channel. ETC is a platform that brings its audience closer to their aspirational lifestyle, as embodied by their idols.\n\nOn May 5, 2005, it test launched delivering debuting service. Intended for a predominantly male audience, the company launched the country\u2019s leading general entertainment cable channel, [[Jack TV]], in July.\n\nOn October 15, 2005, Solar Entertainment launched a crime and action cable channel, Crime/Suspense or [[C/S]].\n\nOn December 15, 2005, Solar Entertainment launched a spin-off channel to ETC, [[2nd Avenue (television channel)|ETC 2nd Avenue]], a lifestyle and general entertainment channel. Started as a test broadcast on December 15, 2005, and had its full launch in 2006. The channel was later renamed as 2nd Avenue on January 17, 2007.\n\nOn October 1, 2006, Sports Plus ceased broadcasting and replaced by the [[Basketball TV]] channel formed by Solar, while moving most of Sports Plus programs to [[Solar Sports]].\n\n===As a broadcast company===\nOn January 1, 2008, Solar Entertainment Corporation began to lease block airtime with terrestrial TV networks, [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN]], [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN]] and [[Rajah Broadcasting Network|RJTV]]. The move was a result of [[SkyCable]] pulling out C/S, ETC, and 2nd Avenue from the cable company's lineup at their own right. Those three started carrying shows from Solar's, with [[C/S]] on RPN, [[ETC (Philippine TV network)|ETC]] on SBN, and [[2nd Avenue (television channel)|2nd Avenue]] on RJTV.\n\n[[File:Solar Sports.png|200px|thumb|left| Former logo of [[Solar Sports]]]]\nOn May 22, 2009, a victory party for [[Manny Pacquiao|Manny \"Pacman\" Pacquiao]], who just became the new IBO (International Boxing Organization) and ''Ring Magazine'' Light Welterweight Champion, was held at the Renaissance Hotel in [[Makati City]], in partnership with [[GMA Network (company)|GMA Network Inc.]] Solar and [[GMA Network|GMA]] executives at that time signed for a partnership in TV coverage of Manny Pacquiao's upcoming boxing matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/photos/1295/gma-victory-party-for-manny-pac-man-pacquiao|title=GMA victory party for Manny 'Pac-Man' Pacquiao|author=|date=|work=PEP.ph|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe C/S cable channel was later rebranded as [[C/S Origin]] in September 2008, while the RPN network later changed its branding to [[C/S 9]] the next month.\n\nOn November 29, 2009, Solar rebranded C/S9 as [[Solar TV]] at 11:00 am with a slogan ''It's A Bright New World'' on RPN. On October 31, 2010, it changed some of its programming content to English/Tagalog with a new slogan ''Kung Saan Lahat Panalo!''.\n\nIn mid-2010, GemCom sold all of its 97% equity share in [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN]] to Solar for Php 368.8 million. Since then, SBN became a fully owned subsidiary of Solar.\n\nOn February 11, 2011, SEC partnered with [[ABS-CBN|ABS-CBN Corporation]] to air [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) games over free TV starting February 19, 2011. The games are aired on [[Studio 23]] (now ABS-CBN Sports and Action later known as [[ABS-CBN Sports and Action|S+A]]) and [[ABS-CBN (television network)|ABS-CBN]], but Solar still airs the games daily on [[Basketball TV|BTV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/sports/02/11/11/abs-cbn-air-nba-all-star-free-tv|title=ABS-CBN to air NBA games on free TV|first=ABS-CBN|last=News|date=|work=ABS-CBN.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Solar TV Network logo.png|200px|thumb|left|Logo of Solar TV as a television network]]\nOn March 2, 2011, after SEC acquired 34 percent of RPN's shares from the Philippine government as part of RPN/IBC privatization in 2011, Solar TV finally ventured into news at the end of 2011. On that same day, ETC moved to [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN]] while TalkTV launched over [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN]]. TalkTV was formed by then Solar-owned Solar Television Network. The first programs that aired on the channel were ''[[Dateline NBC]]'', ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today Show]]'', Today's Talk, ''[[NBC Nightly News]]'', ''[[Inside Edition]]'', ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]'' and ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]''.<ref name=\"manilastandardtoday.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.manilastandardtoday.com/insideBusop.htm?f=2011/february/25/vicagustin.isx&d=2011/february/25|title=Tiengs move into news|last=Agustin|first=Victor C.|date=February 25, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714043823/http://www.manilastandardtoday.com/insideBusop.htm?f=2011%2Ffebruary%2F25%2Fvicagustin.isx&d=2011%2Ffebruary%2F25|archivedate=July 14, 2011|access-date=December 10, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>[http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/214215/news/nation/coloma-privatization-of-rpn-9-ibc-13-in-the-works Coloma: Privatization of RPN 9, IBC 13 in the works] ''[[GMA News and Public Affairs|GMA News Online]]''. 03-01-2011 Retrieved 03-01-2011{{Clarify|reason=ambiguous date format|date=April 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn April 8, 2011, Solar Entertainment Corporation launched [[The Game Channel]] on [[Destiny Cable]]. It conducted its initial test broadcast from April 8, 2011, until September 29. It then began airing on [[Broadcast Enterprises and Affiliated Media|BEAM Channel 31]] on August 15, 2011, after BEAM and Solar signed an affiliation deal, which gave the latter the use of the former's facilities. Full broadcast started on September 30, 2011.\n\nIn May 2011, [[ETC (Philippine TV channel)|ETC]] launched the slogan \"Young and Loving It\". It also saw new programs such as the reality series ''[[The Rachel Zoe Project]]'' and ''Bachelor Pad'', drama series ''[[Nikita (TV series)|Nikita]]'', and ''[[The Secret Circle (TV series)|The Secret Circle]]'', US reality series ''[[The Glee Project]]'', comedy shows like ''[[New Girl]]'' and [[2 Broke Girls]], and local lifestyle show ''[[Etcetera (TV program)|Etcetera]]''. In 2012, ETC includes the reality show ''[[American Idol]]'', local programs like ''[[Project Runway Philippines]]'' (season 3), drama series ''[[The Lying Game (TV series)|The Lying Game]]'', ''[[Emily Owens, M.D.|Emily Owens MD]]'' and ''[[Beauty and the Beast (2012 TV series)|Beauty and the Beast]]'', and local infotainment show ''[[ETC HQ]]''. In 2013, ETC aired comedy-drama series ''[[The Carrie Diaries (TV series)|The Carrie Diaries]]'', sitcom series ''[[Super Fun Night]]'', supernatural drama series ''[[Ravenswood (TV series)|Ravenswood]]'', horror fantasy drama series ''[[The Originals (TV series)|The Originals]]'' and among others.\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:SolarNews.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Logo as the Solar News and Current Affairs from 2011 until August 22, 2014{{deletable image-caption|date=3 July 2016}}]] -->\n[[Solar News]], known for its back-to-basics and unbiased journalism,{{According to whom|date=April 2017}} was formed in January 2012 during the coverage of the impeachment trial of former Chief Justice Renato Corona. Post-EDSA revolution [[ABS-CBN (television network)|ABS-CBN]] newsmen Pal Marquez, Jing Magsaysay and [[Pia Hontiveros]] together with former ANC anchors [[Claire Celdran]], [[Mai Rodriguez]] and Nancy Irlanda, known as the pillars of Solar News.{{According to whom|date=April 2017}} Most of its news reporters are from [[ABS-CBN (television network)|ABS-CBN]] and [[ABS-CBN News Channel|ANC]], as well as from [[NewsWatch (Philippine TV program)|RPN NewsWatch]].<ref>[http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/276523/economy/companies/200-rpn-9-employees-to-lose-jobs 200 RPN 9 employees to lose jobs] ''[[GMA News and Public Affairs|GMA News]]''. 10-02-2012 Retrieved 10-02-2012</ref><ref>[http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/business/10/04/12/ramon-ang-says-talks-buy-solar-entertainment Ramon Ang says in talks to buy Solar Entertainment] ''[[ABS-CBN News and Current Affairs|ABS-CBN News]]''. 10-04-2012 Retrieved 10-04-2012</ref>\n\nOn December 24, 2011, The Game Channel limited its broadcast on daytime sharing with a new programming service called [[Chase (TV channel)|CHASE]] which takes over the evening block. In February 2012, both services aired a promotion, announcing the split of CHASE and TGC to form themselves as separate channels. On February 15, 2012, The Game Channel finally shuts down on free TV and was relaunched as a cable channel; CHASE was also relaunched as a separate channel, now occupying the entire BEAM broadcast airtime on Free TV.\n\nOn April 3, 2012, Solar transferred its former Salcedo Village facilities to their new facility in Worldwide Corporate Center in [[Mandaluyong|Mandaluyong City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medianewser.com/2012/04/solar-news-update-debuts-new-look.html|title=Solar News Update debuts new look|website=Medianewser.com}}</ref> It also featured a newly constructed set for Solar's then-news division, which would become fully functional three months later.\n\nOn July 16, 2012, Solar News launched its first local newscast ''Solar Network News'', followed by ''Solar Nightly News'', an hourly Solar News Update, Solar Daybreak, and Solar Newsday.\n\nOn September 7, 2012, Jack TV plugged their announcement through CHASE programs bearing the title \"Another Jack TV is rising, coming soon on this channel\" (BEAM Channel 31). This indicated that CHASE was being replaced; finally, on October 20, 2012, Jack City was then launched, marking October 19 as the end of CHASE's broadcasts. [[Jack City]] still does carry some of CHASE's programs however.\n\nIn October 2012, it was found out that Solar News would replace the government-controlled RPN News, as a result of RPN's privatization, making Solar TV covering the entire network's airtime. More than 200 RPN employees, particularly those from the labor union and the NewsWatch staff, were retrenched and RPN News was closed down on October 29, effectively axing NewsWatch and NewsCap. Some retrenched government employees were relocated to either [[People's Television Network|People's Television Network (PTV 4)]] or [[Intercontinental Broadcasting Corporation|Intercontinental Broadcasting Corporation (IBC 13)]] (both State-run broadcasters).\n\n[[File:FvfOmbudsman0222 37.JPG|thumb|left|200px|A [[Toyota HiAce]] van used by Solar News parked at the Office of the Ombudsman.]]\nOn October 30, 2012, at 5:45 am, TalkTV was replaced as Solar News Channel on Channel 21 via [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN]]. The channel saw the relaunch of sports news program ''Solar Sports Desk'' (now known as [[Sports Desk (2004 TV series)|CNN Philippines Sports Desk]]), as well as the initial telecast of the Solar News and Current affairs block in November 2012 comprising five public affairs programs ([[Legal Help Desk|Legal HD]], [[MedTalk]], [[News.PH]], [[Opposing Views]], Elections 2013 and [[News Cafe]]), ''[[60 Minutes]]'', ''[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]'', ''[[Undercover Boss (U.S. TV series)|Undercover Boss]]'' and the \"Stories\" [[documentary film|documentaries]] block. In January 2013, Solar News Cebuano (now known as [[CNN Philippines Cebuano News]]) made history as the first national newscast delivered in a local dialect. In 2014, it also launched the [[Kapampangan language|Kapampangan]] national newscast, [[Kapampangan News]] and the public service program ''[[Serbisyo All Access]]'', which is shown in [[Filipino language]].\n\nPrior to the channel's transfer to RPN, SNC's flagship newscast (Solar Network News) simulcasted on RPN 9 (free TV only) from the SNC's launch. The news content for RPN (then affiliated with ETC), however, was switched to ''Solar Nightly News'' on January 14, 2013, onwards, to avoid backlash from free TV viewers, particularly Free TV viewers of ''[[American Idol]]'' (in which the original plan was to replace the 6 pm via satellite broadcast to Free TV viewers by Network News, then airs the AI episodes at the 8 pm rerun in simulcast with cable and satellite viewers). Throughout the ''American Idol'' season, as the episodes are repeated at 8 PM on cable, Solar used the separate free TV-only feed, that contains reruns of selected ETC shows (but with advertisements replaced by ETC teasers and promotions) at 8&nbsp;pm and ''Nightly News'' at 9 PM (with additional ETC programs, if necessary) to be used by RPN after each AI via satellite episode before RPN returns to the main ETC feed at 10 PM. This is to retain RPN's news content as it then has no newscast since the axing of NewsWatch.\n\nOn January 3, 2013, SEC launched Blink Cinema (later renamed as [[My Movie Channel]]) with the full broadcast taking effect later that month.\n\nOn April 14, 2013, [[TV5 Network (company)|TV5 Network Inc.]] and Solar Entertainment Corporation joined to broadcast the [[2013 FIBA Asia Championship]] in Manila on Philippine television on August 1\u201311. Aside from [[TV5 (Philippines)|TV5]] and its sister channel ([[AksyonTV]]), the games were also broadcast over Solar\u2019s cable channel [[Basketball TV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interaksyon.com/interaktv/tv5-solar-team-up-for-2013-fiba-asia-championship-coverage|title=TV5, Solar team up for 2013 FIBA Asia Championship coverage - InterAksyon.com - Sports5|author=|date=|work=InterAksyon.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===New management===\nOn May 22, 2013, Solar Entertainment Corporation appointed two officers to manage its broadcasting and cable businesses: Manuel \u201cMeckoy\u201d Quiogue as chief commercial officer and Maria Theresa \u201cMitos\u201d Borromeo as chief operating officer (COO).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.9news.ph/lifestyle/2013/05/22/solar-entertainment-corp.-appoints-2-new-officers|title=9news.ph - 9news Resources and Information.|author=|date=|work=9news.ph|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> However, Quiogue suddenly died on May 31, 2013 prior to assuming his position.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bworldonline.com/weekender/content.php?id=73221|title=Your life is your message to the world|work=BWorldOnline.com|access-date=April 6, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923221542/http://www.bworldonline.com/weekender/content.php?id=73221|archivedate=September 23, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn June 28, 2013, [[Jack City]] reduced its free TV broadcast to 18 hours a day on BEAM in compliance with the [[National Telecommunications Commission]]'s guidelines. However, it still continues to air as a cable channel 24 hours a day.\n\nOn November 9, 2013, [[San Miguel Corporation]]'s president and COO, [[Ramon S. Ang|Ramon Ang]], explored the possibility of acquiring a controlling stake in Solar Entertainment Corporation in his personal capacity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/business/13606-san-miguel-s-ang-keen-on-solar-tv,-owner-of-rpn-9|title=San Miguel's Ang keen on Solar TV, owner of RPN-9|author=|date=|work=Rappler.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interaksyon.com/business/46828/meeting-of-minds-reached-in-talks-with-ramon-ang-for-investment-says-solar-chairman|title='Meeting of minds' reached in talks with Ramon Ang for investment, says Solar chairman|author=|date=|work=InterAksyon.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> However, no further announcements were made after this and Ang subsequently reached an agreement to acquire a minority stake.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interaksyon.com/business/93653/exclusive--businessmirror-owner-acquires-majority-stake-in-rpn9|title=EXCLUSIVE - BusinessMirror owner acquires biggest stake in RPN9|work=InterAksyon.com|access-date=April 6, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140822083909/http://www.interaksyon.com/business/93653/exclusive--businessmirror-owner-acquires-majority-stake-in-rpn9|archivedate=August 22, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Solar News Channel]] and its partnership moved to [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]] on December 1, 2013, while ETC returned to SBN Channel 21 a day before. (ETC was aired on [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN-21]] from 2008 to 2011 then to RPN-9 from 2011 to 2013),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.inquirer.net/177231/new-investor-vows-to-turn-rpn-9-around|title=New investor vows to turn RPN 9 around|first=Miguel R. Camus and Doris C.|last=Dumlao|date=|work=Inquirer.net|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> as well as the launch of Solar's video-on-demand website Blink. As a result of the channel swap (on RPN's part), Network News and Nightly News became newscasts on its own right.\n\nIn 2014, Solar Entertainment's Solar One Boracay happened during the Labor Day weekend to showcase its channels (ETC, 2nd Avenue, JackTV, JackCITY, My Movie Channel, The Game Channel, Solar Sports, BTV and NBA Premium TV) through various summer activities all over the island.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thedistrictboracay.com/solar-one-boracay-at-the-district-boracay/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=March 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402164529/http://www.thedistrictboracay.com/solar-one-boracay-at-the-district-boracay/ |archive-date=April 2, 2015 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn August 20, 2014, Solar Entertainment Corporation chief Wilson Tieng announced that he ceded his entire share on [[Solar TV Network]], Inc., including its 34% majority share on RPN, to [[Antonio Cabangon Chua]], owner of business daily [[BusinessMirror]] and [[Aliw Broadcasting Corporation]].<ref>[http://www.interaksyon.com/business/93653/exclusive--businessmirror-owner-acquires-majority-stake-in-rpn9 Exclusive: BusinessMirror owner acquires majority stake in RPN9] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140822083909/http://www.interaksyon.com/business/93653/exclusive--businessmirror-owner-acquires-majority-stake-in-rpn9 |date=August 22, 2014 }}, InterAksyon.com, August 20, 2014</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2014/08/21/1360003/cabangon-chua-acquires-rpn-9|title=Cabangon-Chua acquires RPN-9|first=Lawrence|last=Agcaoili|date=August 21, 2014|work=PhilStar.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> Tieng sold Solar TV because they were losing money for operations after purchasing RPN. As a result of this ownership change, STVNI, Solar News Channel and RPN's majority stake were separated from the Tiengs; while ETC, 2nd Avenue, and Jack City reverted to Solar Entertainment's ownership.\n\nOn September 1, 2014, [[Jack City]] ended its run on free TV due to the preparations being made by [[Broadcast Enterprises and Affiliated Media|BEAM 31]] for the incoming transition to ISDB-T digital television, though it continues to be broadcast as a separate cable channel. However, Jack City continued to broadcast on cable networks until March 21, 2015. After Jack City's closure to free TV, BEAM aired under blocktime programs from various local production and religious companies. On November 15, 2014, BEAM began being carried on [[SkyCable]] and Destiny Cable subscribers (per compliance with NTC's \"must-carry\" basis). This move resulted of Jack City in a change of its channel assignment for SkyCable and [[Destiny Cable]] subscribers, as well as several pay TV companies.\n\nIn 2015, Solar Entertainment Corporation launched the #1stonPHTV brand of Solar channels for [[ETC (Philippine TV channel)|ETC]], [[2nd Avenue (television channel)|2nd Avenue]], [[Jack TV]], Jack City and [[My Movie Channel]], with the brand implemented on January 6, 2015. Since then, all SEC channels broadcast first-run foreign television programs with the hashtag #1stonPHTV (First on Philippine TV), which was formerly known as \"Match Airing\" (ETC), \"Playing 1st\" (Jack TV), \"The Newest in the US\" and \"FastCast\" (2nd Avenue) and \"See It First\" (Jack City).\n\n[[The Game Channel]], after almost three years on broadcasting, selling or ceased on February 28, 2015. The channel space was taken over by [[My Movie Channel]] on March 1.\n\nOn March 22, 2015, Jack City was replaced by [[CT (TV channel)|CT]], thus becoming independent from its parent network. Upon launch, the channel broadened its programming focus by adding talk shows, sitcoms and men's lifestyle programs to its roster.\n\nOn March 26, 2015, Solar Entertainment announced its broadcast of the \"Fight Of The Century\" between [[Manny Pacquiao]] and [[Floyd Mayweather Jr.]] on May 3, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/sports/2015/03/27/1437964/abs-cbn-gma-tv5-join-hands-air-pacquiao-fight-networks-unite-historic|title=ABS-CBN, GMA, TV5 join hands to air Pacquiao fight: Networks unite for historic broadcast|first=Abac|last=Cordero|date=March 27, 2015|work=PhilStar.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> As stated in a press conference that day, it was broadcast on May 3 via delayed broadcast in three major television stations in the Philippines, [[ABS-CBN (television network)|ABS-CBN]], [[TV5 (Philippines)|TV5]], and [[GMA Network]] (who waived its exclusive contract with Solar to allow its multi-network coverage, but maintained its exclusive live broadcast on its radio division), with [[Solar Sports]] as its main content provider for this historic event in boxing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/sports/by-sport/boxing-mma/pacquiao/88062-pacquiao-mayweather-television-broadcast-ph|title=Pacquiao vs Mayweather to be televised by GMA, ABS-CBN and TV5|author=|date=|work=Rappler.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/459458/sports/boxing/pacquiao-mayweather-fight-to-air-live-over-gma-radio-stations-nationwide|title=Pacquiao-Mayweather fight to air live over GMA radio stations nationwide|author=|date=|work=GMANetwork.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2015, My Movie Channel ceased broadcasting. The closure or selling was announced by Solar a day before.\n\n===Rebranding of the four flagship networks===\nOn October 16, 2016, Solar relaunched its flagship channels ETC, 2nd Avenue, Basketball TV and Solar Sports. The four networks unveiled their new logos, on-air graphics and station IDs, which took effect on that day. CT, Jack TV, Shop TV and NBA Premium TV on the other hand remains unchanged. Also that day, Solar launched its corporate campaign slogan ''...There's More To Come'', which evolved in 2017 as ''We go for More''.\n\nIn 2017, Solar Entertainment became the official Philippine broadcaster of the 65th edition of the [[Miss Universe]] in Manila. This led to another deal with [[ABS-CBN]], [[TV5 (Philippines)|TV5]] and [[GMA Network|GMA]] (the second time that such deal happened between Solar and the Big 3 networks). According to some sources, a directive from [[Rodrigo Duterte|President Duterte]] ordered that the major networks must cover the prestige pageant as it happens live in the [[Philippines]]. Alongside the Big Three, Solar Entertainment channels [[ETC (Philippine TV network)|etc]], [[2nd Avenue (television channel)|2nd Avenue]], [[Jack TV]] and [[CT (TV channel)|CT]] aired the pageant simultaneously. It was also in the same year when Solar Entertainment forged a joint venture with the Bermuda-based communications satellite company [[Asia Broadcast Satellite]] to launch the first nationwide free-to-air [[Satellite television#Direct broadcast via satellite|direct-to-home]] satellite television services using the [[C band (IEEE)|C-band]], which is set to launch on the 3rd quarter of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.satellitetoday.com/broadcasting/2017/05/22/abs-solar-group-launch-new-dth-service-philippines/|title=ABS, The Solar Group to Launch New DTH Service in the Philippines|author=Kendall Russell|date=May 22, 2017|work=Satellite Today|access-date=July 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Carriage disputes==\n===Sky Cable===\n====2008====\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2014}}\nSolar's channels have ceased airing on [[Sky Cable]], the Philippines' largest cable television provider. An insider{{Who|date=April 2017}} claims that these troubles with Sky Cable started when boxer [[Manny Pacquiao]], whose fights Solar Entertainment has the exclusive right to air and distribute to, moved from [[ABS-CBN]], the flagship television network of [[ABS-CBN Corporation]] and the primary owner of [[Sky Cable Corporation]], to rival [[GMA Network]]. Another insider{{Who|date=April 2017}} claims that SkyCable wanted to remove [[ETC (Philippine TV channel)|ETC]] and [[Jack TV]] to make room for their own channels, [[Velvet (TV channel)|Velvet]] (now defunct) and [[Maxxx]] (now defunct). Sky Cable wanted to retain [[C/S]], [[2nd Avenue (television channel)|2nd Avenue]], [[Solar Sports]] and [[Basketball TV]], but Solar made a decision that they would only renew their contract if Sky Cable carried all six channels. Thus, Solar decided to pull out all their channels rather than remove ETC and Jack TV.\n\nHowever, Solar has signed a deal with local terrestrial channels [[TV5 (Philippines)|ABC]], [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN]], [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN]] and [[Rajah Broadcasting Network|RJTV]] for block-time programming. C/S, ETC and 2nd Avenue programming are seen on terrestrial TV channels RPN, SBN and RJTV, respectively, while [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] and [[WWE]] programming were seen on TV5, now moved to RPN (WWE programming are currently being broadcast thru TV5, while its terrestrial NBA coverage were moved to [[ABS-CBN Sports]] under Solar).\n\nMost of its channels were later returned to Sky Cable, while Jack TV would eventually return to its lineup on January 1, 2010 replacing Maxxx.\n\nMeanwhile, Pacquiao's boxing promotion, [[Top Rank]], signed a non-guaranteed contract with [[ABS-CBN Sports]] to exclusively air fights promoted by Top Rank, with the exception of Pacquiao fights which are still signed exclusively through Solar Entertainment.\n\n====2017\u201319====\nOn April 10, 2017, 3 days before the [[2017 NBA Playoffs]] was scheduled to begin (and coincided with the final day of the [[2016\u201317 NBA season|2016\u201317 NBA regular season]]), Basketball TV, [[NBA Premium TV]], Solar Sports, Jack TV and [[CT (TV channel)|CT]] (now defunct) were removed by Solar from Sky Cable (including [[Sky Direct]], [[Destiny Cable]] & [[Sky On Demand]] thru video on demand) without any prior announcement from Solar.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rappler.com/sports/by-sport/basketball/nba/167065-sky-nba-premium-btv-unavailable |title=Sky subscribers frustrated as NBA Premium, BTV unavailable for playoffs start |last= Rola|first=Alyssa |date= April 16, 2017|website=[[Rappler]] |access-date= April 16, 2017|quote=}}</ref> Initially, both Basketball TV and NBA Premium TV were replaced by airing a simulcast of [[ABS-CBN Sports and Action]] with a ticker announcing the unavailability of the channels, with Solar Sports, Jack TV and CT (now defunct) also doing the latter albeit with a black screen. Later, almost all of the pulled-out Solar channels were replaced by an imaging card, initially detailing the unavailability of the channels and then later, announcing that they will discuss with Solar on returning the aforementioned channels; while for BTV and NBA Premium TV, a schedule of the NBA games that will air on [[ABS-CBN]], ABS-CBN Sports and Action and [[Fox Sports Asia|Fox Sports]] within the week and a loop of an NBA promo. Solar did not comment on the situation for the removal of the channels, but sources and some netizens pointed out a carriage dispute between the two parties for not paying an undisclosed price to continue broadcasting these channels, which was later proven true by an article published by the ''[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]''.\n\nAs the dispute continued, some media enthusiasts and netizens raised concerns of whether these Solar channels will return to Sky and/or Destiny. Others pointed that inaction between the two parties could affect the next long-term local broadcast franchise with the NBA, slated to begin at the Association's 2019-2020 regular season. (Currently, Solar and Sky's parent, ABS-CBN, have a shared broadcast agreement to air the NBA games on pay and terrestrial television, respectively. Rumours circulated that both networks may bid separately, if they could not reach renewal, and use their respective infrastructure to broadcast adequate NBA coverage; otherwise, rival networks with a functioning sports department like [[5 (TV channel)|The 5 Network]] may also seek their own bidding to steal the 2019 contract from both Solar and ABS-CBN.)\n\nNetizens and viewers were dismayed and frustrated by the removal of the said channels by Sky Cable, most notably for BTV and NBA Premium due to the importance of the Playoffs. Some netizens were angered by the removal of the said channels and asked Sky Cable to return the channels before the scheduled Playoffs would begin, however Sky Cable would respond to angered netizens on social media that they are \"fixing the situation with Solar\". Other netizens and viewers would otherwise switch providers from Sky Cable to other cable companies that carried these channels or to other satellite providers like [[Cignal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spin.ph/basketball/nba/news/sky-cable-nba-premium-basketball-tv-negotiations-with-solar |title=SKYcable unable to give timetable for return of NBA Premium, Basketball TV to channel lineup |last=Terrado |first=Reuben |date=April 15, 2017 |website=[[GMA New Media|Spin.ph]] |access-date=April 16, 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nOn October 16, 2018, Basketball TV and NBA Premium TV returned to Sky Cable, Sky Direct, & Sky On Demand for the first time in 18 months<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.spin.ph/basketball/nba/nba-premium-btv-channels-back-on-skycable-per-advisory-a795-20181016 |title=NBA Premium, BTV channels back on SKYCable, per advisory |last=Terrado |first=Reuben |date=October 16, 2018 |website=[[GMA New Media|Spin.ph]] |access-date=October 26, 2018 |quote=}}</ref>; however it was later removed on October 28, 2018 for unknown reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mysky.com.ph/MetroManila/updates/1031/2018/10/28/sky-advisory|title=SKY Advisory|website=Me & My SKY: SKY at 25 years}}</ref>\n\nThe carriage dispute officially ended on January 1, 2019 when all Solar channels: Basketball TV, NBA Premium TV, Solar Sports, and Jack TV were restored on Sky Cable (including Sky On Demand & Sky Direct).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.ph/basketball/nba/nba-premium-and-btv-are-back-in-skycable-s-channel-lineup-a795-20190101|title=NBA Premium and BTV are back in SKYcable's channel lineup|website=Spin.ph}}</ref>\n\nIronically, [[MTVph]], which is a Solar channel, ended its operations on the same day at that time Sky returned the affected Solar channels. As of 2019, Sky Cable's sister company Destiny Cable still does not carry all the aforementioned Solar channels despite its aforementioned return on Sky Cable.\n\nDuring the aforementioned period, [[Shop TV]], ETC and 2nd Avenue (now defunct) were kept on the air, due to the \"must-carry\" rules by the NTC. MTVph was also kept on the air (until it was discontinued on January 1, 2019) since it was carried in a separate programming agreement outside of the affected channels despite its ownership.\n\n===Dream Satellite TV===\n[[Dream Satellite TV]] ceased carrying three Solar Channels, namely [[Solar Sports]], [[ETC (Philippine TV channel)|ETC]] (which was at that time a cable channel prior to its move to free TV and cable) and [[2nd Avenue (TV channel)|2nd Avenue]] (now defunct) (except [[C/S 9]]) effective 1 February 2009. Dream's carriage contract with Solar Entertainment, which expired on 31 December 2008 was not renewed by Dream, citing financial constraints as its main reason. The three Solar channels were replaced by A&E's [[History (South East Asian TV channel)|The History Channel]], [[Bio. (South East Asia)|Biography Channel]] and [[Crime & Investigation Network (South East Asia)|Crime and Investigation Channel]]. As of 2017, ETC and 2nd Avenue remained on its lineup due to the \"must-carry\" rules of the NTC. \n\nUnfortunately, Dream Satellite ended its operations on December 31, 2017 due to bankruptcy and its competition with other satellite providers.\n\n==Divisions / Subsidiaries==\n* ETC Productions<!-- ETC Productions is a production arm of the female-oriented TV channel, ETC -->\n* Blink\n* Solar Pictures\n* Domestic Satellite Philippines, Inc. (DOMSAT)\n* [[Southern Broadcasting Network]] (acquired in 2010 from Lucio Co's Gem Communications Holdings Corporation)\n* [[Easy TV (Philippines)|Solar Digital Media Holdings]] (operator of Solar's digital television service '''Easy TV Home''')\n\n==Filmography of Solar Pictures==\n===Notable local films released or distributed by Solar Pictures===\n* ''Syota ng Bayan'' (2001)\n* ''[[Batas Militar (2006 film)|Batas Militar]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Pacquiao: The Movie]]'' (2006) - with [[Star Cinema]]\n* ''Anak Ng Kumander'' (2007)\n* ''[[Ang Tanging Pamilya: A Marry Go Round|Ang Tanging Pamilya]]'' (2009) - with [[Star Cinema]]\n* ''[[Kimmy Dora: Kambal sa Kiyeme]]'' (2009) - with [[Star Cinema]]\n* ''[[Wapakman]]'' (2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/cebu-entertainment/483549/8-official-entries-2009-mmff-bared|title=8 official entries to 2009 MMFF bared|author=|date=|work=PhilStar.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Flames of Love'' (2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2012/11/05/863321/flames-love-celebrates-year-faith|title=Flames of Love celebrates the Year of Faith|first=Ricky|last=Lo|date=November 5, 2012|work=PhilStar.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Sapi'' (2013)\n* ''Mumbai Love'' (2014)\n* ''[[Bonifacio: Ang Unang Pangulo]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Kid Kulafu]]'' (2015) - with [[Star Cinema]]\n* ''[[Ma' Rosa]]'' (2016)\n* ''Mulat'' (2016)\n* ''Apocalypse Child'' (2016)\n* ''[[Ang Larawan]]'' (2017, 43rd Metro Manila Film Festival's Best Picture)\n* ''[[Siargao (film)|Siargao]]'' (2017, 43rd Metro Manila Film Festival's 2nd Best Picture)\n* ''[[Citizen Jake]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Mary, Marry Me]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Rainbow's Sunset]]'' (2018)\n\n==Broadcast assets==\n\n===Terrestrial TV channels===\n* ''[[ETC (Philippine TV network)|ETC]]'' (Cable TV: 2004-present, [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN 21]]: 2008\u20132011, 2013\u2013present, [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]]: 2011\u20132013)\n* ''[[Shop TV]]'' (2005\u2013present, digital platform only)\n\n===Cable TV channels===\n* ''[[Solar Sports]]'' (1994\u2013present, formerly Solar Entertainment Channel)\n\n===Former subsidiary, divisions and broadcast assets===\n* ''[[Nine Media Corporation]]'' (formerly, Solar Television Network, Inc.; sold to [[Antonio Cabangon-Chua|ALC Group of Companies]])\n** ''[[Solar News Channel]]'' (2012\u20132014)\n** ''[[9TV]]'' (2014\u20132015)\n** ''[[Radio Philippines Network]]'' (34%)\n* ''[[Intercontinental Broadcasting Corporation]]'' (For ''[[NBA]]'', ''[[Shop TV]]'' & ''[[Jai alai|Jai-Alai Games]]'')\n\n===Defunct cable channels and digital TV distribution===\n* ''[[2nd Avenue (TV channel)|2nd Avenue]]'' (Cable TV: 2005\u20132018, [[Rajah Broadcasting Network|RJTV 29]]: 2008\u20132018, formerly ETC 2nd Avenue)\n* ''[[9TV]]'' (34% joint venture with [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]]: 2014\u20132015; owned by [[Nine Media Corporation]])\n* ''[[Aniplus Asia]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[Basketball TV|BTV]]'' (2006\u20132019)\n* ''[https://whatson.astro.com.my/channels/boo/251/?cat=movies&lang=multiple-language&stb=404 Boo] (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[C/S Origin]]'' (2008\u20132009)\n* ''[[C/S 9]]'' (Cable TV: 2005\u20132007, [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]]: 2008\u20132009)\n* ''[[CT (TV channel)|CT]]'' (2015\u20132017)\n* ''[[Chase (TV channel)|Chase]]'' ([[Broadcast Enterprises and Affiliated Media|BEAM TV 31]]: 2011\u20132012)\n* ''[[Diva Universal (Philippines)|Hallmark Channel/Diva Universal Philippines]]'' (2009\u20132013)<sup>1</sup>\n* ''[[Jack City]]'' ([[Broadcast Enterprises and Affiliated Media|BEAM TV 31]]: 2012\u20132014, Cable TV: 2014\u20132015)\n* ''[[Jack TV]]'' (2005\u20132020)\n* ''[[K-Plus (Southeast Asia)|K-Plus]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[Living Asia Channel]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[MTV (Southeast Asia)|MTV]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[MTVph]]'' (2017\u20132018, joint venture with [[Viacom International Media Networks Asia]])\n* ''[[My Movie Channel|Blink Cinema/My Movie Channel]]'' (2013\u20132015)\n* ''[[NBA League Pass]]''\n* ''[[NBA Premium TV]]'' (2010\u20132019)\n* ''[[Outdoor Channel]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[Playboy TV]]''\n* ''[[Solar All Access]]'' (2002\u00ac2020, formerly Solar Sports PPV) \n* ''[[Solar News Channel]]'' (34% joint venture with [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]]: 2013\u20132014, [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN 21]]: 2012\u20132013)\n* ''Sports Plus'' (2004\u20132006)\n* ''[[Solar TV]]'' ([[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]]: 2009\u20132011)\n* ''[[C/S|Solar USA]]'' (2001\u20132005)\n* ''[[Talk TV (Philippines)|Talk TV]]'' ([[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN 21]]: 2011\u20132012)\n* ''[[Telenovela Channel]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[The Game Channel|TGC]]'' ([[Broadcast Enterprises and Affiliated Media|BEAM TV 31]]: 2011\u20132012, Cable TV: 2011, 2012\u20132015)\n* ''SciFi/Universal Channel Philippines'' (2009\u20132012)<sup>1</sup>\n* ''[[Zee Sine]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[ZooMoo]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n\n{{small|<sup>1</sup>Joint venture with [[Universal Networks International]]}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|www.solarentertainmentcorp.com}}\n* [http://philippines.mom-rsf.org/en/owners/companies/ Media Ownership Monitor Philippines - Media Companies: A Duopoly Rules] by VERA Files and [[Reporters Without Borders]]\n\n{{Radio Philippines Network}}\n{{Solar Entertainment}}\n{{Television in the Philippines}}\n{{Philippine cable channels}}\n\n[[Category:Solar Entertainment Corporation| ]]\n[[Category:Media companies of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Philippine radio networks]]\n[[Category:Philippine television networks]]\n[[Category:Television production companies of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Television in Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1976]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1988]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 2008]]\n[[Category:1976 establishments in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:1988 establishments in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Mandaluyong]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Filipino Media Company}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Expert needed|date=February 2016}}\n{{Overly detailed|date=February 2016}}\n{{Self-published|date=February 2016}}\n{{More citations needed|date=February 2016}}}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Solar Entertainment Corporation\n| logo = | \n| caption = | \n| foundation = {{start date and age|1976|1|3}} (as a TV movie company)<br>{{start date and age|1988|7|15}} (as a film distribution company)<br>{{start date and age|2000|6|17}} (as a cable television network)<br>{{start date and age|2008|1|1}} (as a broadcast company)\n| type = [[Private company|Private]] ([[Subsidiary]])\n| traded_as = |\n| predecessor = |\n| location_city = '''Master Playout Facility:''' <br> Third Floor, Worldwide Corporate Center, EDSA corner [[Shaw Boulevard]], [[Mandaluyong|Mandaluyong City]] <br> '''Corporate Offices:''' <br>Solar Century Tower,\n100 Tordesillas St., Corner H.V. Dela Costa St. Salcedo Village, [[Makati City]]\n| location_country = \n| area_served = Nationwide\n| industry = [[Media (communication)|Media company]]\n| services = Free-to-air TV channels and shows, radio broadcasting, cable television, local and international film distribution, film-making, entertainment, television programs and production, news, sports, websites\n| founder = William Y. Tieng<br>Willy Y. Tieng <!-- In other parts of the country remained under the Tieng management and founder led by former Solar Entertainment Corporation Chairman William Tieng and former Solar Entertainment Corporation Vice Chairman Willy Tieng. However, SEC remained as its licensee until July 2015. -->\n| products = [[ETC (Philippine TV network)|ETC]], [[Jack TV]], [[Solar Sports]], Solar Pictures, Solar Scoop, Sinag Maynila Film Festival\n| key_people = Wilson Y. Tieng <small> ([[President (corporate title)|President]] and [[Chief executive officer|CEO]])</small><br>Gidget Lao <small>(Chief Executive for Business Operations)\n| revenue = [[Philippine Peso|PHP]]1.372 billion <small>([[Fiscal year|FY]] 2015)</small><ref name=\"financial\">{{cite web|title=Media Ownnership Monitor Philippines - Solar Entertainment Corporation|url=http://philippines.mom-rsf.org/en/philippines/owners/companies/detail/company/company/show/solar-entertainment-corporation/|access-date=November 24, 2016|publisher=VERA Files}}</ref>\n| operating_income = PHP124.43 million <small>(FY 2015)</small><ref name=\"financial\"/>\n| num_employees = |\n| owner = Solar Films Inc. {{small|(38%)}} <br> Wilson Y. Tieng {{small|(21%)}} <br> William Y. Tieng {{small|(15%)}}\n| subsid = [[ETC (Philippine TV network)|ETC Productions]] <br> [[Southern Broadcasting Network]] <br> [[Easy TV (Philippines)|Solar Digital Media Holdings]] <br> Domestic Satellite Philippines, Inc.\n| homepage = {{URL|www.solarentertainmentcorp.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Solar Entertainment Corporation''' (simply known as '''Solar''' or '''SEC''') is a [[Media in the Philippines|Filipino media company]] founded and owned by the siblings of the Tieng family (Wilson, William and Willy Tieng) which also engages in property development, and distribution of imported products and generic pharmaceutical products. <ref> [http://solarresourcesinc.com/about-us/ Solar Resources - About Us] Solarresourcesinc.com, Accessed on 15 December 2015 </ref>\n\nSolar Entertainment operates two [[Free-to-air|digital free-to-air channels]] and two [[cable television|cable channels]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solarentertainmentcorp.com/about/page/networks|title=List of Solar Networks|website=Solarentertainmentcorp.com}}</ref> Solar also owns a film distribution company (Solar Pictures) and defunct [[freemium]] [[digital television]] service ([[Easy TV (Philippines)|Easy TV Home]]).\n\n==History==\n===Film production and distribution===\nSolar Entertainment was founded and established by the brothers William Tieng, Wilson Tieng and Willy Tieng in 1976.\nSolar Films was then formed in 1988 (one of the first films that distributed by Solar Films is [[Rambo III]] of [[Sylvester Stallone]]), bringing international films (and later, local films since 2009) to the Philippines. Since 2012, Solar has collaborated with independent film director [[Brillante Mendoza]] for a multiple film contract.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.solarentertainmentcorp.com/about/page/solar_today |title=Archived copy |access-date=May 15, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517114818/http://www.solarentertainmentcorp.com/about/page/solar_today |archive-date=May 17, 2014 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On March 18, 2015, Solar launched the Sinag Maynila film festival is, which featured five films from a talented group of directors, each with a different vision and approach. The films were shown in select SM Cinemas from March 18 to 24, 2015. The winners were announced at the \u201cGabi ng Parangal\u201d on March 22.\n\n===Cable television===\nOn January 1, 1994, Solar launched on cable television as the Solar Entertainment Channel.\n\nIn 2000, DOMSAT became Solar's subsidiary. As a result, DOMSAT\u2019s teleport is being used by Solar to produce, originate, and distribute its various television program services. Its full service digital broadcast teleport features server technology facility located in Barangay Sta. Cruz, Sumulong Highway, [[Antipolo City]], Rizal. It is built around two encoder platforms, Scientific Atlanta Power Vu Classic(DVB) and Motorola Digicipher II(MPEG-@). Program origination is done on a SeaChange Media Cluster Server System. The facility includes a 500-square-meter studio and various linear and non-linear production bays.<ref name=\"acquisition\">{{cite news|title= MVP-Ang rivalry set to spill over into television with San Miguel acquisition of Solar stake |url= http://www.spin.ph/sports/basketball/news/mvp-ang-rivalry-set-to-spill-over-into-television-with-san-miguel-acquisition-of-solar-stake|date= November 9, 2013|access-date= August 18, 2014}}</ref> Solar Entertainment first launched its namesake entertainment cable channel in the early 2000s, one devoted to American programs. This channel was later known as Solar USA (the acronym stands for \"Ultimate in Suspense and Action\"), and then later simply as USA before it was replaced by two separate channels.\n\nIn January 2004, Solar launched on cable sports alternative channel as Sports Plus.\n\nOn August 23, 2004, Solar Entertainment launched [[ETC (Philippine TV channel)|ETC]] or Entertainment Central, which is positioned as the country\u2019s premier cable female entertainment channel. ETC is a platform that brings its audience closer to their aspirational lifestyle, as embodied by their idols.\n\nOn May 5, 2005, it test launched delivering debuting service. Intended for a predominantly male audience, the company launched the country\u2019s leading general entertainment cable channel, [[Jack TV]], in July.\n\nOn October 15, 2005, Solar Entertainment launched a crime and action cable channel, Crime/Suspense or [[C/S]].\n\nOn December 15, 2005, Solar Entertainment launched a spin-off channel to ETC, [[2nd Avenue (television channel)|ETC 2nd Avenue]], a lifestyle and general entertainment channel. Started as a test broadcast on December 15, 2005, and had its full launch in 2006. The channel was later renamed as 2nd Avenue on January 17, 2007.\n\nOn October 1, 2006, Sports Plus ceased broadcasting and replaced by the [[Basketball TV]] channel formed by Solar, while moving most of Sports Plus programs to [[Solar Sports]].\n\n===As a broadcast company===\nOn January 1, 2008, Solar Entertainment Corporation began to lease block airtime with terrestrial TV networks, [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN]], [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN]] and [[Rajah Broadcasting Network|RJTV]]. The move was a result of [[SkyCable]] pulling out C/S, ETC, and 2nd Avenue from the cable company's lineup at their own right. Those three started carrying shows from Solar's, with [[C/S]] on RPN, [[ETC (Philippine TV network)|ETC]] on SBN, and [[2nd Avenue (television channel)|2nd Avenue]] on RJTV.\n\n[[File:Solar Sports.png|200px|thumb|left| Former logo of [[Solar Sports]]]]\nOn May 22, 2009, a victory party for [[Manny Pacquiao|Manny \"Pacman\" Pacquiao]], who just became the new IBO (International Boxing Organization) and ''Ring Magazine'' Light Welterweight Champion, was held at the Renaissance Hotel in [[Makati City]], in partnership with [[GMA Network (company)|GMA Network Inc.]] Solar and [[GMA Network|GMA]] executives at that time signed for a partnership in TV coverage of Manny Pacquiao's upcoming boxing matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/photos/1295/gma-victory-party-for-manny-pac-man-pacquiao|title=GMA victory party for Manny 'Pac-Man' Pacquiao|author=|date=|work=PEP.ph|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe C/S cable channel was later rebranded as [[C/S Origin]] in September 2008, while the RPN network later changed its branding to [[C/S 9]] the next month.\n\nOn November 29, 2009, Solar rebranded C/S9 as [[Solar TV]] at 11:00 am with a slogan ''It's A Bright New World'' on RPN. On October 31, 2010, it changed some of its programming content to English/Tagalog with a new slogan ''Kung Saan Lahat Panalo!''.\n\nIn mid-2010, GemCom sold all of its 97% equity share in [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN]] to Solar for Php 368.8 million. Since then, SBN became a fully owned subsidiary of Solar.\n\nOn February 11, 2011, SEC partnered with [[ABS-CBN|ABS-CBN Corporation]] to air [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) games over free TV starting February 19, 2011. The games are aired on [[Studio 23]] (now ABS-CBN Sports and Action later known as [[ABS-CBN Sports and Action|S+A]]) and [[ABS-CBN (television network)|ABS-CBN]], but Solar still airs the games daily on [[Basketball TV|BTV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/sports/02/11/11/abs-cbn-air-nba-all-star-free-tv|title=ABS-CBN to air NBA games on free TV|first=ABS-CBN|last=News|date=|work=ABS-CBN.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Solar TV Network logo.png|200px|thumb|left|Logo of Solar TV as a television network]]\nOn March 2, 2011, after SEC acquired 34 percent of RPN's shares from the Philippine government as part of RPN/IBC privatization in 2011, Solar TV finally ventured into news at the end of 2011. On that same day, ETC moved to [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN]] while TalkTV launched over [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN]]. TalkTV was formed by then Solar-owned Solar Television Network. The first programs that aired on the channel were ''[[Dateline NBC]]'', ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today Show]]'', Today's Talk, ''[[NBC Nightly News]]'', ''[[Inside Edition]]'', ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]'' and ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]''.<ref name=\"manilastandardtoday.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.manilastandardtoday.com/insideBusop.htm?f=2011/february/25/vicagustin.isx&d=2011/february/25|title=Tiengs move into news|last=Agustin|first=Victor C.|date=February 25, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714043823/http://www.manilastandardtoday.com/insideBusop.htm?f=2011%2Ffebruary%2F25%2Fvicagustin.isx&d=2011%2Ffebruary%2F25|archivedate=July 14, 2011|access-date=December 10, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>[http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/214215/news/nation/coloma-privatization-of-rpn-9-ibc-13-in-the-works Coloma: Privatization of RPN 9, IBC 13 in the works] ''[[GMA News and Public Affairs|GMA News Online]]''. 03-01-2011 Retrieved 03-01-2011{{Clarify|reason=ambiguous date format|date=April 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn April 8, 2011, Solar Entertainment Corporation launched [[The Game Channel]] on [[Destiny Cable]]. It conducted its initial test broadcast from April 8, 2011, until September 29. It then began airing on [[Broadcast Enterprises and Affiliated Media|BEAM Channel 31]] on August 15, 2011, after BEAM and Solar signed an affiliation deal, which gave the latter the use of the former's facilities. Full broadcast started on September 30, 2011.\n\nIn May 2011, [[ETC (Philippine TV channel)|ETC]] launched the slogan \"Young and Loving It\". It also saw new programs such as the reality series ''[[The Rachel Zoe Project]]'' and ''Bachelor Pad'', drama series ''[[Nikita (TV series)|Nikita]]'', and ''[[The Secret Circle (TV series)|The Secret Circle]]'', US reality series ''[[The Glee Project]]'', comedy shows like ''[[New Girl]]'' and [[2 Broke Girls]], and local lifestyle show ''[[Etcetera (TV program)|Etcetera]]''. In 2012, ETC includes the reality show ''[[American Idol]]'', local programs like ''[[Project Runway Philippines]]'' (season 3), drama series ''[[The Lying Game (TV series)|The Lying Game]]'', ''[[Emily Owens, M.D.|Emily Owens MD]]'' and ''[[Beauty and the Beast (2012 TV series)|Beauty and the Beast]]'', and local infotainment show ''[[ETC HQ]]''. In 2013, ETC aired comedy-drama series ''[[The Carrie Diaries (TV series)|The Carrie Diaries]]'', sitcom series ''[[Super Fun Night]]'', supernatural drama series ''[[Ravenswood (TV series)|Ravenswood]]'', horror fantasy drama series ''[[The Originals (TV series)|The Originals]]'' and among others.\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:SolarNews.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Logo as the Solar News and Current Affairs from 2011 until August 22, 2014{{deletable image-caption|date=3 July 2016}}]] -->\n[[Solar News]], known for its back-to-basics and unbiased journalism,{{According to whom|date=April 2017}} was formed in January 2012 during the coverage of the impeachment trial of former Chief Justice Renato Corona. Post-EDSA revolution [[ABS-CBN (television network)|ABS-CBN]] newsmen Pal Marquez, Jing Magsaysay and [[Pia Hontiveros]] together with former ANC anchors [[Claire Celdran]], [[Mai Rodriguez]] and Nancy Irlanda, known as the pillars of Solar News.{{According to whom|date=April 2017}} Most of its news reporters are from [[ABS-CBN (television network)|ABS-CBN]] and [[ABS-CBN News Channel|ANC]], as well as from [[NewsWatch (Philippine TV program)|RPN NewsWatch]].<ref>[http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/276523/economy/companies/200-rpn-9-employees-to-lose-jobs 200 RPN 9 employees to lose jobs] ''[[GMA News and Public Affairs|GMA News]]''. 10-02-2012 Retrieved 10-02-2012</ref><ref>[http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/business/10/04/12/ramon-ang-says-talks-buy-solar-entertainment Ramon Ang says in talks to buy Solar Entertainment] ''[[ABS-CBN News and Current Affairs|ABS-CBN News]]''. 10-04-2012 Retrieved 10-04-2012</ref>\n\nOn December 24, 2011, The Game Channel limited its broadcast on daytime sharing with a new programming service called [[Chase (TV channel)|CHASE]] which takes over the evening block. In February 2012, both services aired a promotion, announcing the split of CHASE and TGC to form themselves as separate channels. On February 15, 2012, The Game Channel finally shuts down on free TV and was relaunched as a cable channel; CHASE was also relaunched as a separate channel, now occupying the entire BEAM broadcast airtime on Free TV.\n\nOn April 3, 2012, Solar transferred its former Salcedo Village facilities to their new facility in Worldwide Corporate Center in [[Mandaluyong|Mandaluyong City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medianewser.com/2012/04/solar-news-update-debuts-new-look.html|title=Solar News Update debuts new look|website=Medianewser.com}}</ref> It also featured a newly constructed set for Solar's then-news division, which would become fully functional three months later.\n\nOn July 16, 2012, Solar News launched its first local newscast ''Solar Network News'', followed by ''Solar Nightly News'', an hourly Solar News Update, Solar Daybreak, and Solar Newsday.\n\nOn September 7, 2012, Jack TV plugged their announcement through CHASE programs bearing the title \"Another Jack TV is rising, coming soon on this channel\" (BEAM Channel 31). This indicated that CHASE was being replaced; finally, on October 20, 2012, Jack City was then launched, marking October 19 as the end of CHASE's broadcasts. [[Jack City]] still does carry some of CHASE's programs however.\n\nIn October 2012, it was found out that Solar News would replace the government-controlled RPN News, as a result of RPN's privatization, making Solar TV covering the entire network's airtime. More than 200 RPN employees, particularly those from the labor union and the NewsWatch staff, were retrenched and RPN News was closed down on October 29, effectively axing NewsWatch and NewsCap. Some retrenched government employees were relocated to either [[People's Television Network|People's Television Network (PTV 4)]] or [[Intercontinental Broadcasting Corporation|Intercontinental Broadcasting Corporation (IBC 13)]] (both State-run broadcasters).\n\n[[File:FvfOmbudsman0222 37.JPG|thumb|left|200px|A [[Toyota HiAce]] van used by Solar News parked at the Office of the Ombudsman.]]\nOn October 30, 2012, at 5:45 am, TalkTV was replaced as Solar News Channel on Channel 21 via [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN]]. The channel saw the relaunch of sports news program ''Solar Sports Desk'' (now known as [[Sports Desk (2004 TV series)|CNN Philippines Sports Desk]]), as well as the initial telecast of the Solar News and Current affairs block in November 2012 comprising five public affairs programs ([[Legal Help Desk|Legal HD]], [[MedTalk]], [[News.PH]], [[Opposing Views]], Elections 2013 and [[News Cafe]]), ''[[60 Minutes]]'', ''[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]'', ''[[Undercover Boss (U.S. TV series)|Undercover Boss]]'' and the \"Stories\" [[documentary film|documentaries]] block. In January 2013, Solar News Cebuano (now known as [[CNN Philippines Cebuano News]]) made history as the first national newscast delivered in a local dialect. In 2014, it also launched the [[Kapampangan language|Kapampangan]] national newscast, [[Kapampangan News]] and the public service program ''[[Serbisyo All Access]]'', which is shown in [[Filipino language]].\n\nPrior to the channel's transfer to RPN, SNC's flagship newscast (Solar Network News) simulcasted on RPN 9 (free TV only) from the SNC's launch. The news content for RPN (then affiliated with ETC), however, was switched to ''Solar Nightly News'' on January 14, 2013, onwards, to avoid backlash from free TV viewers, particularly Free TV viewers of ''[[American Idol]]'' (in which the original plan was to replace the 6 pm via satellite broadcast to Free TV viewers by Network News, then airs the AI episodes at the 8 pm rerun in simulcast with cable and satellite viewers). Throughout the ''American Idol'' season, as the episodes are repeated at 8 PM on cable, Solar used the separate free TV-only feed, that contains reruns of selected ETC shows (but with advertisements replaced by ETC teasers and promotions) at 8&nbsp;pm and ''Nightly News'' at 9 PM (with additional ETC programs, if necessary) to be used by RPN after each AI via satellite episode before RPN returns to the main ETC feed at 10 PM. This is to retain RPN's news content as it then has no newscast since the axing of NewsWatch.\n\nOn January 3, 2013, SEC launched Blink Cinema (later renamed as [[My Movie Channel]]) with the full broadcast taking effect later that month.\n\nOn April 14, 2013, [[TV5 Network (company)|TV5 Network Inc.]] and Solar Entertainment Corporation joined to broadcast the [[2013 FIBA Asia Championship]] in Manila on Philippine television on August 1\u201311. Aside from [[TV5 (Philippines)|TV5]] and its sister channel ([[AksyonTV]]), the games were also broadcast over Solar\u2019s cable channel [[Basketball TV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interaksyon.com/interaktv/tv5-solar-team-up-for-2013-fiba-asia-championship-coverage|title=TV5, Solar team up for 2013 FIBA Asia Championship coverage - InterAksyon.com - Sports5|author=|date=|work=InterAksyon.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===New management===\nOn May 22, 2013, Solar Entertainment Corporation appointed two officers to manage its broadcasting and cable businesses: Manuel \u201cMeckoy\u201d Quiogue as chief commercial officer and Maria Theresa \u201cMitos\u201d Borromeo as chief operating officer (COO).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.9news.ph/lifestyle/2013/05/22/solar-entertainment-corp.-appoints-2-new-officers|title=9news.ph - 9news Resources and Information.|author=|date=|work=9news.ph|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> However, Quiogue suddenly died on May 31, 2013 prior to assuming his position.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bworldonline.com/weekender/content.php?id=73221|title=Your life is your message to the world|work=BWorldOnline.com|access-date=April 6, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923221542/http://www.bworldonline.com/weekender/content.php?id=73221|archivedate=September 23, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn June 28, 2013, [[Jack City]] reduced its free TV broadcast to 18 hours a day on BEAM in compliance with the [[National Telecommunications Commission]]'s guidelines. However, it still continues to air as a cable channel 24 hours a day.\n\nOn November 9, 2013, [[San Miguel Corporation]]'s president and COO, [[Ramon S. Ang|Ramon Ang]], explored the possibility of acquiring a controlling stake in Solar Entertainment Corporation in his personal capacity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/business/13606-san-miguel-s-ang-keen-on-solar-tv,-owner-of-rpn-9|title=San Miguel's Ang keen on Solar TV, owner of RPN-9|author=|date=|work=Rappler.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interaksyon.com/business/46828/meeting-of-minds-reached-in-talks-with-ramon-ang-for-investment-says-solar-chairman|title='Meeting of minds' reached in talks with Ramon Ang for investment, says Solar chairman|author=|date=|work=InterAksyon.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> However, no further announcements were made after this and Ang subsequently reached an agreement to acquire a minority stake.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interaksyon.com/business/93653/exclusive--businessmirror-owner-acquires-majority-stake-in-rpn9|title=EXCLUSIVE - BusinessMirror owner acquires biggest stake in RPN9|work=InterAksyon.com|access-date=April 6, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140822083909/http://www.interaksyon.com/business/93653/exclusive--businessmirror-owner-acquires-majority-stake-in-rpn9|archivedate=August 22, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Solar News Channel]] and its partnership moved to [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]] on December 1, 2013, while ETC returned to SBN Channel 21 a day before. (ETC was aired on [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN-21]] from 2008 to 2011 then to RPN-9 from 2011 to 2013),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.inquirer.net/177231/new-investor-vows-to-turn-rpn-9-around|title=New investor vows to turn RPN 9 around|first=Miguel R. Camus and Doris C.|last=Dumlao|date=|work=Inquirer.net|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> as well as the launch of Solar's video-on-demand website Blink. As a result of the channel swap (on RPN's part), Network News and Nightly News became newscasts on its own right.\n\nIn 2014, Solar Entertainment's Solar One Boracay happened during the Labor Day weekend to showcase its channels (ETC, 2nd Avenue, JackTV, JackCITY, My Movie Channel, The Game Channel, Solar Sports, BTV and NBA Premium TV) through various summer activities all over the island.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thedistrictboracay.com/solar-one-boracay-at-the-district-boracay/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=March 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402164529/http://www.thedistrictboracay.com/solar-one-boracay-at-the-district-boracay/ |archive-date=April 2, 2015 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn August 20, 2014, Solar Entertainment Corporation chief Wilson Tieng announced that he ceded his entire share on [[Solar TV Network]], Inc., including its 34% majority share on RPN, to [[Antonio Cabangon Chua]], owner of business daily [[BusinessMirror]] and [[Aliw Broadcasting Corporation]].<ref>[http://www.interaksyon.com/business/93653/exclusive--businessmirror-owner-acquires-majority-stake-in-rpn9 Exclusive: BusinessMirror owner acquires majority stake in RPN9] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140822083909/http://www.interaksyon.com/business/93653/exclusive--businessmirror-owner-acquires-majority-stake-in-rpn9 |date=August 22, 2014 }}, InterAksyon.com, August 20, 2014</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2014/08/21/1360003/cabangon-chua-acquires-rpn-9|title=Cabangon-Chua acquires RPN-9|first=Lawrence|last=Agcaoili|date=August 21, 2014|work=PhilStar.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> Tieng sold Solar TV because they were losing money for operations after purchasing RPN. As a result of this ownership change, STVNI, Solar News Channel and RPN's majority stake were separated from the Tiengs; while ETC, 2nd Avenue, and Jack City reverted to Solar Entertainment's ownership.\n\nOn September 1, 2014, [[Jack City]] ended its run on free TV due to the preparations being made by [[Broadcast Enterprises and Affiliated Media|BEAM 31]] for the incoming transition to ISDB-T digital television, though it continues to be broadcast as a separate cable channel. However, Jack City continued to broadcast on cable networks until March 21, 2015. After Jack City's closure to free TV, BEAM aired under blocktime programs from various local production and religious companies. On November 15, 2014, BEAM began being carried on [[SkyCable]] and Destiny Cable subscribers (per compliance with NTC's \"must-carry\" basis). This move resulted of Jack City in a change of its channel assignment for SkyCable and [[Destiny Cable]] subscribers, as well as several pay TV companies.\n\nIn 2015, Solar Entertainment Corporation launched the #1stonPHTV brand of Solar channels for [[ETC (Philippine TV channel)|ETC]], [[2nd Avenue (television channel)|2nd Avenue]], [[Jack TV]], Jack City and [[My Movie Channel]], with the brand implemented on January 6, 2015. Since then, all SEC channels broadcast first-run foreign television programs with the hashtag #1stonPHTV (First on Philippine TV), which was formerly known as \"Match Airing\" (ETC), \"Playing 1st\" (Jack TV), \"The Newest in the US\" and \"FastCast\" (2nd Avenue) and \"See It First\" (Jack City).\n\n[[The Game Channel]], after almost three years on broadcasting, selling or ceased on February 28, 2015. The channel space was taken over by [[My Movie Channel]] on March 1.\n\nOn March 22, 2015, Jack City was replaced by [[CT (TV channel)|CT]], thus becoming independent from its parent network. Upon launch, the channel broadened its programming focus by adding talk shows, sitcoms and men's lifestyle programs to its roster.\n\nOn March 26, 2015, Solar Entertainment announced its broadcast of the \"Fight Of The Century\" between [[Manny Pacquiao]] and [[Floyd Mayweather Jr.]] on May 3, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/sports/2015/03/27/1437964/abs-cbn-gma-tv5-join-hands-air-pacquiao-fight-networks-unite-historic|title=ABS-CBN, GMA, TV5 join hands to air Pacquiao fight: Networks unite for historic broadcast|first=Abac|last=Cordero|date=March 27, 2015|work=PhilStar.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> As stated in a press conference that day, it was broadcast on May 3 via delayed broadcast in three major television stations in the Philippines, [[ABS-CBN (television network)|ABS-CBN]], [[TV5 (Philippines)|TV5]], and [[GMA Network]] (who waived its exclusive contract with Solar to allow its multi-network coverage, but maintained its exclusive live broadcast on its radio division), with [[Solar Sports]] as its main content provider for this historic event in boxing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/sports/by-sport/boxing-mma/pacquiao/88062-pacquiao-mayweather-television-broadcast-ph|title=Pacquiao vs Mayweather to be televised by GMA, ABS-CBN and TV5|author=|date=|work=Rappler.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/459458/sports/boxing/pacquiao-mayweather-fight-to-air-live-over-gma-radio-stations-nationwide|title=Pacquiao-Mayweather fight to air live over GMA radio stations nationwide|author=|date=|work=GMANetwork.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2015, My Movie Channel ceased broadcasting. The closure or selling was announced by Solar a day before.\n\n===Rebranding of the four flagship networks===\nOn October 16, 2016, Solar relaunched its flagship channels ETC, 2nd Avenue, Basketball TV and Solar Sports. The four networks unveiled their new logos, on-air graphics and station IDs, which took effect on that day. CT, Jack TV, Shop TV and NBA Premium TV on the other hand remains unchanged. Also that day, Solar launched its corporate campaign slogan ''...There's More To Come'', which evolved in 2017 as ''We go for More''.\n\nIn 2017, Solar Entertainment became the official Philippine broadcaster of the 65th edition of the [[Miss Universe]] in Manila. This led to another deal with [[ABS-CBN]], [[TV5 (Philippines)|TV5]] and [[GMA Network|GMA]] (the second time that such deal happened between Solar and the Big 3 networks). According to some sources, a directive from [[Rodrigo Duterte|President Duterte]] ordered that the major networks must cover the prestige pageant as it happens live in the [[Philippines]]. Alongside the Big Three, Solar Entertainment channels [[ETC (Philippine TV network)|etc]], [[2nd Avenue (television channel)|2nd Avenue]], [[Jack TV]] and [[CT (TV channel)|CT]] aired the pageant simultaneously. It was also in the same year when Solar Entertainment forged a joint venture with the Bermuda-based communications satellite company [[Asia Broadcast Satellite]] to launch the first nationwide free-to-air [[Satellite television#Direct broadcast via satellite|direct-to-home]] satellite television services using the [[C band (IEEE)|C-band]], which is set to launch on the 3rd quarter of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.satellitetoday.com/broadcasting/2017/05/22/abs-solar-group-launch-new-dth-service-philippines/|title=ABS, The Solar Group to Launch New DTH Service in the Philippines|author=Kendall Russell|date=May 22, 2017|work=Satellite Today|access-date=July 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Carriage disputes==\n===Sky Cable===\n====2008====\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2014}}\nSolar's channels have ceased airing on [[Sky Cable]], the Philippines' largest cable television provider. An insider{{Who|date=April 2017}} claims that these troubles with Sky Cable started when boxer [[Manny Pacquiao]], whose fights Solar Entertainment has the exclusive right to air and distribute to, moved from [[ABS-CBN]], the flagship television network of [[ABS-CBN Corporation]] and the primary owner of [[Sky Cable Corporation]], to rival [[GMA Network]]. Another insider{{Who|date=April 2017}} claims that SkyCable wanted to remove [[ETC (Philippine TV channel)|ETC]] and [[Jack TV]] to make room for their own channels, [[Velvet (TV channel)|Velvet]] (now defunct) and [[Maxxx]] (now defunct). Sky Cable wanted to retain [[C/S]], [[2nd Avenue (television channel)|2nd Avenue]], [[Solar Sports]] and [[Basketball TV]], but Solar made a decision that they would only renew their contract if Sky Cable carried all six channels. Thus, Solar decided to pull out all their channels rather than remove ETC and Jack TV.\n\nHowever, Solar has signed a deal with local terrestrial channels [[TV5 (Philippines)|ABC]], [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN]], [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN]] and [[Rajah Broadcasting Network|RJTV]] for block-time programming. C/S, ETC and 2nd Avenue programming are seen on terrestrial TV channels RPN, SBN and RJTV, respectively, while [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] and [[WWE]] programming were seen on TV5, now moved to RPN (WWE programming are currently being broadcast thru TV5, while its terrestrial NBA coverage were moved to [[ABS-CBN Sports]] under Solar).\n\nMost of its channels were later returned to Sky Cable, while Jack TV would eventually return to its lineup on January 1, 2010 replacing Maxxx.\n\nMeanwhile, Pacquiao's boxing promotion, [[Top Rank]], signed a non-guaranteed contract with [[ABS-CBN Sports]] to exclusively air fights promoted by Top Rank, with the exception of Pacquiao fights which are still signed exclusively through Solar Entertainment.\n\n====2017\u201319====\nOn April 10, 2017, 3 days before the [[2017 NBA Playoffs]] was scheduled to begin (and coincided with the final day of the [[2016\u201317 NBA season|2016\u201317 NBA regular season]]), Basketball TV, [[NBA Premium TV]], Solar Sports, Jack TV and [[CT (TV channel)|CT]] (now defunct) were removed by Solar from Sky Cable (including [[Sky Direct]], [[Destiny Cable]] & [[Sky On Demand]] thru video on demand) without any prior announcement from Solar.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rappler.com/sports/by-sport/basketball/nba/167065-sky-nba-premium-btv-unavailable |title=Sky subscribers frustrated as NBA Premium, BTV unavailable for playoffs start |last= Rola|first=Alyssa |date= April 16, 2017|website=[[Rappler]] |access-date= April 16, 2017|quote=}}</ref> Initially, both Basketball TV and NBA Premium TV were replaced by airing a simulcast of [[ABS-CBN Sports and Action]] with a ticker announcing the unavailability of the channels, with Solar Sports, Jack TV and CT (now defunct) also doing the latter albeit with a black screen. Later, almost all of the pulled-out Solar channels were replaced by an imaging card, initially detailing the unavailability of the channels and then later, announcing that they will discuss with Solar on returning the aforementioned channels; while for BTV and NBA Premium TV, a schedule of the NBA games that will air on [[ABS-CBN]], ABS-CBN Sports and Action and [[Fox Sports Asia|Fox Sports]] within the week and a loop of an NBA promo. Solar did not comment on the situation for the removal of the channels, but sources and some netizens pointed out a carriage dispute between the two parties for not paying an undisclosed price to continue broadcasting these channels, which was later proven true by an article published by the ''[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]''.\n\nAs the dispute continued, some media enthusiasts and netizens raised concerns of whether these Solar channels will return to Sky and/or Destiny. Others pointed that inaction between the two parties could affect the next long-term local broadcast franchise with the NBA, slated to begin at the Association's 2019-2020 regular season. (Currently, Solar and Sky's parent, ABS-CBN, have a shared broadcast agreement to air the NBA games on pay and terrestrial television, respectively. Rumours circulated that both networks may bid separately, if they could not reach renewal, and use their respective infrastructure to broadcast adequate NBA coverage; otherwise, rival networks with a functioning sports department like [[5 (TV channel)|The 5 Network]] may also seek their own bidding to steal the 2019 contract from both Solar and ABS-CBN.)\n\nNetizens and viewers were dismayed and frustrated by the removal of the said channels by Sky Cable, most notably for BTV and NBA Premium due to the importance of the Playoffs. Some netizens were angered by the removal of the said channels and asked Sky Cable to return the channels before the scheduled Playoffs would begin, however Sky Cable would respond to angered netizens on social media that they are \"fixing the situation with Solar\". Other netizens and viewers would otherwise switch providers from Sky Cable to other cable companies that carried these channels or to other satellite providers like [[Cignal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spin.ph/basketball/nba/news/sky-cable-nba-premium-basketball-tv-negotiations-with-solar |title=SKYcable unable to give timetable for return of NBA Premium, Basketball TV to channel lineup |last=Terrado |first=Reuben |date=April 15, 2017 |website=[[GMA New Media|Spin.ph]] |access-date=April 16, 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nOn October 16, 2018, Basketball TV and NBA Premium TV returned to Sky Cable, Sky Direct, & Sky On Demand for the first time in 18 months<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.spin.ph/basketball/nba/nba-premium-btv-channels-back-on-skycable-per-advisory-a795-20181016 |title=NBA Premium, BTV channels back on SKYCable, per advisory |last=Terrado |first=Reuben |date=October 16, 2018 |website=[[GMA New Media|Spin.ph]] |access-date=October 26, 2018 |quote=}}</ref>; however it was later removed on October 28, 2018 for unknown reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mysky.com.ph/MetroManila/updates/1031/2018/10/28/sky-advisory|title=SKY Advisory|website=Me & My SKY: SKY at 25 years}}</ref>\n\nThe carriage dispute officially ended on January 1, 2019 when all Solar channels: Basketball TV, NBA Premium TV, Solar Sports, and Jack TV were restored on Sky Cable (including Sky On Demand & Sky Direct).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.ph/basketball/nba/nba-premium-and-btv-are-back-in-skycable-s-channel-lineup-a795-20190101|title=NBA Premium and BTV are back in SKYcable's channel lineup|website=Spin.ph}}</ref>\n\nIronically, [[MTVph]], which is a Solar channel, ended its operations on the same day at that time Sky returned the affected Solar channels. As of 2019, Sky Cable's sister company Destiny Cable still does not carry all the aforementioned Solar channels despite its aforementioned return on Sky Cable.\n\nDuring the aforementioned period, [[Shop TV]], ETC and 2nd Avenue (now defunct) were kept on the air, due to the \"must-carry\" rules by the NTC. MTVph was also kept on the air (until it was discontinued on January 1, 2019) since it was carried in a separate programming agreement outside of the affected channels despite its ownership.\n\n===Dream Satellite TV===\n[[Dream Satellite TV]] ceased carrying three Solar Channels, namely [[Solar Sports]], [[ETC (Philippine TV channel)|ETC]] (which was at that time a cable channel prior to its move to free TV and cable) and [[2nd Avenue (TV channel)|2nd Avenue]] (now defunct) (except [[C/S 9]]) effective 1 February 2009. Dream's carriage contract with Solar Entertainment, which expired on 31 December 2008 was not renewed by Dream, citing financial constraints as its main reason. The three Solar channels were replaced by A&E's [[History (South East Asian TV channel)|The History Channel]], [[Bio. (South East Asia)|Biography Channel]] and [[Crime & Investigation Network (South East Asia)|Crime and Investigation Channel]]. As of 2017, ETC and 2nd Avenue remained on its lineup due to the \"must-carry\" rules of the NTC. \n\nUnfortunately, Dream Satellite ended its operations on December 31, 2017 due to bankruptcy and its competition with other satellite providers.\n\n==Divisions / Subsidiaries==\n* ETC Productions<!-- ETC Productions is a production arm of the female-oriented TV channel, ETC -->\n* Blink\n* Solar Pictures\n* Domestic Satellite Philippines, Inc. (DOMSAT)\n* [[Southern Broadcasting Network]] (acquired in 2010 from Lucio Co's Gem Communications Holdings Corporation)\n* [[Easy TV (Philippines)|Solar Digital Media Holdings]] (operator of Solar's digital television service '''Easy TV Home''')\n\n==Filmography of Solar Pictures==\n===Notable local films released or distributed by Solar Pictures===\n* ''Syota ng Bayan'' (2001)\n* ''[[Batas Militar (2006 film)|Batas Militar]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Pacquiao: The Movie]]'' (2006) - with [[Star Cinema]]\n* ''Anak Ng Kumander'' (2007)\n* ''[[Ang Tanging Pamilya: A Marry Go Round|Ang Tanging Pamilya]]'' (2009) - with [[Star Cinema]]\n* ''[[Kimmy Dora: Kambal sa Kiyeme]]'' (2009) - with [[Star Cinema]]\n* ''[[Wapakman]]'' (2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/cebu-entertainment/483549/8-official-entries-2009-mmff-bared|title=8 official entries to 2009 MMFF bared|author=|date=|work=PhilStar.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Flames of Love'' (2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2012/11/05/863321/flames-love-celebrates-year-faith|title=Flames of Love celebrates the Year of Faith|first=Ricky|last=Lo|date=November 5, 2012|work=PhilStar.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Sapi'' (2013)\n* ''Mumbai Love'' (2014)\n* ''[[Bonifacio: Ang Unang Pangulo]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Kid Kulafu]]'' (2015) - with [[Star Cinema]]\n* ''[[Ma' Rosa]]'' (2016)\n* ''Mulat'' (2016)\n* ''Apocalypse Child'' (2016)\n* ''[[Ang Larawan]]'' (2017, 43rd Metro Manila Film Festival's Best Picture)\n* ''[[Siargao (film)|Siargao]]'' (2017, 43rd Metro Manila Film Festival's 2nd Best Picture)\n* ''[[Citizen Jake]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Mary, Marry Me]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Rainbow's Sunset]]'' (2018)\n\n==Broadcast assets==\n\n===Terrestrial TV channels===\n* ''[[ETC (Philippine TV network)|ETC]]'' (Cable TV: 2004-present, [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN 21]]: 2008\u20132011, 2013\u2013present, [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]]: 2011\u20132013)\n* ''[[Shop TV]]'' (2005\u2013present, digital platform only)\n\n===Cable TV channels===\n* ''[[Solar Sports]]'' (1994\u2013present, formerly Solar Entertainment Channel)\n\n===Former subsidiary, divisions and broadcast assets===\n* ''[[Nine Media Corporation]]'' (formerly, Solar Television Network, Inc.; sold to [[Antonio Cabangon-Chua|ALC Group of Companies]])\n** ''[[Solar News Channel]]'' (2012\u20132014)\n** ''[[9TV]]'' (2014\u20132015)\n** ''[[Radio Philippines Network]]'' (34%)\n* ''[[Intercontinental Broadcasting Corporation]]'' (For ''[[NBA]]'', ''[[Shop TV]]'' & ''[[Jai alai|Jai-Alai Games]]'')\n\n===Defunct cable channels and digital TV distribution===\n* ''[[2nd Avenue (TV channel)|2nd Avenue]]'' (Cable TV: 2005\u20132018, [[Rajah Broadcasting Network|RJTV 29]]: 2008\u20132018, formerly ETC 2nd Avenue)\n* ''[[9TV]]'' (34% joint venture with [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]]: 2014\u20132015; owned by [[Nine Media Corporation]])\n* ''[[Aniplus Asia]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[Basketball TV|BTV]]'' (2006\u20132019)\n* ''[https://whatson.astro.com.my/channels/boo/251/?cat=movies&lang=multiple-language&stb=404 Boo] (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[C/S Origin]]'' (2008\u20132009)\n* ''[[C/S 9]]'' (Cable TV: 2005\u20132007, [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]]: 2008\u20132009)\n* ''[[CT (TV channel)|CT]]'' (2015\u20132017)\n* ''[[Chase (TV channel)|Chase]]'' ([[Broadcast Enterprises and Affiliated Media|BEAM TV 31]]: 2011\u20132012)\n* ''[[Diva Universal (Philippines)|Hallmark Channel/Diva Universal Philippines]]'' (2009\u20132013)<sup>1</sup>\n* ''[[Jack City]]'' ([[Broadcast Enterprises and Affiliated Media|BEAM TV 31]]: 2012\u20132014, Cable TV: 2014\u20132015)\n* ''[[Jack TV]]'' (2005\u20132020)\n* ''[[K-Plus (Southeast Asia)|K-Plus]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[Living Asia Channel]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[MTV (Southeast Asia)|MTV]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[MTVph]]'' (2017\u20132018, joint venture with [[Viacom International Media Networks Asia]])\n* ''[[My Movie Channel|Blink Cinema/My Movie Channel]]'' (2013\u20132015)\n* ''[[NBA League Pass]]''\n* ''[[NBA Premium TV]]'' (2010\u20132019)\n* ''[[Outdoor Channel]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[Playboy TV]]''\n* ''[[Solar All Access]]'' (2002-2017, formerly Solar Sports PPV) \n* ''[[Solar News Channel]]'' (34% joint venture with [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]]: 2013\u20132014, [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN 21]]: 2012\u20132013)\n* ''Sports Plus'' (2004\u20132006)\n* ''[[Solar TV]]'' ([[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]]: 2009\u20132011)\n* ''[[C/S|Solar USA]]'' (2001\u20132005)\n* ''[[Talk TV (Philippines)|Talk TV]]'' ([[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN 21]]: 2011\u20132012)\n* ''[[Telenovela Channel]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[The Game Channel|TGC]]'' ([[Broadcast Enterprises and Affiliated Media|BEAM TV 31]]: 2011\u20132012, Cable TV: 2011, 2012\u20132015)\n* ''SciFi/Universal Channel Philippines'' (2009\u20132012)<sup>1</sup>\n* ''[[Zee Sine]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[ZooMoo]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n\n{{small|<sup>1</sup>Joint venture with [[Universal Networks International]]}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|www.solarentertainmentcorp.com}}\n* [http://philippines.mom-rsf.org/en/owners/companies/ Media Ownership Monitor Philippines - Media Companies: A Duopoly Rules] by VERA Files and [[Reporters Without Borders]]\n\n{{Radio Philippines Network}}\n{{Solar Entertainment}}\n{{Television in the Philippines}}\n{{Philippine cable channels}}\n\n[[Category:Solar Entertainment Corporation| ]]\n[[Category:Media companies of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Philippine radio networks]]\n[[Category:Philippine television networks]]\n[[Category:Television production companies of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Television in Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1976]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1988]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 2008]]\n[[Category:1976 establishments in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:1988 establishments in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Mandaluyong]]\n", "name_user": "112.198.211.70", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eDefunct cable channels and digital TV distribution)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solar_Entertainment_Corporation"}
{"title_page": "Lil Skies", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist https://shrinkme.io/lA0dxZ1Z\n| name             = Lil Skies\n| background       = solo_singer<!--includes rappers-->\n| image            = Lil_Skies_2019.png\n| caption          = Lil Skies in 2018\n| birth_name       = Kimetrius Christopher Foose\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1998|8|4}}\n| birth_place      = [[Chambersburg, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Rapper|singer|songwriter}}\n| origin           = [[Waynesboro, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]|[[trap music|trap]]|[[emo rap]]||[[contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[cloud rap]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://revolt.tv/stories/2018/08/15/emo-rap-genre-artists-review-restrictions-07008fed7a|title=The claustrophobic air of emo rap will kill the genre|website=REVOLT TV}}</ref>}}\n| years_active     = 2012\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|All We Got|[[Atlantic Records]]|[[Roc Nation]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Gucci Mane]]|Landon Cube|Spirte Lee|[[Machine Gun Kelly (musician)|Machine Gun Kelly]]|[[Wiz Khalifa]]|Yung Pinch}}\n| website          = {{url|lilskiesofficial.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Kimetrius Christopher Foose''' (born August 4, 1998), known by his stage name '''Lil Skies''', is an American rapper, singer and songwriter from [[Waynesboro, Pennsylvania|Waynesboro]], [[Pennsylvania]] currently signed to All We Got Entertainment through [[Atlantic Records]]. His top three highest charting tracks on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] are \"[[I (Lil Skies song)|I]]\" (#39), \"[[Nowadays]]\" (#55), and \"[[Red Roses (song)|Red Roses]]\" (#69). His major label debut mixtape, ''[[Life of a Dark Rose]]'', was released on January 10, 2018 and peaked at #10 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart. The mixtape was certified Gold by the [[RIAA]] on November 9, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?share=19182&t=t|title=LIL SKIES - LIFE OF A DARK ROSE|website=RIAA}}</ref> He released his debut studio album, [[Shelby (album)|''Shelby'']], on March 1, 2019. On March 4, 2020, Skies released the song \"Havin My Way\", featuring [[Lil Durk]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/lil-skies-and-lil-durk-dont-miss-on-havin-my-way-new-song.1986406.html|title=Lil Skies & Lil Durk Don't Miss On \"Havin My Way\"|last=Zidel|first=Alex|date=March 4, 2020|website=[[HotNewHipHop]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nKimetrius Christopher Foose was born August 4, 1998 in [[Chambersburg, Pennsylvania]] to multiracial parents.<ref name=\"Genius\">{{cite news | last=Mench| first=Chris| title =From Waynesboro To The Web: Lil Skies Is On The Verge Of Breaking Out| newspaper =| publisher =| date =December 5, 2017 | url =https://genius.com/a/from-waynesboro-to-the-web-lil-skies-is-on-the-verge-of-breaking-out| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Stokey\">{{cite news| last =Adams| first =Joi S.| title =New TSP Artist Alert: Lil Skies Releases Video For \"Some Way\"| newspaper =| publisher =The Stokey Project| date =April 1, 2017| url =https://www.thestokeyproject.com/single-post/2017/04/01/New-TSP-Artist-Alert-Lil-Skies-Releases-Video-For-%E2%80%9CSome-Way%E2%80%9D| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Foose began writing songs at age 4. He was introduced to music by his father, Michael Burton, Jr., a fellow hip hop artist formerly known as Dark Skies, now as BurntMan, and his mother Shelby Feliciano. Foose's stage name is a play on his father's.<ref name=\"Elevator\">{{cite news | last=McCarthy| first=Liam| title =Going Up w/ Lil Skies| hnewspaper =| publisher =Elevator Magazine| date = September 5, 2017| url =http://www.elevatormag.com/going-up-w-lil-skies/| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ShipNC\">{{cite news | last=Bonura| first=Denise| title =Reaching for the stars: Lil Skies to open for Fetty Wap | newspaper =Shippensburg News Chronicle| publisher =| date =October 20, 2016 | url =http://www.shipnc.com/news/local/article_0b5d2f38-9639-11e6-9a86-bf8da9fc1cd0.html| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref> Foose and his family moved to Waynesboro, Pennsylvania when he was in third grade.<ref name=\"Stokey\"/> He started his career with help from his friend, Landon Cube and with his cousin, Marco Feliciano. When he was 11, his father was injured in a workplace chemical explosion at the Rust-Oleum plant near [[Williamsport, Maryland]]. For the meantime he would spend the summer at a relatives' house; it was at that point in time he worked in collaboration with his cousin Marco Feliciano, on his first project released on August 14, entitled, \"Birth of Skies Vol. 1\". Foose and his father would write an album the following year, ''Father-Son Talk'', discussing the recovery process.<ref name=\"RH\">{{cite news | last=Bonura| first=Denise| title =Michael Burton Jr. of Waynesboro emerges stronger after suffering third-degree burns in Rust-Oleum chemical\u2026| newspaper =The Record Herald| publisher =| date =March 28, 2014 | url =http://www.therecordherald.com/article/20140328/news/140329752| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref> Foose graduated from [[Waynesboro Area Senior High School]] in 2016<ref name=\"RH2\">{{cite news | last=| first=| title =Waynesboro Area Senior High School Class of 2016| newspaper =The Record Herald| publisher =| date =May 27, 2016| url =http://www.therecordherald.com/article/20160527/NEWS/160529855| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref> and briefly attended [[Shippensburg University of Pennsylvania]] before dropping out to focus on his rap career.<ref name=\"Genius\" />\n\n==Career==\nIn October 2016, Foose opened for [[Fetty Wap]] at Shippensburg University<ref name=\"ShipNC\"/> and later released his first mixtape, ''Alone'', in January 2017.<ref name=\"Drill\">{{cite web | last=Jackson| first=Shawn| title =Lil Skies Drops \u2018Alone\u2019 An AyRap Delicacy| website=Drill Kings| date =January 25, 2017 | url =https://www.drillking.org/lil-skies-drops-alone-an-ayrap-delicacy/| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref> In July 2017, he released two songs, \"Red Roses\" featuring Landon Cube<ref name=\"DrillRoses\">{{cite web | last=Jackson| first=Shawn| title =Lil Skies Teams Up With Landon Cube For \u2018Red Roses\u2019| website=Drill Kings| date =July 24, 2017 | url =https://www.drillking.org/lil-skies-teams-up-with-landon-cube-for-red-roses/| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref> and \"Off The Goop\" featuring Sprite Lee.<ref name=\"ElevatorSprite\">{{cite news | last=Hef| first=Hollywood| title =Lil Skies & Sprite Lee unleash catchy new jam \"Off The Goop\"| work=Elevator Magazine| date =July 17, 2017 | url =http://www.elevatormag.com/lil-skies-sprite-lee-unleash-catchy-new-jam-off-the-goop/| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref> He would later release other songs that year, including \"Rude\" and \"Signs of Jealousy.\"<ref name=\"Complex\">{{cite news | last=Ortiz| first=Edwin| title =Premiere: Lil Skies Stunts in \"Signs of Jealousy\" Video| work=Complex| date =November 14, 2017 | url =http://www.complex.com/music/2017/11/lil-skies-signs-of-jealousy-video| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFoose's repertoire of singles caught the attention of [[Atlantic Records]] who partnered with his own label, All We Got.<ref name=\"Genius\"/><ref name=\"All\">{{cite web | last=Thomas| first=Fred| title =Artist Biography by Fred Thomas| website =AllMusic| date =December 2017 | url =https://www.allmusic.com/artist/lil-skies-mn0003677493/biography| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref> He released his first major label mixtape, ''Life of a Dark Rose'', on January 10, 2018.<ref name=\"XXL\">{{cite news |last=Coleman II |first=C. Vernon |title=Lil Skies Releases \u2018Life of a Dark Rose\u2019 Mixtape |work=XXL |date =January 10, 2018 |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/new-music/2018/01/lil-skies-life-of-a-dark-rose-mixtape/ |accessdate=February 12, 2018}}</ref> The album debuted at #23<ref name=\"BillDebut\">{{cite news | last=Zellner| first=Xander| title =Lil Skies Makes Billboard Hot 100 Debut With 'Nowadays' & 'Red Roses'| work=Billboard| date =January 17, 2018 | url =https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/8094756/lil-skies-makes-billboard-hot-100-debut-with-nowadays-red-roses| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref> on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' 200 chart and went on to peak at #10.<ref name=\"Bill200\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/2018-01-27 |title=Billboard 200 - The Week of January 27, 2018 |website=Billboard |accessdate=February 12, 2018}}</ref> The songs \"Nowadays\" and \"Red Roses\" (both featuring Landon Cube) debuted on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 list at #85 and #98 respectively<ref name=\"URDebut\">{{cite news | last=Williams| first=Aaron| title =Lil Skies Is Already Chartings And Showing All The Signs Of A Star In The Making| work=Uproxx| date =January 17, 2018 | url =http://uproxx.com/hiphop/lil-skies-life-of-a-dark-horse-debut-billboard-charts/| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref> and have since peaked at #55 and #69 (also respectively).<ref name=\"Bill100\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2018-01-27 |title=The Hot 100 - The Week of January 27, 2018 |website=Billboard |accessdate=February 12, 2018}}</ref> He also toured nationally with [[Lil Uzi Vert]] in 2017 and began his \"Life of a Dark Rose\" tour in 2018, but had to end the tour short due to illness.<ref name=\"XXL\"/> On May 4, 2018, the music video for \"Lust\" was released, peaking at number 87 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and being certified platinum by the RIAA.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8454621/lil-skies-lust-animated-hip-hop-videos|title=Lil Skies' 'Lust' Continues a Tradition of Animated Hip-Hop Videos: Here Are 15 of the Best|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref> On May 31, he released \"[[I Know You (Lil Skies song)|I Know You]]\" featuring Yung Pinch which peaked at 79 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and is now certified gold by RIAA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/05/lil-skies-drops-i-know-you-video-yung-pinch|title=Lil Skies Drops Frenetic \"I Know You\" Video f/ Yung Pinch|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref>\n\nOn March 1, 2019, Lil Skies released his album ''Shelby'', while simultaneously debuting the music video for lead single \"I\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8500617/lil-skies-shelby-album-stream|title=Lil Skies Surprise Drops Debut Album 'Shelby' Featuring Gunna, Gucci Mane: Listen|date=March 1, 2019|last=Saponara|first=Michael|accessdate=March 5, 2019|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref> On May 21, 2019, Lil Skies dropped a video for \"Breathe\", a song from his album ''Shelby''.<ref name=\"Top40-Charts\">{{cite web |url=https://top40-charts.com/news.php?nid=146821 |title=Lil Skies Drops New Video For 'Breathe' |website=Top40-Charts.com |accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref> On July 14th, 2019, Lil Skies collaborated with rapper Machine Gun Kelly in the song \"Burning Memories\".\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn February 2019, Foose announced he's expecting his first child with his longtime girlfriend.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qJk0fvt6jBs|title=Lil Skies - Shelby (The Documentary)|first=|last=Lil Skies|date=13 March 2019|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>https://www.fuse.tv/videos/2019/05/lil-skies-mind-massage-interview</ref> In October 2019, Foose acknowledged the birth of his son in an Instagram post.<ref>https://www.pinterest.ca/pin/350858627220951247/</ref>\n\nFoose cites his own song \"[[Red Roses (song)|Red Roses]]\" as his personal favorite song, referring to the musical combination with him and Landon Cube as \"epic\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elevatormag.com/going-up-w-lil-skies/|title=Going Up w/ Lil Skies|date=6 September 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Foose uses his social media solely for promoting his music, claiming he does so in order to \"not live my life through the internet\".<ref name=\"highsnobiety.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/lil-skies-interivew/|title=Lil Skies Talks His Favorite Tattoo & Touring With Lil Uzi|date=28 December 2017|website=Highsnobiety}}</ref> He cites [[Lil Wayne]] as his biggest music inspiration.<ref name=\"highsnobiety.com\"/>\n\nFoose tries to avoid drugs as much as possible after seeing it negatively impact the lives of his old friends.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://djbooth.net/features/2018-02-21-lil-skies-scared-of-drugs|title=Lil Skies Explains Why He Avoids Lean & Xanax: \"I'm Scared, Bro\"|first=Brian \"Z\"|last=Zisook|website=DJBooth}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{main|Lil Skies discography}}\n\n* ''[[Life of a Dark Rose]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Shelby (album)|Shelby]]'' (2019)\n\n== Music videos ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%\"\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Director\n! style=\"background:#ccc;width:250px\"| Artist(s)\n|-teringlijer\n|2016\n|\"Da Sauce\"<ref>{{Citation|last=Lil Skies|title=Lil Skies \"DA SAUCE\"|date=2016-03-25}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"5\"| Nicholas Jandora\n| rowspan=\"5\" {{n/a}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\"| 2017\n|\"Some Way\"<ref>{{Citation|last=Lil Skies|title=LIL SKIES -  SOME WAY (OFFICIAL VIDEO)|date=2017-04-18}}</ref>\n|-\n|\"Rude\"\n|-\n|\"Signs of Jealousy\"\n|-\n|\"Fake\"\n|-\n|\"Red Roses\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"| Cole Bennett\n| rowspan=\"2\"| With Landon Cube\n|-\n|\"Nowadays\" \n|-\n|\"Lonely\"\n|With [[Yung Bans]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 2018\n|\"Lettuce Sandwich\"<ref>{{Citation|author=Jandora Media|title=LIL SKIES - LETTUCE SANDWICH [OFFICIAL VIDEO] (Dir. by @NicholasJandora)}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Nicholas Jandora\n| rowspan=\"1\" {{n/a}}\n|-\n|\"Lavagirl\"<ref>{{Citation|author=Jandora Media|title=SPRITE LEE - LAVAGIRL ft. LIL SKIES (Dir. by @NicholasJandora)}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"1\"| With Sprite Lee\n|-\n|\"Welcome to the Rodeo\"<ref>{{Citation|last=Cole Bennett|title=Lil Skies - Welcome To The Rodeo (Dir. by @_ColeBennett_)}}</ref>\n|Cole Bennett\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a}}\n|-\n|\"Lust\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Nicholas Jandora\n|-\u201cBreath\u201d\n|\"I Know You\"\n|With Yung Pinch\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |2019\n|\"Real Ties\"\n|Xandros\n| rowspan=\"5\" {{n/a}}\n|-\n|\"Name in the Sand\"\n|Nicholas Jandora\n|-\n|\"Going Off\"\n|Louieknows\n|-\n|\"i\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Cole Bennett\n|-\n|\"More Money More Ice\"\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Lil Skies}}\n\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Chambersburg, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American musicians]]\n[[Category:American hip hop singers]]\n[[Category:East Coast hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:Pop rappers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Lil Skies\n| background       = solo_singer<!--includes rappers-->\n| image            = Lil_Skies_2019.png\n| caption          = Lil Skies in 2018\n| birth_name       = Kimetrius Christopher Foose\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1998|8|4}}\n| birth_place      = [[Chambersburg, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Rapper|singer|songwriter}}\n| origin           = [[Waynesboro, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]|[[trap music|trap]]|[[emo rap]]||[[contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[cloud rap]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://revolt.tv/stories/2018/08/15/emo-rap-genre-artists-review-restrictions-07008fed7a|title=The claustrophobic air of emo rap will kill the genre|website=REVOLT TV}}</ref>}}\n| years_active     = 2012\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|All We Got|[[Atlantic Records]]|[[Roc Nation]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Gucci Mane]]|Landon Cube|Spirte Lee|[[Machine Gun Kelly (musician)|Machine Gun Kelly]]|[[Wiz Khalifa]]|Yung Pinch}}\n| website          = {{url|lilskiesofficial.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Kimetrius Christopher Foose''' (born August 4, 1998), known by his stage name '''Lil Skies''', is an American rapper, singer and songwriter from [[Waynesboro, Pennsylvania|Waynesboro]], [[Pennsylvania]] currently signed to All We Got Entertainment through [[Atlantic Records]]. His top three highest charting tracks on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] are \"[[I (Lil Skies song)|I]]\" (#39), \"[[Nowadays]]\" (#55), and \"[[Red Roses (song)|Red Roses]]\" (#69). His major label debut mixtape, ''[[Life of a Dark Rose]]'', was released on January 10, 2018 and peaked at #10 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart. The mixtape was certified Gold by the [[RIAA]] on November 9, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?share=19182&t=t|title=LIL SKIES - LIFE OF A DARK ROSE|website=RIAA}}</ref> He released his debut studio album, [[Shelby (album)|''Shelby'']], on March 1, 2019. On March 4, 2020, Skies released the song \"Havin My Way\", featuring [[Lil Durk]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/lil-skies-and-lil-durk-dont-miss-on-havin-my-way-new-song.1986406.html|title=Lil Skies & Lil Durk Don't Miss On \"Havin My Way\"|last=Zidel|first=Alex|date=March 4, 2020|website=[[HotNewHipHop]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nKimetrius Christopher Foose was born August 4, 1998 in [[Chambersburg, Pennsylvania]] to multiracial parents.<ref name=\"Genius\">{{cite news | last=Mench| first=Chris| title =From Waynesboro To The Web: Lil Skies Is On The Verge Of Breaking Out| newspaper =| publisher =| date =December 5, 2017 | url =https://genius.com/a/from-waynesboro-to-the-web-lil-skies-is-on-the-verge-of-breaking-out| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Stokey\">{{cite news| last =Adams| first =Joi S.| title =New TSP Artist Alert: Lil Skies Releases Video For \"Some Way\"| newspaper =| publisher =The Stokey Project| date =April 1, 2017| url =https://www.thestokeyproject.com/single-post/2017/04/01/New-TSP-Artist-Alert-Lil-Skies-Releases-Video-For-%E2%80%9CSome-Way%E2%80%9D| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Foose began writing songs at age 4. He was introduced to music by his father, Michael Burton, Jr., a fellow hip hop artist formerly known as Dark Skies, now as BurntMan, and his mother Shelby Feliciano. Foose's stage name is a play on his father's.<ref name=\"Elevator\">{{cite news | last=McCarthy| first=Liam| title =Going Up w/ Lil Skies| hnewspaper =| publisher =Elevator Magazine| date = September 5, 2017| url =http://www.elevatormag.com/going-up-w-lil-skies/| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ShipNC\">{{cite news | last=Bonura| first=Denise| title =Reaching for the stars: Lil Skies to open for Fetty Wap | newspaper =Shippensburg News Chronicle| publisher =| date =October 20, 2016 | url =http://www.shipnc.com/news/local/article_0b5d2f38-9639-11e6-9a86-bf8da9fc1cd0.html| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref> Foose and his family moved to Waynesboro, Pennsylvania when he was in third grade.<ref name=\"Stokey\"/> He started his career with help from his friend, Landon Cube and with his cousin, Marco Feliciano. When he was 11, his father was injured in a workplace chemical explosion at the Rust-Oleum plant near [[Williamsport, Maryland]]. For the meantime he would spend the summer at a relatives' house; it was at that point in time he worked in collaboration with his cousin Marco Feliciano, on his first project released on August 14, entitled, \"Birth of Skies Vol. 1\". Foose and his father would write an album the following year, ''Father-Son Talk'', discussing the recovery process.<ref name=\"RH\">{{cite news | last=Bonura| first=Denise| title =Michael Burton Jr. of Waynesboro emerges stronger after suffering third-degree burns in Rust-Oleum chemical\u2026| newspaper =The Record Herald| publisher =| date =March 28, 2014 | url =http://www.therecordherald.com/article/20140328/news/140329752| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref> Foose graduated from [[Waynesboro Area Senior High School]] in 2016<ref name=\"RH2\">{{cite news | last=| first=| title =Waynesboro Area Senior High School Class of 2016| newspaper =The Record Herald| publisher =| date =May 27, 2016| url =http://www.therecordherald.com/article/20160527/NEWS/160529855| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref> and briefly attended [[Shippensburg University of Pennsylvania]] before dropping out to focus on his rap career.<ref name=\"Genius\" />\n\n==Career==\nIn October 2016, Foose opened for [[Fetty Wap]] at Shippensburg University<ref name=\"ShipNC\"/> and later released his first mixtape, ''Alone'', in January 2017.<ref name=\"Drill\">{{cite web | last=Jackson| first=Shawn| title =Lil Skies Drops \u2018Alone\u2019 An AyRap Delicacy| website=Drill Kings| date =January 25, 2017 | url =https://www.drillking.org/lil-skies-drops-alone-an-ayrap-delicacy/| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref> In July 2017, he released two songs, \"Red Roses\" featuring Landon Cube<ref name=\"DrillRoses\">{{cite web | last=Jackson| first=Shawn| title =Lil Skies Teams Up With Landon Cube For \u2018Red Roses\u2019| website=Drill Kings| date =July 24, 2017 | url =https://www.drillking.org/lil-skies-teams-up-with-landon-cube-for-red-roses/| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref> and \"Off The Goop\" featuring Sprite Lee.<ref name=\"ElevatorSprite\">{{cite news | last=Hef| first=Hollywood| title =Lil Skies & Sprite Lee unleash catchy new jam \"Off The Goop\"| work=Elevator Magazine| date =July 17, 2017 | url =http://www.elevatormag.com/lil-skies-sprite-lee-unleash-catchy-new-jam-off-the-goop/| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref> He would later release other songs that year, including \"Rude\" and \"Signs of Jealousy.\"<ref name=\"Complex\">{{cite news | last=Ortiz| first=Edwin| title =Premiere: Lil Skies Stunts in \"Signs of Jealousy\" Video| work=Complex| date =November 14, 2017 | url =http://www.complex.com/music/2017/11/lil-skies-signs-of-jealousy-video| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFoose's repertoire of singles caught the attention of [[Atlantic Records]] who partnered with his own label, All We Got.<ref name=\"Genius\"/><ref name=\"All\">{{cite web | last=Thomas| first=Fred| title =Artist Biography by Fred Thomas| website =AllMusic| date =December 2017 | url =https://www.allmusic.com/artist/lil-skies-mn0003677493/biography| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref> He released his first major label mixtape, ''Life of a Dark Rose'', on January 10, 2018.<ref name=\"XXL\">{{cite news |last=Coleman II |first=C. Vernon |title=Lil Skies Releases \u2018Life of a Dark Rose\u2019 Mixtape |work=XXL |date =January 10, 2018 |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/new-music/2018/01/lil-skies-life-of-a-dark-rose-mixtape/ |accessdate=February 12, 2018}}</ref> The album debuted at #23<ref name=\"BillDebut\">{{cite news | last=Zellner| first=Xander| title =Lil Skies Makes Billboard Hot 100 Debut With 'Nowadays' & 'Red Roses'| work=Billboard| date =January 17, 2018 | url =https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/8094756/lil-skies-makes-billboard-hot-100-debut-with-nowadays-red-roses| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref> on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' 200 chart and went on to peak at #10.<ref name=\"Bill200\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/2018-01-27 |title=Billboard 200 - The Week of January 27, 2018 |website=Billboard |accessdate=February 12, 2018}}</ref> The songs \"Nowadays\" and \"Red Roses\" (both featuring Landon Cube) debuted on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 list at #85 and #98 respectively<ref name=\"URDebut\">{{cite news | last=Williams| first=Aaron| title =Lil Skies Is Already Chartings And Showing All The Signs Of A Star In The Making| work=Uproxx| date =January 17, 2018 | url =http://uproxx.com/hiphop/lil-skies-life-of-a-dark-horse-debut-billboard-charts/| accessdate =February 12, 2018}}</ref> and have since peaked at #55 and #69 (also respectively).<ref name=\"Bill100\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2018-01-27 |title=The Hot 100 - The Week of January 27, 2018 |website=Billboard |accessdate=February 12, 2018}}</ref> He also toured nationally with [[Lil Uzi Vert]] in 2017 and began his \"Life of a Dark Rose\" tour in 2018, but had to end the tour short due to illness.<ref name=\"XXL\"/> On May 4, 2018, the music video for \"Lust\" was released, peaking at number 87 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and being certified platinum by the RIAA.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8454621/lil-skies-lust-animated-hip-hop-videos|title=Lil Skies' 'Lust' Continues a Tradition of Animated Hip-Hop Videos: Here Are 15 of the Best|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref> On May 31, he released \"[[I Know You (Lil Skies song)|I Know You]]\" featuring Yung Pinch which peaked at 79 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and is now certified gold by RIAA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/05/lil-skies-drops-i-know-you-video-yung-pinch|title=Lil Skies Drops Frenetic \"I Know You\" Video f/ Yung Pinch|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref>\n\nOn March 1, 2019, Lil Skies released his album ''Shelby'', while simultaneously debuting the music video for lead single \"I\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8500617/lil-skies-shelby-album-stream|title=Lil Skies Surprise Drops Debut Album 'Shelby' Featuring Gunna, Gucci Mane: Listen|date=March 1, 2019|last=Saponara|first=Michael|accessdate=March 5, 2019|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref> On May 21, 2019, Lil Skies dropped a video for \"Breathe\", a song from his album ''Shelby''.<ref name=\"Top40-Charts\">{{cite web |url=https://top40-charts.com/news.php?nid=146821 |title=Lil Skies Drops New Video For 'Breathe' |website=Top40-Charts.com |accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref> On July 14th, 2019, Lil Skies collaborated with rapper Machine Gun Kelly in the song \"Burning Memories\".\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn February 2019, Foose announced he's expecting his first child with his longtime girlfriend.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qJk0fvt6jBs|title=Lil Skies - Shelby (The Documentary)|first=|last=Lil Skies|date=13 March 2019|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>https://www.fuse.tv/videos/2019/05/lil-skies-mind-massage-interview</ref> In October 2019, Foose acknowledged the birth of his son in an Instagram post.<ref>https://www.pinterest.ca/pin/350858627220951247/</ref>\n\nFoose cites his own song \"[[Red Roses (song)|Red Roses]]\" as his personal favorite song, referring to the musical combination with him and Landon Cube as \"epic\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elevatormag.com/going-up-w-lil-skies/|title=Going Up w/ Lil Skies|date=6 September 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Foose uses his social media solely for promoting his music, claiming he does so in order to \"not live my life through the internet\".<ref name=\"highsnobiety.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/lil-skies-interivew/|title=Lil Skies Talks His Favorite Tattoo & Touring With Lil Uzi|date=28 December 2017|website=Highsnobiety}}</ref> He cites [[Lil Wayne]] as his biggest music inspiration.<ref name=\"highsnobiety.com\"/>\n\nFoose tries to avoid drugs as much as possible after seeing it negatively impact the lives of his old friends.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://djbooth.net/features/2018-02-21-lil-skies-scared-of-drugs|title=Lil Skies Explains Why He Avoids Lean & Xanax: \"I'm Scared, Bro\"|first=Brian \"Z\"|last=Zisook|website=DJBooth}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{main|Lil Skies discography}}\n\n* ''[[Life of a Dark Rose]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Shelby (album)|Shelby]]'' (2019)\n\n== Music videos ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%\"\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Director\n! style=\"background:#ccc;width:250px\"| Artist(s)\n|-teringlijer\n|2016\n|\"Da Sauce\"<ref>{{Citation|last=Lil Skies|title=Lil Skies \"DA SAUCE\"|date=2016-03-25}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"5\"| Nicholas Jandora\n| rowspan=\"5\" {{n/a}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\"| 2017\n|\"Some Way\"<ref>{{Citation|last=Lil Skies|title=LIL SKIES -  SOME WAY (OFFICIAL VIDEO)|date=2017-04-18}}</ref>\n|-\n|\"Rude\"\n|-\n|\"Signs of Jealousy\"\n|-\n|\"Fake\"\n|-\n|\"Red Roses\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"| Cole Bennett\n| rowspan=\"2\"| With Landon Cube\n|-\n|\"Nowadays\" \n|-\n|\"Lonely\"\n|With [[Yung Bans]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 2018\n|\"Lettuce Sandwich\"<ref>{{Citation|author=Jandora Media|title=LIL SKIES - LETTUCE SANDWICH [OFFICIAL VIDEO] (Dir. by @NicholasJandora)}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Nicholas Jandora\n| rowspan=\"1\" {{n/a}}\n|-\n|\"Lavagirl\"<ref>{{Citation|author=Jandora Media|title=SPRITE LEE - LAVAGIRL ft. LIL SKIES (Dir. by @NicholasJandora)}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"1\"| With Sprite Lee\n|-\n|\"Welcome to the Rodeo\"<ref>{{Citation|last=Cole Bennett|title=Lil Skies - Welcome To The Rodeo (Dir. by @_ColeBennett_)}}</ref>\n|Cole Bennett\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a}}\n|-\n|\"Lust\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Nicholas Jandora\n|-\u201cBreath\u201d\n|\"I Know You\"\n|With Yung Pinch\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |2019\n|\"Real Ties\"\n|Xandros\n| rowspan=\"5\" {{n/a}}\n|-\n|\"Name in the Sand\"\n|Nicholas Jandora\n|-\n|\"Going Off\"\n|Louieknows\n|-\n|\"i\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Cole Bennett\n|-\n|\"More Money More Ice\"\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Lil Skies}}\n\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Chambersburg, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American musicians]]\n[[Category:American hip hop singers]]\n[[Category:East Coast hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:Pop rappers]]\n", "name_user": "65.111.169.4", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lil_Skies"}
{"title_page": "AGN-241751", "text_new": "{{Drugbox\n| Verifiedfields = \n| Watchedfields = \n| verifiedrevid = \n| IUPAC_name = \n| image = \n| width = \n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename = \n| pregnancy_AU = <!-- A / B1 / B2 / B3 / C / D / X -->\n| pregnancy_US = <!-- A / B / C / D / X -->\n| pregnancy_category = \n| legal_AU = <!-- Unscheduled / S2 / S3 / S4 / S5 / S6 / S7 / S8 / S9 -->\n| legal_CA = \n| legal_UK = \n| legal_US = \n| legal_status = \n| routes_of_administration = [[Oral administration|By mouth]]\n| class = [[NMDA receptor modulator]]\n\n<!--Pharmacokinetic data-->\n| bioavailability = \n| protein_bound = \n| metabolism = \n| elimination_half-life = \n| excretion = \n\n<!-- Identifiers -->\n| CAS_number_Ref = \n| CAS_number = 2254028-71-0\n| CAS_supplemental = \n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII =\n| ATC_prefix = \n| ATC_suffix = \n| ATC_supplemental = \n| PubChem = \n| IUPHAR_ligand = \n| DrugBank_Ref = \n| DrugBank = \n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = \n| ChemSpiderID = \n| KEGG = \n| ChEBI = \n| ChEMBL = \n| synonyms = \n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C= | H= | N= | O= \n| molecular_weight = \n| SMILES = \n| StdInChI_Ref = \n| StdInChI = \n| StdInChIKey_Ref = \n| StdInChIKey = \n}}\n\n'''AGN-241751''' is an [[oral administration|orally active]] [[small-molecule]] [[NMDA receptor modulator]] which is under development for the treatment of [[major depressive disorder]] (MDD).<ref name=\"AdisInsight-AGN-241751\">{{cite web|url=https://adisinsight.springer.com/drugs/800031388|title=Research programme: NMDA receptor modulators - Allergan - AdisInsight|website=adisinsight.springer.com}}</ref><ref name=\"PRNewswire2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/allergan-exercises-option-to-acquire-compound-from-aptinyx-discovery-platform-under-ongoing-research-collaboration-300652397.html|title=Allergan Exercises Option to Acquire Compound from Aptinyx Discovery Platform Under Ongoing Research Collaboration|first=Aptinyx|last=Inc.|website=www.prnewswire.com}}</ref> It was originated by [[Naurex]] and was acquired by [[Allergan]] from Aptinyx in May 2018.<ref name=\"AdisInsight-AGN-241751\" /><ref name=\"PRNewswire2018\" /> Allergan (previously Naurex) is also developing the NMDA receptor modulators [[rapastinel]] (GLYX-13; [[intravenous therapy|intravenous]]) and [[apimostinel]] (NRX-1074, AGN-241660; oral) for the treatment of MDD.<ref name=\"pmid28758582\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Vazquez GH, Camino S, Tondo L, Baldessarini RJ | title = Potential Novel Treatments for Bipolar Depression: Ketamine, Fatty Acids, Anti-inflammatory Agents, and Probiotics | journal = CNS Neurol Disord Drug Targets | volume = 16 | issue = 8 | pages = 858\u2013869 | pmid = 28758582 | doi = 10.2174/1871527316666170728165648 | url = | year = 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"AdisInsight-Rapastinel\">{{cite web|url=https://adisinsight.springer.com/drugs/800031281|title=Rapastinel - Allergan - AdisInsight|website=adisinsight.springer.com}}</ref><ref name=\"AdisInsight-Apimostinel\">{{cite web|url=https://adisinsight.springer.com/drugs/800038114|title=Apimostinel - Allergan - AdisInsight|website=adisinsight.springer.com}}</ref> Like apimostinel, AGN-241751 is intended as an oral follow-up compound to rapastinel.<ref name=\"PRNewswire2018\" /><ref name=\"PMLiVE2016\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pmlive.com/pharma_news/j_and_j_therapy_for_suicidal_depressives_a_breakthrough,_says_fda_1101990|title=J&J therapy for suicidal depressives 'a breakthrough', says FDA|date=17 August 2016|website=PMLive}}</ref> As of May 2018, the drug is in [[Phases of clinical research#Phase I|phase I]] [[clinical trial]]s.<ref name=\"AdisInsight-AGN-241751\" /><ref name=\"PRNewswire2018\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of investigational antidepressants]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://adisinsight.springer.com/drugs/800031388 AGN-241751 - AdisInsight]\n\n\n{{Ionotropic glutamate receptor modulators}}\n\n[[Category:Antidepressants]]\n[[Category:Drugs with undisclosed chemical structures]]\n[[Category:Experimental drugs]]\n[[Category:NMDA receptor modulators]]\n\n\n{{Nervous-system-drug-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Drugbox\n| Verifiedfields = \n| Watchedfields = \n| verifiedrevid = \n| IUPAC_name = \n| image = \n| width = \n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename = \n| pregnancy_AU = <!-- A / B1 / B2 / B3 / C / D / X -->\n| pregnancy_US = <!-- A / B / C / D / X -->\n| pregnancy_category = \n| legal_AU = <!-- Unscheduled / S2 / S3 / S4 / S5 / S6 / S7 / S8 / S9 -->\n| legal_CA = \n| legal_UK = \n| legal_US = \n| legal_status = \n| routes_of_administration = [[Oral administration|By mouth]]\n| class = [[NMDA receptor modulator]]\n\n<!--Pharmacokinetic data-->\n| bioavailability = \n| protein_bound = \n| metabolism = \n| elimination_half-life = \n| excretion = \n\n<!-- Identifiers -->\n| CAS_number_Ref = \n| CAS_number = 2254028-71-0\n| CAS_supplemental = \n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII = 2254028-71-0\n| ATC_prefix = \n| ATC_suffix = \n| ATC_supplemental = \n| PubChem = \n| IUPHAR_ligand = \n| DrugBank_Ref = \n| DrugBank = \n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = \n| ChemSpiderID = \n| KEGG = \n| ChEBI = \n| ChEMBL = \n| synonyms = \n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C= | H= | N= | O= \n| molecular_weight = \n| SMILES = \n| StdInChI_Ref = \n| StdInChI = \n| StdInChIKey_Ref = \n| StdInChIKey = \n}}\n\n'''AGN-241751''' is an [[oral administration|orally active]] [[small-molecule]] [[NMDA receptor modulator]] which is under development for the treatment of [[major depressive disorder]] (MDD).<ref name=\"AdisInsight-AGN-241751\">{{cite web|url=https://adisinsight.springer.com/drugs/800031388|title=Research programme: NMDA receptor modulators - Allergan - AdisInsight|website=adisinsight.springer.com}}</ref><ref name=\"PRNewswire2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/allergan-exercises-option-to-acquire-compound-from-aptinyx-discovery-platform-under-ongoing-research-collaboration-300652397.html|tit